column6: The Minyari lease areas are known to be covered by deep lateritic and transported gravel and aeolian sand cover, with a varied weathering and erosional profile. Existing regional aeromagnetics, covering the entire Minyari Dome, has highlighted a complexly folded domal structure with existing prospects located within the core region of this dome. The following work program is recommended to test the extent and significance of existing goldcopper prospects shown in Figure 5.1 plus locate new target areas suitable for follow-up work: 1. A limited program of infill RC and diamond drilling is recommended over the Minyari Prospect to test for down dip and down plunge extensions to known mineralisation. Diamond drillholes would need to be strategically located to help define stratigraphy and structure in accordance with the established Newcrest logging and database management systems.

column6: The deposit was estimated by ResEval using Inverse Distance to Power 2 (ID2) grade interpolation, constrained by resource outlines based on mineralisation envelopes prepared using a nominal 0.5/t cut-off grade and a minimum downhole length of 3m. The block dimensions used in the model were 5m NS x 10m EW x 5m vertical with subcells of 2.5m x 5m x 2.5m. The Mineral Resource is reported using a high grade cut of 20g/t was used for the Horseshoe, Cassidy and Pod zones, whereas a cut of 10g/t was used for the Hangingwall zone. The Mineral Resource was largely classified as Indicated due to the reasonable continuity of the mineralised zones and the adequate drillhole spacing. However, zones defined by wider spaced drilling (>20-30m), poor continuity and therefore lower confidence were classified as Inferred.

column6: The model includes 16 diamond holes drilled between November 2004 and January 2005 that were designed to improve definition of the likely reserve area. The model supersedes the July 2004 (RUG0604) estimate and is intended for feasibility study investigations and for generating publicly released resource/reserve statements. RUG0505 was generated from the same mineralisation wireframes and drill data used to create the April 2005 Rubicon open pit resource model (ROP0405). Model construction is consistent with the May 2004 Hornet underground model (HUG0504), with differences reflecting the specific differences in drill data and mineralisation between the deposits. RUG0505 and HUG0504 have compatible origins and orientations to allow them to be merged into a single model if required.

column6: Emperor and Shogun resource estimates are via a block models (250 m x 250 m x 0.5 m and 100 m x 100 m x 0.5 m respectively) by Robsearch at a 500 ppm U cutoff. The Emperor 1 Resource is that where all blocks had average grade greater than the cut off grade (i.e. The Emperor 2 Resource is that assigned to the full selective mining category; this being where the average grade of a block (which were very large) was under cut off, but a large proportion of the block contained material greater than cut off, which could potentially be recovered by a selective mining process. We include this material in the total resource because of the very high cut off grade of 500 ppm U used by Robsearch for the block model compared to the grade of 200 ppm U that will be used in future studies, and therefore the likelihood that this material will subsequently be classified as part of the resource. A review of the resource estimates was commenced during the year by the Brisbane based consultants Taylor Wall, as part of an authorised due diligence commissioned by Maple Minerals.

column6: FMG proposes to seek environmental approval for the Cloud Break iron ore mine (No Beneficiation) and associated infrastructure with a life of 12 years at a production rate of 10 to 30 million tonnes per annum (Mtpa) that will be exported via the Port Hedland facility. The proposed ore will not be additional to the 45 Mtpa proposed to be mined from FMGs other mines, but rather will be blended with ore produced from these mines, to allow greater flexibility in terms of product grade control and meeting customer requirements. To ensure that the cumulative impacts of the Cloud Break Project, FMGs other projects and other relevant projects in the area are well understood, cumulative impacts will be a key focus of the studies proposed in this Scoping Document. The specialist consultants for groundwater, surface water, flora and vegetation, and fauna will (have) consider(ed) cumulative impacts. The overall ecological and social impact of Cloud Break, and other mining projects in the area, in particular in the Chichester Ranges, will be assessed in the context of the principles of sustainability.

column6: The footwall domain: To the west of the calc-alkaline units, the footwall domain is characterised by mafic and ultramafic schist, dolerite and banded iron-formation. 6.0 Project Mineralisation Copper and gold at Admiral Hill display a high degree of spatial correlation, although the greater mobility of copper in the supergene zone causes some separation. As presently known, the main contribution to copper-gold mineralisation is in the supergene zone, approximately coincident with, and beneath, the andalusite-bearing schist ridge. Copper and gold occur sporadically throughout the leached, kaolinitic rock. Copper, mainly as malachite and chalcocite, is concentrated near the base of the supergene zone, but gold is more widespread, being retained in relatively refractory quartz veins.

column6: The anomalous Hannans South fault structure (NNE fault) which extends into the western and central zones from the Hannans South gold deposit has anomalous historical drilling results within close proximity and requires further exploration. The Several high strain zones within the group of thin ultramafic units are gold mineralisation targets, especially where they intersect N-S and NNE faults. Southern Geoscience Consultants conducted the initial interpretation of the phase 1 gravity survey where four possible drilling targets were delineated. The Bouguer gravity data generated displayed some subtle gravity-high features in the western section of the Group 1 package adjacent to Hannans East open pit. These have been interpreted as buried mafics within the dominant felsic volcanic/sediment package and so were considered good targets for drilling.

column6: The gossan itself is described as a goethite-magnetite-sericite quartz vein with visible galena-pyrite. Prior to the 2004-05 reporting period the focus of Thundelarras work within the reporting group tenements was evaluating the PGE potential of the Big Ben intrusion, with particular reference to chromitite reef hosted mineralisation. In excess of 1000 soil samples were collected along with rock chip sampling and prospect mapping. From this work it was concluded the chromitite horizons were of limited width and strike extent and did not warrant further assessment. During the 2004-2005 reporting period the work was focused on testing a large number of targets within the project area but failed to identify high order gossan or geochemical anomalies.

column6: A number of results between 0.77-1.87% HM were returned from the older Tertiary dune systems which overlie a predominantly limestone sequence which is currently being mined adjacent to Matildas tenements as a source of construction stone. The observations made support the previous interpretation that the dune systems present within the Matilda Minerals tenements have been reasonably systematically tested by previous air core drilling. Scope for higher grade deposits than previously identified within the tenements seems unlikely with the drill spacing over the dune systems down to 20 metres in places. It is felt that there may be an opportunity to explore the younger dune systems which do not appear to have been systematically evaluated Page 2 of 6 before. There may be potential for narrow higher grade strands buried beneath the more recent dune systems.

column6: These surfaces have subsequently been eroded by the existing drainage system, often preserving remnants of the Hamersley surfaces in mesas. 3.2 Structure The Hamersley Province has undergone a complex deformation history, with at least five deformation events (D1-D5) recognised, as follows: D 1 is indicated by layer-parallel isoclinal folds and boudinage of chert and BIF horizons. The event is widespread but does not disrupt stratigraphy significantly. The structures are interpreted to have developed because of extension and compaction within the early basin. Mount Elvire Project Annual Technical Report E47/1256 D 2 (Ophthalmia Orogeny) was the most significant event to affect the Province.

column6: Oxygen fugacity (written fO2) is not a function of the ferrous/ferric ratio but is dependent on mineral equilibria and composition. The petrologic application in geology of oxygen fugacity is measured by mineral assemblages that are referred to as oxygen buffers. In igneous rocks the important oxygen buffers in decreasing oxidation potential are: Hematite = magnetite (MH buffer) Magnetite + quartz = fayalite (FMQ buffer) There is a significant difference in oxygen fugacity between tholeiitic and Calc-alkalic magmas. Calcalkalic rocks appear to have crystallized at oxygen fugacities about 1 to 2 log units above the FMQ buffer. In contrast, tholeiitic volcanics and plutons generally crystallize below the FMQ buffer.

column6: Better knowledge of potential target characteristics is required before any further attempts to define targets directly from the existing airborne magnetic data, so no further attempts will be made to directly define targets for costly loam sampling. Ferruginous pebble lag sampling can potentially become a cost effective strategy in some areas to more cheaply evaluate areas with disturbed magnetics that may represent potential pipes (Cornelius et al, 2005). More detailed geophysical data could help with interpretation of bedrock geology and identification of potential pipe sources, but smaller, better defined target areas will need to be identified and prioritised by either geochemistry or indicator mineral sampling to justify acquisition of such data. Encouragingly, microdiamonds were located by the orientation samples in several places. However, indicator minerals to support these appear to be rare.

column6: In Snowdens opinion the Bounty project remains prospective for gold mineralisation based on (1) the projects previous gold mining history; (2) the relatively shallow nature of previous exploration drilling the strike extents to the former open pit gold deposits; and (3) many of the known gold deposits being of short strike length. Furthermore, Snowden considers the Bounty project also to be prospective for nickel sulphide mineralisation given: the projects location over a fertile ultramafic unit; (2) the paucity of recent nickel sulphide exploration; (3) the known nickel mineralisation at Bounty East prospect; and (4) the discrete nature of the known massive nickel sulphide deposits to the south of the Bounty area.

column6: Page 5 At the Yarbu North target (Figure 14), auger soil sampling defined two extensive areas of strongly anomalous gold in soils (Andromeda North and Andromeda South). Reconnaissance RAB drilling of Andromeda North returned several plus g/t gold intersections requiring follow-up RAB drilling. Widely spaced reconnaissance auger soil sampling along the inferred position of the Clampton Shear Zone (CSZ) within E77/864 (Figures 15 - 18), returned anomalous gold results up to 746 ppb, warranting follow-up infill soil sampling followed by RAB drilling. A single RAB drill traverse testing a discrete aeromagnetic high along the CSZ returned anomalous gold, suggesting that aeromagnetic highs are high priority targets for follow-up RAB drilling.  Reconnaissance RAB drilling of the Sandplain soil gold target area has established the presence of widespread anomalous to low grade gold mineralisation hosted by extensively altered Diemals Formation sediments and ultramafics.

column6: Overall 250 inloop TEM stations were recorded for a total of 19.2 line kilometres of data (16 survey lines). Resultant inloop TEM surveying has effectively sterilised the immediate Betsy Bore area of interest for the presence of significant bedrock conductors to a depth of ~200-300m. Three bedrock conductors of potential interest have been identified in the Betsy Bore area. A discrete, moderate bedrock conductor was delineated in the SE quadrant of the survey area. The associated source appears to be directly along strike from a local, possible ultramafic package (anomalous geochem) and is moderately conductive, being possibly consistent with a reasonably sulphidic unit (~850S).

column6: The eastern half of the project area occurs within a two to three kilometre thick unit of mixed felsic volcanic and volcaniclastic rocks. This unit is underlain, to the east, by a thick pile of mixed mafic and intermediate volcanic rocks and associated intrusive types. In the western portion of the project area, the Norman Well felsic unit is overlain, possibly unconformably by a predominantly sedimentary unit comprising local polymictic conglomerates and more widespread fine to medium grained clastic sediments. At Yilgangi the sediments are intruded by northerly to north westerly trending feldspar porphyries. The sedimentary unit is folded into anticlines and synclines along north-northwesterly trending axes.

column6: Drill Collar Plan (1:25,000) Figure 6: .Siberia North Regional Aeromagnetics List of Appendices Appendix 1. Logging Codes and Algorithm Appendix 2.Cross Sections & Strip Logs Appendix 3.Beneficiation (Screening) Data Appendix 4.Digital Data INCO Australia Limited Partnership, Siberia North Prospect Tenement P24/3750 2005-2007 Annual Report Page 1 of 24 . 1.0 Introduction The Siberia North Prospect is located approximately 80km north north west of Kalgoorlie. column6: 2.3 CLIMATE The Pilbara Region (where the study area occurs) is characterised by an arid climate resulting from the influence of tropical maritime and tropical continental air masses, receiving summer rainfall. Cyclones occur during this period, bringing heavy rain and causing potential destruction to inland and coastal towns. The region has an extreme temperature range, potentially rising to 50C during the summer, and dropping to around 0C in winter. At Newman, mean monthly maximum temperatures range from 39C in January to 22C in July (with corresponding monthly minimum temperatures range 25C and 7C). High summer temperatures and humidity seldom occur together, giving the Pilbara its very dry climate.

column6: The structural deformation events within the project area have been adequately described in the GSWA 1:100,000 Geological Series explanatory notes (Reganti & Chen 2002 and Wyche et al. Local Structure The prominent structural features of the district includes a large NW-SE trending basin to the south, occupied by the Marda Complex and associated granitoids, and the SSW plunging Diemals Anticline in the northwest. Both features are separated by a series of extensive northeast trending faults with an interpreted dextral movement of 18 to 25km. The areas between these faults are highly deformed and are strongly influenced by the intrusive diapiric Pigeon Rocks medium grained monzogranite and subsequent movement along the major bounding faults. Tenement Geology and Prospectivity Exploration Licence E77/1158 is dominantly underlain by felsic volcaniclastic lithologies assigned to the Marda Complex.

column6: Detrital mineralisation, comprising scree, canga and limonite-goethite, is also present within the area. Most of the scree deposits consist of younger BIF-rich colluvium except for hematite-rich scree that may exist at depth below surficial talus material over an area 2 km long by 0.6 km wide in the north-western part of the mapped area. Relatively thin and sporadic high grade and moderate phosphorus canga mineralisation flanks the bedded martite-hematite. The main low grade limonite-goethite deposit within Mindy Mindy Creek extends over an area 700m long by 400m wide. Additional closer spaced RC drilling is recommended to evaluate the grade, thickness and geological continuity of the bedded martite-goethite mineralisation with drill holes on a maximum of 50m intervals along drill lines 100m apart and large diameter diamond drilling for bulk density determination in order to define a JORC resource estimate in the measured category.

column6: Cavities are interpreted to have formed by hydrothermal karsting. Mineralisation is localised at the regional dolomite front, which is partly controlled by the transition from platform to reef carbonates. Mineralisation also shows a strong structural control, concentrated along N-trending structural corridors. Displacement is minor, and mineralisation occurs in dissolution breccias around the corridors rather than within discrete structures. At Kutarta, disseminated low-grade replacive mineralisation forms a broad zone in the hangingwall of the Cadjebut Fault, extending away from the fault as stratabound zones within favourable reefal and fenestral units.

column6: As this flow waned, lava ponded and in situ fractionation occurred where olivinedepleted lava remained within the lava lake. Under these circumstances, the crystal pile rapidly changes from olivine cumulates to pyroxene cumulates to plagioclase-pyroxene cumulates and then to non-cumulate gabbro. Nickeliferous laterite mineralisation has formed by weathering processes since the Tertiary, and is generally restricted to olivine adcumulate mesocumulate komatiites, rarely reaching ore grades over the more weather resistant orthocumulate komatiite facies rocks. The genesis of nickel laterite ores involve the removal of soluble minerals (MgO, SiO2, Ca, K and Na) and elements, resulting in preferentially concentrated resistant minerals and insoluble elements (Ni and Co) within the extremely leached ultramafic clay weathering profile aided with concentration by supergene processes. Further enrichment occurred at palaeo-water tables, particularly during the Tertiary when continental weathering of the Eastern Goldfields was on going.

column6: It appears to have been discovered in the early 1950s, as a result of ground prospecting activities of United Uranium. It is not clear whether United Uraniums airborne radiometric survey of the area contributed to the discovery. No United Uranium report has been sighted by the present author, but a Rio Tinto Report of 1955 describes the mineralisation as being on fracture surfaces within, and adjacent to, coarse fault breccia zones which have been intruded by dolerite. The identified uranium mineralisation (mostly torbernite) is hosted by both granite and dolerite, as well as by the breccia clasts which include both Proterozoic sediment and granite. The fault breccia was interpreted to be part of the Dunham Fault (Denham Fault Zone).

column6: An induced polarization survey was completed at Minnie Springs, showing an extensive elongate and strike parallel chargeability anomaly which lies along the margin of the potassic/sericite alteration zone. Low chargeability at the eastern and western extremities of the grid are probably reflecting more extensive cover over more massive chloritised granitoid around the margins of the alteration system. This broad chargeability anomaly which mirrors the regional trend of the foliation and alteration includes several NNW and NS trending peaks. The central part of the anomaly is split by a NS trending chargeability low which corresponds to the trace of the main dolerite dyke. It appears that the chargeability anomaly is related to sulphide mineralization (mainly pyrite) within the central part of the alteration zone as indicated by the amount of oxides at surface and sulphide outlined in drilling.

column6: A suite of 11 drill core rock samples was received from Mr Kym Revington (Independence Group NL, South Perth, Western Australia) on 11 July 2008. It was indicated that the samples originate from the Frankopan Prospect, an Archaean greenstone-hosted orogenic gold system located 65 km south of Newman in the Pilbara Province of Western Australia. The Frankopan Prospect is part of the Karlawinda Project, and parts of a prior geological report by Ben Grguric and Neil McNaugton for BHP Billiton were provided. That work indicated that amphibolite facies metamorphism had affected intermediate to mafic volcanic rocks, and that gold mineralisation formed in quartz-veined and biotite-pyrite altered potassic alteration zones in a brittle-ductile structural environment under retrograde greenschist facies P-T conditions. While the previous work emphasised the volcanic origin of the rock types, drilling by Independence Group indicates that the lithologies within the Frankopan Prospect appear to be well bedded and are interpreted to be dominated by volcaniclastic to epiclastic lithologies, with minor intermediate to mafic volcanics.

column6: The project area lies on a corridor of north-northwest trending mafic volcanics interspersed with narrow bands of ultramafics and volcanogenic sediments, extending in a south easterly trend through the BrightStar Alpha deposit. The area is prospective for further shear-hosted deposits, as tensional gash link structures between north-northwest trending sinistral strike parallel (D2) structures. Most mineralisation is related to these linking structures between major NNW-SSE trending shears such as the Jasper Hills Transfer. Targets include dilation positions along these shear zones especially where intrusive rocks are present, providing pressure shadow areas and dilatant zones that may trap gold. Deformation can be recognised as distinct events.

column6: Iluka has identified two potential beach barrier systems in the vicinity of the project area, with the major Ooldea barrier system being interpreted to be contained within the tenements and the Barton barrier system to lie to the north. In the first year of tenure Iluka negotiated Land and Mineral Exploration Access Agreements with the Native Title owner of the lease area and acquired publicly available radiometric and magnetic airborne survey data covering the lease area. This data was used along with the government geological mapping to identify a prospective trap site on the Ooldea barrier sequence and design a reconnaissance drill program to test it. Due to problems with obtaining a suitable drill rig to test Ilukas Vernon/Wanna project to the north, no drilling was undertaken in the first year, but is planned for the second year of tenure. The Wanna South tenements sit on the margin of the Eucla and Officer Basins (see Figure 3), where Miocene/Eocene Eucla Basin sediments onlap Permian Officer Basin sediments.

column6: This coincides with an increasing number of igneous intrusions and quartz veins towards the east. The appearance of chlorite, biotite and finally garnet has been observed from west to east within E70/2237, and is consistent with a Barrovian-type metamorphic Page 11 of 17 October 2008 sequence, where temperature increased into amphibolite facies towards the intrusions to the east. The presence of well preserved actinolite appears to be the result of retrograde metamorphism through greenschist facies. Finally, towards the eastern edge of the tenement, the quartzite adopts a gneissic texture, indicative of high grade metamorphic conditions. In general in E09/1004 the rocks have been extensively granitised and in all case both sedimentary and metamorphic textures have been obliterated by the granitisation process except in the migmatite after BIF.

column6: The Wiluna Greenstone Belt can be divided into two metamorphic domains, the Wiluna domain in the east and the Matilda domain in the west. The major north west trending Perseverance Fault (also known as the Erawalla Fault) separates the domains. The Wiluna domain is a low grade, prehnite-pumpellyite facies, metamorphic terrain comprising mafic to ultramafic lavas with intercalated sedimentary units, felsic volcanics and dolerite sills overlain by a thick pile of felsic volcanics, tuffaceous sediments, and sedimentary rocks, interrupted by extrusion of a large volume of komatiitic lava. Primary igneous textures and structures are well preserved, and deformation is predominantly brittle. The Matilda domain is a medium to high grade, greenschist to lower amphibolite facies, metamorphic terrain with predominantly ductile deformation.

column6: The current interpretation is that local sulphide-rich gossans and sulphidic cherts have originated from mineralising fluids exploiting structural pathways. The mineralising fluids are possibly derived from porphyries that intrude the sequences although surface gold values are generally low over the porphyries. Best surface results occur at the fuchsitic ultramafic-sediment contact and drilling of these anomalies has intersected in situ gold mineralisation. In 2004 the area saw a change of exploration focus with Great Australian Resources Ltd (GAR) following-up a nickel sulphide target at the Cepline Prospect originally drilled by BHP which returned assay results of up to 2.9% nickel. GAR drilled a further 5 holes (MZR01-MZR05) and intercepted minor disseminated and stringer sulphides.

column6: A kaolinitic shale containing the mineral xenotime assayed 1.55% yttrium, 0.49% phosphorous and 205ppm uranium. Although sediment-hosted, the geochemical association of these occurrences (U-REE-P) suggests a possible carbonatite source. The Cummins Range carbonatite 160 kilometres west of Billiluna displays similar anomalous geochemistry. Unconformity-related uranium occurrences are also common in the Billiluna Project area. column6: The district experiences a dry tropical climate, with a wet humid summer from October to April and a cool dry winter during May to September. Climate data for the project area is based on records from the nearest weather stations located at Kalumburu. Kalumburu experiences significantly less rainfall and slightly higher average maximum and minimum daily temperatures than Mitchell Plateau which is to this tenements west. The average annual rainfall for Kalumburu is 1217 mm and the region is subjected to heavy summer downpours from northern tropical cyclones and monsoonal activity. Maximum summer temperatures range from about 34C to 37C and the winter maximum temperature range is about 32C to 35C.

column6: The Meentheena Project region is dominated by two granitoid batholiths, the Yilgalong (within and marginal to tenure) and the Mt Edgar further to the west (Figures 1). Major structures have been recorded by regional mapping (GSWA) of which several N-S fault zones are proving of significant interest. In the East Pilbara, the N-S Meentheena fault zone is a crustal scale suture and at the prospect level it has sub-parallel components such as the Big Ridge Fault Zone that has been a major metasomatising structure. Prospecting in the area dating back to earlier this century located small amounts of alluvial gold from along/adjacent to the Yilgalong Granitoid Batholith and its contact with the mafic and sedimentary rocks of the older Archaean Warrawoona Group. Information available from archival sources shows limited work has been conducted in the area.

column6: The majority of Australian deposits are located in the Yilgarn Craton of Western Australia. However a small but significant number of deposits also occur in the Pilbara Craton and in small Archaean outliers between the Yilgarn and Pilbara Cratons. Archaean lode-gold deposits so a broad range of sizes up to 1600 t gold in the Golden Mile deposit. Most average around 2 t of gold. With improving technology and gold price the economic grade of these materials has fallen from around 40 g/t in the 1890s to around 5 g/t.

column6: Previous mining and exploration activities within the tenement were mostly focussed on areas of outcrop or shallow cover. Much of the drilling undertaken in the last 20 years, mainly in the vicinity of the historic gold workings, had only evaluated their potential to host shallow gold mineralization suitable for mining by open pit. The depth potential of many of the historic workings remains largely untested. Furthermore, much of the surface geochemistry and shallow RAB drilling completed outside of these areas during the early to mid1980s may have been ineffective due to the variable depths of alluvial cover and a lack of understanding of the regolith. 3 2.0 GEOLOGICAL SETTING 2.1 Regional Geology The Kookynie Project area is located on the MELITA 1: 100,000 geological map sheet which was extensively remapped in the 1980s and early 1990s by the Geological Survey of Western Australia (GSWA) and the National Mapping Accord program in the Eastern Goldfields.

column6: Three ultramafic units are recognised in the Emily Ann Maggie Hays area; the Western Ultramafic (WUU), the Central Ultramafic (CUU) and the Eastern Ultramafic (EUU). The CUU is the thickest and contains a succession of ultramafic differentiates with basal olivine peridotite which is a typical host for nickel sulphide mineralisation. The EUU consists of thin discontinuous volcanic flows and may also host minor nickel sulphide mineralisation. The WUU is thicker and more persistent than the EUU and typical nickel sulphide host rock types have been identified. The stratigraphic relationships between the three ultramafics are not certain because of the early thrust faulting.

column6: GEOLOGY 4.1 REGIONAL GEOLOGICAL SETTING The project area E47/1937 is located near the eastern margin of the Wyloo Dome to the immediate southeast of the Hamersley Province of Western Australia. The distribution of the regional stratigraphy around the project area is shown in Figure 3, which is based on the GSWA 1:250000 Wyloo sheet. It is characterised by a thick succession of low grade metamorphic, late Archaean to early Proterozoic rocks, known as the Mt Bruce Supergroup. The Mt Bruce supergroup is composed of volcanic rocks, banded iron formations (BIFs), carbonate and clastic rocks, which unconformably overly an Archaean granite and greenstone basement. The Mt Bruce supergroup is subdivided into four subgroups; the basal Fortescue group, which is overlain by the Hamersley Group, the Turee Creek Group and the uppermost Wyloo group.

column6: The RTP process simplifies the anomaly shape, thus improving the ability to accurately locate the causative source and more easily map the magnetic lithology (Figure 12b). First Vertical Derivative (1VD) This algorithm mathematically estimates the rate of fall off of the magnetic and or gravity field with height to remove the broad magnetic/gravity field that is created with a body. Its effect is to sharpen the edges of anomalies and to suppress broad anomalies associated with deeper sources (Figure 12d). Second Vertical Derivative (2VD) The second vertical derivative uses a mathematical algorithm to change the rate of fall of the either the magnetic or gravity field with height to remove the broad magnetic/gravity field that is created with a body. Its effect is to further sharpen the edges of anomalies and to suppress broad anomalies associated with deeper sources (Figure 12e).

column6: Cazaly Resources Ltd is the 100% owner and operator of the Project. The terrane, which is bounded to the east by the major NNW trending Mt Monger Fault, comprises three greenstone sequences, separated by low-angle D1 thrust faults, which have been folded and offset by subsequent folding and faulting. The northerly-trending and cross cutting faults provide favourable hosts for mineralisation in the area. The greenstone successions comprise basal basalts and rhyolites overlain by finegrained sedimentary rocks, which in turn are overlain by mafic and ultramafic komatiites and basaltic-felsic sequences, see Figure 2. A number of base and precious metal deposits, namely Nimbus (Zn, Ag, Pb), Boorara (Au), Golden Ridge (Au, Ni/Cu), and Blair (Ni) are located in the area.

column6: Lysander Resources Pty Ltd E37/967 Annual Technical Report 1 1.0 SUMMARY Banjawarn E37/967 is at an early stage of exploration. In Year 2, a power auger base-of-hardpan geochemistry program was completed to infill and further define the gold anomaly discovered in Year 1 exploration. The gold anomaly is located along an interpreted ultramafic contact at a distinct break between two magnetic highs.

column6: Location: The Bonnie Vale North project is located 25 kilometres southwest from Kalgoorlie and just north of the historic Bonnie Vale mining centre, in the Coolgardie Goldfield of Western Australia. Access within the tenement is provided by the unsealed but well maintained Coolgardie North road and by the gravel Jaurdi Hills Road. Geology: E15/1165 lies within the Archaean Kalgoorlie Terrane, immediately west of the regional Kunanalling Shear Zone which is associated with gold mineralisation along its 120 kilometre length. A belt of mafic and ultramafic rocks trends northeasterly through the central project area, between granites to the west and felsic volcanics to the east. A small granite intrusion in the northeast sector adjoins the Kunanalling Shear Zone.

column6: At present (2013) Aurora are actively exploring for manganese at their Capricorn Southeast Project, which lies directly north and east of Mt Augustus (refer Figure 2) and approx. Airborne Geoscience Exploration NL (AGE) 2000-2002 Airborne Geoscience Exploration NLs tenement E08/1154 formed part of their Cheyne Spring Project and overlapped a portion of Shaw Rivers current E08/2077. AGE applied for the tenement on the basis of an interpretation of regional geochemical mapping data published by the Geological Survey of Western Australia (Pye et al., 1998) The data revealed a series of strong zinc stream sediment anomalies with associated silver, cadmium and lead anomalism aligned with stratigraphy and suggesting a potential for strata-bound zinc mineralisation (Agar, 2002). These lithologies are typical of deposition in a shallow marine environment marginal to the Bangemall Basin and are very similar to the lithologies and depositional environment of the Middle Proterozoic Upper McNamara Group, Lawn Hill, Queensland, which hosts the giant Century deposit and many other zinc and lead mineral occurrences (Andrews, 1998, Broadbent et al, 1998). From the regional stream sediment geochemical data AGE identified 2 target areas within the tenement (NW target and SE target).

column6: The metamorphic and structural history of each zone also contrasts with the histories of the zones that bound it. The Gascoyne Complex was primarily shaped by four separate orogenic events: The 2005-1960 Ma Glenburgh Orogeny The 1830-1780 Ma Capricorn Orogeny The 1680-1620 Ma Mangaroon Orogeny The 1030-950 Ma Edmundian Orogeny 5 The Gascoyne Complex within E09/1053 is associated with the Mangaroon Orogeny and comprises metasedimentary rocks of the Pooranoo Metamorphics which were deposited at or before 1680Ma (Million Years). During the Mangaroon Orogeny these low to medium-grade mainly psammitic rocks were deformed and metamorphosed and intruded by extensive granites of the Durlacher Supersuite. The supersuite comprises mainly monzogranite, syenogranite and granodiorite. The Gascoyne Complex is fault-bounded to the east by younger Mesoproterozoic rocks belonging to the Edmund sedimentary basin which was affected by the Edmundian Orogeny reactivating faults and shear zones within the Gascoyne Complex as well as folding of sedimentary rocks of the Edmund Group.

column6: Geochemistry is no substitute for geology as samples can have contamination and geologic variance from features such as xenoliths, dykes, interbedding units etc. Alteration may affect chemical composition of mobile elements. No single geochemical feature can independently distinguish between all rock types at Kukerin but the units each have characteristic chemical compositions. column6: This dolerite is a major host for gold mineralisation. The structure around the mine site is dominated by late tectonic, brittle-ductile to purely brittle faults and shears. These are exposed in the Darlot pit and underground workings, and can be classified into three broad classes: Shallowly to steeply northeast and southwest dipping "thrust" faults. Large, steeply dipping east-northeast and north striking faults that cut across the reverse faults. Second order, also steeply dipping faults having a wider range of strikes, from northnortheast to east southeast, and bounded by the "thrusts".

column6: An interpreted solid geology map was constructed of the Pinjin Project area. The interpreted bedrock of P28/1061 is shown in Figure 5. column6: The Cummins Range Project (E80/4308) is located 130 kilometres southwest of Halls Creek in the East Kimberley, Western Australia. The project is on the northern margin of the Great Sandy Desert. (Figure1) E80/4308 is prospective for rare earth oxide (REO), phosphate, uranium, niobium, tantalum, yttrium and zirconium mineralisation associated with the Cummins Range Carbonatite, discovered by CRAE Pty Ltd in 1978 in the enclosed tenement E80/2232. Preferred access to the project from Halls Creek is SE for a distance of 30kms on the well maintained gravel Tanami road (turn-off located approx 20kms south of Halls Creek), to a turn-off located 1.5kms past Ruby Plains pastoral station, thence SW along station tracks for a distance of approximately 90km. Access in the wet season is limited due to concerns of potential damage to station tracks by the pastoralist, and to creek washouts in some areas.

column6: The Lagonda Prospect lies within the Independence Group Jaguar Project area north of Leonora (Fig. 1) Previous exploration beginning in 1976 had delineated the Lagonda prospect from a strong trace-element anomaly in soils, lag, rockchips and shallow regolith drilling. Subsequent historical Diamond and RC drilling intersected semi-massive zinc rich sulphides in hanging wall basalt and stringer mineralisation in adjacent rhyolite (max. Over the intervening years there has been extensive drilling on the prospect with 100+ AC holes; 30+ RC holes; and 19 diamond holes. Lagonda is modelled as a VMS hydrothermal system with similar characteristics to the Teutonic Bore, Jaguar and Bentley deposits which lie on the same mafic/rhyolite contact 5, 10 and 15 km (respectively) to the south.

column6: The most intensely sheared zones are referred to as mylonite zones, and these host much of the known gold mineralisation. Gold mineralisation is intimately associated with quartz veining and sulphides within a broader mylonite zone. It was noted during the desk-top study and field visit that N-S trending veins were generally more likely to contain gold mineralisation than other orientations. In general, the tenement is characterised by transported and in-situ regolith covering greenstones. The abundant basalt outcrop shows that these rocks were metamorphosed into amphibolite.

column6: At the Yarbu North target auger soil sampling defined two extensive areas of strongly anomalous gold in soils (Andromeda North and Andromeda South). Reconnaissance RAB drilling of Andromeda North returned several plus g/t gold intersections requiring follow-up RAB drilling. Widely spaced reconnaissance auger soil sampling along the inferred position of the Clampton Shear Zone (CSZ) within E77/864 returned anomalous gold results up to 746 ppb, warranting follow-up infill soil sampling followed by RAB drilling. A single RAB drill traverse testing a discrete aeromagnetic high along the CSZ returned anomalous gold, suggesting that aeromagnetic highs are high priority targets for follow-up RAB drilling. Exploration undertaken by Polaris during 2006 comprised infill auger soil sampling and follow-up reconnaissance RAB drilling.

column6: Exploration of the Santy Well Project area has been recorded from 1973, with EZ, NBH / Preussag Australia, Roebuck Resources / CRA, Delta Gold, West Peak Iron and Atlas Iron having explored the area over the ensuing period. column6: Historic percussion drilling intersected favourable host rocks with anomalous assays in serpentinite up to 0.43% nickel. Recent soil sampling confirmed a coherent nickel anomaly (with associated Cu and PGEs) over a strike length of at least 1.8km. Furthermore, a detailed fixed loop electromagnetic (FLEM) survey identified three semi discrete targets partly coincident with anomalous soil geochemistry. Such results have made this area highly prospective for accumulations of massive nickel-copper-PGE sulphides. An initial RC drilling programme of 4 holes for 983m was completed in late 2013 to test modelled EM plates at depth and to gain lithological information in an area relatively underexplored (see Figure 8 and 9 below).

column6: Strong oxidation occurs to 60 metres vertical depth below surface which is encouraging for development of higher grade manganese oxide from the primary carbonate mineralisation. A 16m interval at 6.3% Mn collected from ZBRC003 was dry screened (See Table 2). Results indicate that upgrade of Mn into selected size fractions by dry screening in this interval is only minimal.

column6: Wydgee is located within the Murchison Domain of the Youanmi Terrane in the Archean Yilgarn Craton of Western Australia. Alchemys Wydgee Project is located within the Murchison Domain of the Archean Yilgarn Craton of Western Australia. The Murchison Domain displays a dome and keel geometry in which narrow greenstone belts of metamorphosed mafic, ultramafic, sedimentary and volcanic rocks occur as structural troughs wedged between broad dome-shaped granitic bodies. The development of the Murchison Domain suite of rocks or stratigraphy involved at least three main geological cycles of volcanism, plutonism and sedimentation from 2820 to 2720 Ma (millions of years ago) and granitic magmatism from about 2785 to 2600 Ma. Layered mafic-ultramafic intrusive rocks constitute nearly half of the greenstone belts.

column6: 9 | P a g e In the Central zone of the Lamboo Complex, felsic volcanic rocks of the Koongie Park Formation contain VMS Zn-Pb-Cu-Ag (Au) mineralisation. The Mount Angelo Granite, which is probably petrogenetically related to these felsic volcanic rocks, hosts porphyry Cu-Mo (Ag) mineralisation. Felsic volcanic and chemical sedimentary rocks of the Biscay Formation are associated with exhalative volcanogenic Zn-Cu-Pb mineralisation in the Eastern zone. Alkaline volcanic rocks of the Butchers Gully Member in the Eastern zone are host to REE-Ta mineralisation at the Brockman prospect. Orthomagmatic Cr-Ni-V-PGE mineralisation is hosted by layered mafic-ultramafic intrusions in the Central zone and, to a lesser extent, the Western zone.

column6: Gold was analysed using 25g aqua regia digest with ICP MS finish. All results are presented in Appendix 1. Results returned anomalous gold in several samples. The geology of the Peak Hill regional area is diverse with a sequence comprising lithologies from both the Padbury and Bryah basins tightly folded along an arcuate NW to NE trending axis and juxtaposed unconformably on underlying Archean rocks of the Marymia Dome. Gold mineralisation in the region is hosted in four deposit type settings, namely: Peak Hill (includes Peak Hill-Fiveways, Jubilee, Mt Pleasant deposits) mineralisation occurs within muscovite-biotite schists of the Peak Hill Schist and associated with north-northeast trending shear zones and pyrite as the dominant sulfide.

column6: Annual Report for the Period 21 June 2009 to 20 June 2010, Panton River Project, E80/3319, Kimberley Mineral Field, Western Australia. Pancontinental Mining Corporation. Gold mineralisation in the East Kimberley is predominantly associated with the Eastern Zone of the Lamboo Complex where it is concentrated in mafic volcanic and sedimentary rocks of the Biscay Formation and the overlying Olympio Formation. The gold occurrences generally define a north-easterly trend, roughly parallel to the faulted boundary with the Central Zone. The Grants Patch Gold Mining Centre lies immediately to the north of E80/4472.

JAURDI HILLS 2015 ANNUAL TECHNICAL REPORT Report No. PML-JH-2-2015 23 5.7 Moving Loop EM Survey A high power, deep-penetrating B-field moving-loop electromagnetic (MLEM) survey was conducted at the Dunnsville Nickel Prospect by Gap Geophysics from the 14th to the 29th of November 2014 for the purpose of testing for conductivity responses indicative of nickel-sulphide mineralisation. Parmelia engaged Core Geophysics to analyse the data and model any bedrock conductors identified. The survey area was divided between the Southern and Northern high priority targets located within Prospecting Licences P16/2438, 2441, 2443 and 2657 and was mostly carried out in an in-loop configuration using a three-component Fluxgate receiver sensor, SMARTem receiver and Gap Geopak MLTX-200 transmitter operating at 100 amps (A) current and a very low base frequency of 0.25 Hertz (Hz).

column6: It is worth noting that the requirements for heritage monitors was not mentioned in this area during the heritage clearance. Numerous registered aboriginal heritage sites and exclusion zones are recorded on the southern parts of the E53/1603 & E53/1604 tenements and are largely associated with creeklines, clay pans and open washout areas. Incredulously, these areas have been the subject of extensive historical drilling for uranium (as seen in Figure 11) in the past yet are now off limits. Drilling on E53/1603 highlighted the importance of drilling traverses across suspected palaeochannel locations rather than single holes within the interpreted centre of the channels. Five holes were drilled as a West to East traverse in order to locate the centre of the palaeovalley (Figure 13).

column6: These grains include altered FeTi oxide (now represented by aggregates of leucoxene-rutile up to 0.5 mm across), altered (metamict) ?monazite in grains up to 0.6 mm across, zircon and cassiterite (each up to 0.3 mm across) and rare tourmaline (Figs 59, 60). The detrital components in the rock are partly surrounded by a subordinate fine grained recrystallised matrix, mostly composed of quartz, but also including minor sericite and considerable later-imposed hematite and goethite (Fig. b) Alteration and structure: Mild deformation and probable low grade metamorphic effects were imposed, leading to strain phenomena being observed in single quartz grains and recrystallisation of the fine grained matrix to form a locally weakly foliated and granular quartz-rich aggregae, in places with minor sericite. Original detrital FeTi oxide grains were replaced by leucoxene-rutile and there appears to have been metamictisation of former detrital ?monazite, with this phase being subsequently impregnated by hematite and goethite and in places showing the development of adjacent radial cracking (Figs 59, 60). The matrix and some of the sandstone/siltstone lithic clasts show considerable impregnation by fine grained hematite and local goethite, and the rock has been cut by several thin veins containing the same phases.

column6: The target horizon considered prospective for Broken Hill Style lead-zinc mineralisation was the Lower Proterozoic Morrissey Metamorphics. This unit consists of schist, phyllite, quartzite, micaceous quartzite and thick sequences of quartzo-feldspathic paragneiss. The Morrissey Metamorphics is a metamorphosed sequence of shale, siltstone, sandstone, greywacke, arkose and conglomerate, with extensive migmatite development. Small amphibolite and calc-silicate bodies derived from basalt and carbonate sediments respectively also occur within the sequence. The Morrissey Metamorphics were intruded by early stage gneissic granitoids during or just after peak metamorphism.

column6: The mineralisation appears to thin and dissipate into unmineralised BIF towards the east. Westward the mineralisation becomes obscured by hematite rich scree cover but then surfaces again one kilometer further west on the adjoining Hamersley Iron tenement. Southern Lens Exposure of mineralization in the southern lens is slightly better but still generally poor, again obscured in part by hematitic scree and canga. Mineralisation was mapped over an east-west strike length of about two kilometers with outcropping sections intermittently forming small prominent ridges 20 to 40 meters in thickness and dipping southward at 30-40 degrees. The southern mineralised lens may represent a northern limb of another parallel syncline, similar to the structural setting of the northern lens.

column6: These holes intersected zones of low-grade to medium-grade gold mineralisation over narrow intervals. The bulk of the known gold mineralisation at the Empire Prospect is contained within a subhorizontal layer of lateritic gravels, typically 1.5-4m thick, but locally up to 8m thick (Table 7). At lower cut-off of 0.5g/t Au, the mineralised gravels extend over an area of 600m x 75-400m. The gravels are developed over saprolite (25-70m deep) derived from bedrock basalt and dolerite. Minor gold mineralisation associated with quartz veining has been recorded in saprolite exposed on the pit floor.

column6: In summary, the Egerton transitional and fresh ore types are moderately hard, free milling ores containing a significant gravity gold component. Conventional treatment of these ore types would require crushing and grinding to nominally 75 microns and subsequent processing by gravity concentration and cyanidation (CIL). Failure to include a gravity concentration step in the process route would likely result in loss of recovery due to the presence of slow leaching coarse gold. NGM Resources Limited Stage 1 - Egerton Project Egerton Stage 1 Report Final 11 3.0 GRAVATTM AMENABILITY METALLURGICAL RESULTS The Bemex GraVatTM process incorporates gravity recovery and cyanidation of gravity tailings via vat leaching. The process is a low capital, low operating cost processing method, ideally suited to small and/or low throughput operations.

column6: A mineralised high level epithermal field (~20 km2 mapped) has been recognised in late Archaean to Fortescue Group rocks via collective geological, structural, geochemical features. This field was emplaced into part of the Warrawoona rocks, although principally into and syn the Mt Roe Basalt and lessor into the overlying Hardey Formation volcanosediments with evidence of minor reactivation well up into the Kylena Formation. Geochemically the system is variably anomalous in Au-Ag-As-Hg-Sb-W-Mo-Se and lessor Cu-Pb. Hydrothermal mineralisation in veins and breccias is dominated by silica (multiple textures including dominantly chalcedonic/opaline, micro crystalline quartz, banded colloform silica and quartz pseudomorphing platy calcite), extensive chlorite, sericite, some kaolin and carbonate alteration with significant sulphide in breccia veins (mainly pyrite, possibly arsenical pyrite). Geochemical data has been processed by Carras Mining to determine assay relationships between samples thereby allowing sample grouping (based on geochemical features) and then assessment of anomalism within those individual groups.

column6: If a large data set that covers a variety of rock types (and may include variations in sampling techniques) is not split in some manner, then very high value (or values) will obscure any more subtle responses from other areas - say a very poorly exposed system with weak leakage compared to something that is readily seen and sampled. Page 5 Mathematical techniques such as used by Carras Mining do not initially require knowledge of specific field conditions and therefore can be applied to large data sets successfully. As the targets/anomalous groups show then application of field data (or need to collect more field data) becomes more critical. This has the ability to make more subtle targets visible/discreet and therefore they can then be more effectively explored. There are some cautions with some of the smaller or apparently "unusual" groups that can appear in any set (sometimes a function of too few samples etc) and also with elements that tend to only occur at around detection levels.

column6: For massive magnetite resources, the analytic signal amplitude magnetite hot-spot plot is probably the most useful product, providing a clear picture of areas which may be direct shipping or magnetite beneficiation targets. A number of hot-spots have been picked as targets. Magnetic interpretation of possible residual hematite deposits is indirect. The hematite ores have much lower magnetization than the host BIFs but the magnetic signal from underlying unoxidized BIF overprints the magnetic low due to the hematite deposit. This produces a subtle reduction in magnetic amplitude signal instead of a clear magnetic low.

column6: NWB060123_North EWE soils.doc 6 Results: Data Manipulation and Evaluation A summary of the element statistics are presented in Table 1 (below). Raw element plots over the North EWE Lease are presented in Appendix 6. Elements were transformed after assessment to assess element correlations (Table 2), enable outliers to be identified and perform multi variant statistics (MVS). A number of elements (Ag, Cd, S, Sb, Tl & W) were excluded from MVS due to there low concentration and contrast (values below dl). A number of techniques were then used to maximize the information gained from this quality aqua regia data to identify anomalous areas including: Identifying outliers through Z scores (data transformed) Identifying outliers through key breaks in data (normal probability plot) Element ratios (Ni:Cr, Cu:Zn, Kambalda Ratio) Principal Component Analysis (PCA) Minimum Volume Ellipse algorithme (Cr-Cu-Ni).

column6: 3.9 Diamond Drilling-Cody Well (Sinclair)-E37/287 A total of 4 holes, CWD001-4 and 1 water bore CWWB001 were completed at Cody Well for a total of 1191.4m and 282 laboratory assay samples. The holes were drilled to test a surface MLEM anomaly CW#1, defined in 2004, the discovery of massive nickel sulphides within this drilling has led to the discovery of a new grass roots nickel sulphide prospect which has been named SINCLAIR. The prospect is located some 90km south of Jubilee Cosmos Nickel Mine. Past exploration has been restricted to shallow gold exploration and this discovery opens up the prospectivity of the ultramafic sequence over some 45km of strike length. Holes CWD001-3 were drilled by contractor Major Drilling via an RC precollar using a UDR650 rig with a 5.5 face sampling hammer and an NQ2 sized diamond drill core tail whilst CWD004 was drilled by contractor DWDH using a UDR1000 rig with an RC pre-collar 5.5 face sampling hammer and an NQ2 sized diamond drill core tail.

column6: The project area is located on the western edge of the Eucla Basin, a Cretaceous-Early Tertiary flat lying shelf deposit consisting predominantly of carbonate sediments overlying a basement of Precambrian igneous and metamorphic rocks. Outcrop is rare in the area and in general, there is a cover of 1-2m of calcareous soil. The detailed soil sampling programme will provide a good base for targeting potential limestone deposits in the area. Further work anticipated within the licence will be dependant on the assay results from the recent sampling programme. It is expected that this future will include a drilling programme to delineate areas of interest.

column6: The hydrothermal fluid was a H2O-CO2-S-metal bearing fluid, as supported by the nature of fluid inclusions in veins and in sealed microcracks in preserved quartz phenocrysts in wallrock, and by the sericite-carbonate-sulphide-bearing nature of the alteration assemblage. The inferred fluid composition is typical of lode-gold systems, and is inferred to have been sourced externally from the observed porphyries. The pale yellow colour of the strongly altered rocks is entirely attributable to sericite; epidote is absent from all of the alteration assemblages because it is unstable in the presence of even small amounts of CO2-bearing hydrothermal fluid. Early hematite-bearing alteration affected the porphyries (sample WHD003, 118.6m). Relict hematite occurs in ovoid to cuspate patches, now overprinted by the reduced sericite-pyrite-bearing Mason Geoscience Pty Ltd Report #3156 -4- Placer Dome Kalgoorlie Exploration mineralising assemblage.

column6: Gold mineralisation in the Meekatharra-Wydgee Greenstone Belt occurs in most of the Archean lithologies listed, often close to inferred major shear zones and appears to be largely localised in generally steeply-dipping contact zones between felsic porphyry intrusives and ultramafic and mafic volcanics/intrusives. The mineralization can be considered mesothermal, shear zone hosted in style, being associated with quartz-pyrite veins, veinsets and stockworking and variable carbonate-fuchsitesericite-biotite alteration assemblages. Clearly supergene gold mineralisation also occurs, notably in the Bluebird East and adjacent deposit areas in the Bluebird Gold Camp to the south of the Highway of the northeastern Murchison Province of the Archaean Yilgarn Craton (Figure 2). The multi-element analyses of the MAGLAG samples has effectively defined areas that require follow-up either by additional sampling, auger geochemical sampling or RAB/air core drilling. The wide spaced initial MAGLAG programme strongly supports the need for infill MAGLAG sampling on traverses 200 m apart and sample stations initially of 80 m (with the potential to close down to 40 m).

column6: The mineralised komatiites of interest to this study lie in the UG, a narrow (5 km wide in the Mt Keith-Six Mile Well area), elongate (240 km long) belt that strikes NNW, dips W and is dominantly W facing. The stratigraphy for the UG is poorly understood, comprising of volcanic and volcanoclastic rocks (acid, felsic & mafic), sedimentary rocks (pelites, shales and cherts), basalts (pillowed, tholeiitic and high Mg) and komatiite sequences (olivine ad-mesoorthocumulates and thin spinifex textured flows). The olivine adcumulates, host to Type 2 NiS mineralisation are the thicker lenticular part of the komatiitic sequences and were originally interpreted as intrusive dykes, (e.g., Burt and Sheppy, 1975; Binns et al., 1977, 1982; Groves and Keays, 1979; Marston et al., 1981), sill-like feeder chambers for the overlying spinifex-textured komatiites (Naldrett and Turner, 1977; Lesher and Groves, 1986) or ponded lava lakes (Donaldson et al., 1986). However, a more recent interpretation indicates that these komatiites formed as channelized flows (Barnes et al., 1988c; Hill et al., 1990b, 1995; Dowling and Hill, 1990). These sequences are overlain by the E-facing Jones Creek Conglomerate, the basal contact of which represents a major Archan unconformity (Durney, 1972; Marston and Travis, 1976), dated at 2.695 Ga 0.015 (Rb-Sr total rock age; Roddick et al., 1976).

column6: 10.1 Discussion92 10.2 Exploration Potential.94 10.3 Existing Resources with Potential to Expand and Convert to Mineable Reserves.103 As part of conducting due diligence on behalf of Matador and as part of a technical report, Mr. S. Capp, B.Sc., M.Aus.I.M.M., was commissioned to review the existing Herald Leviathan resource models for the Coolgardie tenements and calculations for both recent and historical data (Besserer et al., 2005, Capp, 2005a). The intent of his review was to comment on the quality of the models, calculations and existing databases from which the models were created, provide comments as to the quality of the existing resources and, where possible, classify the existing resources based upon Best Practice Guidelines for the Estimation of Mineral Resources and Mineral Reserves (CIM, 2003) and CIM Definition and Standards on Mineral Resource and Mineral Reserves (CIM, 2004). A total of 14 geographically separate deposits on the combined RJV tenements, of which 10 are within the Coolgardie tenements, were considered appropriate for the purposes of current resource estimation under NI 43-101. Drilling at the 10 Coolgardie deposits consists of approximately 237,000 m in 3,340 drillholes.

In 1993 Dominion Mining conducted a small RC drilling program at Maid Marion, with encouraging results.

column6: A few sills contain a lower olivine cumulate layer that is usually less than 25 m thick. Igneous textures are commonly well preserved within ultramafic rocks but generally are less well preserved within mafic rocks due to more extensive recrystallisation of pyroxenes by amphibole and almost complete replacement of plagioclase by a wide variety of metamorphic products. The geographic distribution of the layered sills mirrors that of the basaltic komatiite flows within the Pyradie Formation suggesting that the sills are likely to be subvolcanic feeder chambers to the overlying extrusive flows (Cowley, 1979; Bright, 1985; Meakins, 1990; Thorne and Trendall, 2001). Structuraly, deformation within the South Pilbara Basin forms a classic Type-2 fold interference pattern with older Archaean rocks exposed in the cores of domal anticlinal structures, unconformably overlain by the basal Fortescue Group, and younger Palaeoproterozoic rocks, including the economically important iron formations of the Hammersley Fm, exposed within synclinal basins. Dips in the region vary from shallow dipping (typically 15-45 degrees max) away from domal cores, to flat lying in the centre of dome and basin structures and on flanking saddle structures between adjacent domes and basins.

column6: Available evidence indicates that the sequence is broadly conformable and that it youngs consistently to the northeast, with steep dips commonly to the northeast. A static style of regional metamorphism of low greenschist facies is most common for the belt. However within the project area and along the western margin of the belt, the presence of metamorphic foliation and amphibolites indicates higher grade dynamic recrystallisation to middle-amphibolite facies. The belt is enclosed to the east, west and south by granitoids whose fabrics resemble those of the Western Gneiss Terrain. Less deformed granitoids intrude the older granitic Mt.Gibson Project - Combined Annual Report 2006 2 rocks and are believed to be responsible for the later, symmetrical, open cylindrical folding of the supracrustral rocks.

column6: 4.0 OVERVIEW OF ARCHAEAN LODE-GOLD GEOLOGY The following is adapted from Yeats and Vanderhor, 1998 and is provided by way of background for those less familiar with Archaean gold mineralisation, which is the main focus of exploration in the project area. Archaean lode-gold deposits are sited in the greenstone belts of all Archaean Shield Belts areas (Roberts 1987). In Australia, this style of mineralisation is the single most important source of gold with annual production in 1994 close to 180 t from approximately 100 mines. The majority of Australian deposits are located in the Yilgarn Craton of Western Australia. However a small but significant number of deposits also occur in the Pilbara Craton and in small Archaean outliers between the Yilgarn and Pilbara Cratons.

column6: All other blocks were estimated using the remaining samples. The global statistics of the declustered composite data and two block models differing in the treatment of high-grade outlier samples indicate that the average grade of the top-cut model is favourable (Table 7-1). Further, the grade tonnage curves of the two models showed that the high-grade restraining resulted in a very distinctive population of high-grade blocks (Figure 7-1). Thus, Golder regards the top-cut model to be the more realistic representation of the gold mineralisation of the Venus deposit based on the currently available data. The validity of the top-cut model vs a restrained model needs to be tested with further short scale drilling.

column6: Altona-Cosmopolitan: A significant number of old workings lie along the Altona trend, which strikes north-south and dips -50o to the east. It is parallel to similar structures at Cosmopolitan to the west and the Champion deposits to the northwest and all appear to be high angle reverse faults with steeply plunging ore shoots. All three deposits lie within a north to northeast trending corridor of mineralisation that defines the Kookynie mining centre and occur along structures of significant strike extent, up to 2.5km in the case of the Champion Trend. The magnetic interpretation suggests these three deposits and the Puzzle deposit may all lie within or along the contact of the same granite body although there is a significant degree of extrapolation under cover. The radiometric data indicates the granite is potassium rich and this may in part reflect an alteration phenomena (sericite/K fsp).

column6: Felsic dykes become more abundant in the south east of the tenement. The dykes generally strike north-west, sub-parallel to the dominant fabric in the area and are related to the large granodiorite intrusive to the south east. The felsic intrusives are interpreted to be synchronous with tectonism and mineralisation, as they often intrude along zones of shearing and mineralisation. The margins of the dykes are often foliated and contain low-grade mineralisation. No physical exploration was carried out over the tenement during the period of tenure.

column6: More that 60 small pegmatite dykes were mapped by Australian Anglo American over 3 square kilometres extending south from circular air-photograph anomaly thought to indicate a shallow intrusive granitoid apophysis. Surface soil and rock chip sampling was carried out without significant metal values detected and six diamond drill holes totalling 1626m to a maximum depth of 500m failed to intersect significant mineralisation or the postulated intrusive. One hole (RE5) tested the subsurface potential of an outcropping calc-silicate lens, again with no significant mineralization intersected. It can be concluded that there is no close spatial correlation between the occurrence of pegmatite bodies and granitic intrusive at Remus, but some of the larger pegmatite bodies in the southwest of the field up to 100m x 50m remain untested for geochemical characteristics and subsurface extent. column6: Coarse grained quartz and arkosic sandstones and minor conglomerate and volcanoclastic sediments of the Speewah Group were deposited to the west of the Greenvale Fault, and were in turn, unconformably overlaid by the cliff-forming King Leopold Sandstone of the basal Kimberley Group. The focus of Northern Star Resources exploration is the discovery of economic mineralization associated with the numerous layered mafic-ultramafic magmatic intrusive complexes of the East Kimberley region. Similar, economically significant intrusions include; Bushveld Complex of South Africa (PGMs, Cr), Great Dyke of Zimbabwe (PGMs, Cr), Norilsk-Talnakh region of Russia (PGMs, Ni, Cu), Stillwater Complex, Montana (Cr, PGMs), Sudbury Igneous Complex of Ontario (Ni, Cu, PGMs). The Springvale tenement covers parts of target mafic-ultramafic intrusives including the prospective peripheral zones of the large Springvale intrusion and parts of the potential feeder dyke Corridor Gabbro. In the past, reasonably intensive exploration, mainly focussed on the traditional Bushveld layered mineralization model, has resulted in identification of 17 mineral occurrences in the immediate area.

column6: Geochemical sampling was conducted in conjunction with regional geological mapping of the Beyondie Project area. The Beyondie area exhibits generally higher rock chip and MAGSTREAM values than the other areas sampled and represents a priority target areas. Mapping at Beyondie/Beyondie Bluff has confirmed the presence of grey (black) argillites, black chert and locally Cu mineralised flaggy argillites occurring stratigraphically below the Beyondie Bluff quartzite unit. column6: The Duffer Formation, which extends over 18km of strike in E45/2578, is a recognised host for base metals mineralisation for these deposits. At Lennons Find a group of stratiform bodies bearing Zn, Cu, Pb and Ag lies in sheared sericite schists, calc-silicate rocks, and metamorphosed felsic volcanic rocks of the upper part of the Duffer Formation (cyclic mafic to metavolcanic rocks) of the Warrawoona Group (GSWA Report 81, p. 66). The main mineralised zone extends 4.3km and the bodies are typically Zn, Pb and Ba rich at the top and Zn and Cu rich at the base. The Hammerhead Prospect has been reported as an Indicated Resource of 1.2 mt at 7.7% zinc, 0.43% copper, 1.94% lead and 100g/t silver (under 1988 Australian Code for Reporting Resources and Reserves). Centenary Mining subsequently defined an inferred resource of 4.2mt in extensions of Hammerhead and in other on-strike mineralised zones.

column6: The licence area is accessed by road from Perth by following the Great Northern Highway to Cue, some 650km northeast of Perth, and then following the unsealed north-westerly Cue to Beringarra Road for some 180km to a point where the road crosses the Jack Hills towards their south-western end (this road also traverses Midwests Weld Range Project just to the south of Madoonga Station). The main area of iron ore mineralisation is then reached by a track towards the northeast along the northern side of the ranges for some 15km, or to the south west along a station track along the southern side of the ranges for some 10 km (Figure 1) (total distance from Perth about 850km). Alternatively, it is possible to access the area from the Great Northern Highway at Meekatharra, some 760km from Perth, and then follow the unsealed Meekatharra to Mt Gould Homestead turning off to Beringarra Station road (50 km) then 15 km to the Jack Hills ranges (total distance from Perth about 940km). The project area is also about 420km by road to the northeast of Geraldton. The Jack Hills Range is a curvilinear southwest to northeast trending line of hills rising to over 600m above sea level, adjacent to river plains and colluvial flats at about 300m above sea level.

column6: The maximum extent Page 7 of 15 November 2006 these folds could be traced as a distinct feature was about 50 m down the hinge and along the plunge. A major F3 synform trending towards 340 and plunging 50-75 towards 350 comprises the Koolanooka Synform described by Baxter and Lipple (1979 & 1985). This synform is asymmetric due to more extensive granitoid emplacement on the eastern limb. Open to tight folds (F4) with an associated mineral cleavage (S4) in pelitic rocks and BIF, and spaced fracture cleavage in sandstone plunge 50-75 towards the southwest (220-250). These structures probably correlate with the "mild concentric buckling with moderate southwesterly plunge and an intersection lineation of spaced cleavage on bedding" recorded by Baxter and Lipple (1979).

column6: The ultramafic rocks are also less MgO-rich (as reflected in Ni content) in BMW1 compared to further west (Mt Jope Komatiite, BMW1 max 1200 ppm, to west 1400 ppm Ni: Suite 16, 950 ppm compared to 1310 ppm Ni). Mapping coupled with detailed aeromagnetic data has defined the geometry and lateral extent of the main units within the Fortescue Group around the Bellary Dome that have potential to host magmatic Ni-Cu-PGE sulphide mineralisation. These are the Mt Jope Komatiite, an olivine-rich channel-facies sequence within a komatiitic basalt flow, Suite 16, an extensive (>40 km strike) fractionated mafic/ultramafic sill with an olivine-rich ultramafic zone up to 70 m thick, and several layered gabbrodominated sills with pyroxenitic basal zones. The komatiite flow is located in the lowest part of the Pyradie Formation whereas Suite 16 transgresses the lower Formations of the Fortescue Group particularly within a high-level feeder complex within a NW-trending fracture zone. One of the gabbro/pyroxenite sills also is markedly transgressive.

column6: Nickel laterite mineralisation in Western Australia occurs in two distinct weathering mantle products. At Murrin Murrin, Eucalyptus and Bulong the ore host is smectite, while at Goongarrie, Cawse, Mt Margaret and Ravensthorpe, the ore host comprises variably siliceous goethite-kaolin-gibbsite. The model for the formation of this mineralization involves initial cataclysmic eruption of komatiite magma with very high effusion rates to allow a regional scale blanket of olivine cumulates to crystallise from a turbulently flowing sheet of lava. The flow probably had a similar scale to continental flood basalt eruptions. With time, an olivine cumulate pile built up, continually replenished by fresh lava.

Conclusion Recent detailed resource definition drilling at the companys Prairie Downs Project has allowed upgrading of Mineral resources for the Main Lode base metal mineralisation from an Inferred status to Indicated status across the entire length of the defined deposit to a vertical depth of ~120m. Wider spaced drilling completed on the East Lode and Gabbro Lode ore positions have allowed a better geological and spatial understanding of the base metal mineralisation hosted by these lodes, and by extension, demonstrated a level of geological and grade continuity sufficient to establish Inferred Mineral resources for these lodes. Future work will extend the Main Lode definition drilling a short distance to the grid west, undertake wider spaced to the east of the East Lode mineralisation and complete targeted drilling both up dip and up plunge from the currently defined limits of the Gabbro Lode mineralisation. Additionally, further drilling will be undertaken across the Project to follow up existing IP and aeromagnetic targets.

column6: 2.1 Regional Geology Yalgoo The two main greenstone sequences of the Murchison Province are both present in the Yalgoo Greenstone Belt. These are the Luke Creek Group and the Mount Farmer Group. The Luke Creek Group consists of laterally extensive (province-wide) lava plains, banded iron formations (BIF) and associated rocks. The Mount Farmer group consists of nine distinct volcanic centres and one sedimentary basin (Watkins and Hickman, 1990). The Luke Creek Group is the older of the two and includes the Murrouli Basalt, the Golconda, Gabanintha and Windaning Formations.

column6: GME Resources Ltd 5 The regional geology has been described in detail by both Williams et al (1976) and Hallberg (1985). A prcis of that information follows. Open-upright folds and extensive strike faulting dominate the Murrin-Margaret Sector, and the Laverton and Keith-Kilkenny Tectonic Zones respectively bound it to the east and west (Hallberg, p. 14). The metamorphic grade is low, with prehnite-pumpelleyite to greenschist facies mineralogy and good preservation of sedimentary and igneous textures. GME Resources Ltd 6 The Morelands Formation, a mafic-ultramafic assemblage with lesser clastic sediments and minor intrusive and extrusive felsic rocks, is the most widely distributed Archaean formation and forms the cores of several large anticlinal structures across the Edjudina map sheet (Williams et al, p.12).

column6: It contains the oldest ore deposit known in the world (a barite deposit with an age of around 3490 Ma). It also contains the oldest volcanic-hosted massive sulphide (VMS) dated at 3470 Ma, lode-gold (3420 Ma), porphyry copper-molybdenum (3320 Ma), komatiite-hosted nickel-copper (3270 Ma), iron (3200-3000 MA), layered maficintrusion-hosted nickel-copper-PGE (2920 Ma), tantalum-tin pegmatite (2880 Ma) and epithermal (2750 Ma) deposits in the world. In the West Pilbara terrain the oldest known mineralization is the Ruth Well komatiite-associated Ni-Cu deposit which is hosted by the Ruth Well Formation, the oldest rock sequence of the Roebourne Group of greenstones with an age in excess of 3270 Ma. The 3120 Ma Whundo Group hosts several VMS deposits of which the largest, the Whundo deposit, has been partially mined in the mid seventies. The most significant mineralizing event in the West Pilbara terrain was the intrusion of large layered intrusions at 2920-2900 Ma.

column6: Within the plasmic clay zone may be zones of silcrete and iron rich hardpan of silcrete thickness. Underlying the plasmic clays are saprolitic clays with occasional silcrete bands up to 5-6 metre thick. The saprolites, where not mineralised with nickel and cobalt, are usually iron rich (limonitic, haematitic and goethitic). The economic nickel\cobalt occurs within the saprolitic clay zones, generally a few metres below the boundary between the overlying plasmic clays and the underlying saprolitic clays. Much of the potential mineralisation is found within grey\brown or dark grey saprolites, but frequently high grade material is found within goethitic\haematitic saprolites or within siliceous pale grey saprolites.

The synclinorium appears to plunge south-westerly at the northeast end of the range and possibly to the northeast in the southwest of the range (Noonie Hills Sector). column6: It was concluded that the komatiitic ultramafics of the Pinnacles Project are essentially of Kambalda type. The olivine-cumulate rocks intersected in the Posex drilling and in Kanownas PND 2 and PND 3 together with PND 1, PN 176 and PN 177 are interpreted to be ortho- to mescocumulates. To the east of the main unit are several ultramafic flow units of reasonable thickness but these are less magnetic and lack both persistence and nickel sulphide discovery potential. Methodical exploration for nickel sulphide mineralisation has been carried out sporadically on the Pinnacles Project over the last 20 years. Geophysical surveys comprising ground magnetic surveys, MLEM surveys, a helicopter borne Hoistem electromagnetic survey over the whole project strike length and follow up MLEM have resulted in the identification of 18 conductive anomalies, seven of which were recommended for drilling.

column6: This programme of work proceeded over a period of some 3.5 years until late 1997 and comprised the drilling of 88 vertical aircore holes for a total of 6731 metres along east to west drill traverse lines spaced at irregular intervals. Towards the end of the programme, 5 inclined RC holes were drilled for a total of 645 metres to test further zones of elevated nickel values obtained from earlier aircore drilling but only one hole reached target because of difficulty in penetrating thick transported overburden. Owing to these drilling difficulties, continuation of this follow-up programme was abandoned and no down hole geophysical surveying was possible. Drill samples were selectively analysed for nickel, chromium, cobalt, zinc and gold at variable drill sample intervals based on geology. However, most mafic and ultramafic sequences were sampled over 2 or 1 metre intervals.
