column6: The vein swarms lie within and define a narrow, highly irregular belt or corridor, which closely follows the margins and crests of a steep-sided line of hills. For the stream samples suitable trap sites were selected and approximately 3kg of roughly sieved sample was collected for later drying and sizing by Genalysis Laboratory Services at their Perth laboratory. For the soil samples sites were selected on a rough grid pattern around a trend of quartz veining and approximately 3kg of roughly sieved sample was collected for later drying and sizing by Genalysis Laboratory Services at their Perth laboratory. The western Anomaly prospect which extends into Image Resources adjoining tenement had originally been identified in 2002 by soil sampling as a narrow, East West trending Au and As anomaly about 1.5km in length. Subsequent mapping indicated that the anomalous zone appeared to be related to swarms of small deformed quartz veins intruded into folded and cleaved shaly turbidites of the Archaean Mosquito Creek Formation.

column6: Models of the sample correlogram can be used directly in Ordinary Kriging and Indicator Kriging. The various parameters of the variogram model, such as the nugget effect and ranges in different directions, describe properties of the statistical continuity of metal grades. For example, a variogram with high nugget may indicate that there is a high level of error in the sample grades being used to construct the variograms or that there is a high degree of variability in the grade over very short distances in the mineralisation. A different range in one direction compared to another is likely to be indicating that grade is more continuous in one direction than another. 5.2 Directional Controls on Gold Mineralisation Gold and indicator variograms were calculated and modelled for Domain 2, all sub-domains combined.

column6: This report is the Annual Report for The Mount Project (Combined Report C37/2002), outlining exploration activities for the period June 22, 2006 to June 21, 2007. column6: In the area of Pincher Hill, felsic metasedimentary and volcanic rocks of the Pincher Well Complex dominate. In the far south, the geology consists of narrow bands of mafics and ultramafics, bound and intercalated by granites. Numerous gold prospects have been identified. These include the Specking Patch, Currans and Currans South within the lower mafic dominated portion of the greenstone succession, the majority of which are believed to be associated with splay structures propagating off the Youanmi Fault Zone. The Pincher Well, North Dome, Hannans, Superior and Bohemia gold prospects lie within the upper felsic volcano-sedimentary succession dominating the western portion of the Pincher Hill tenement block, and are largely associated with gossanous sulphidic BIF horizons.

column6: This describes tenements that have the potential to generate new resources and discoveries, and range from true grass roots category through to brownfields category where deposits have already been found and more of similar style may be located. There is some natural overlap of function between the two teams. The resource development team has the principal role of advancing discoveries and loosely defined resources to a point where they can be presented to the mining department for pit design and optimisation to reserve status. column6: The deposits commonly comprise varying combinations of disseminated, breccia, massive and triangular net textured mineralisation. The Flying Fox, Digger Rocks and New Morning deposits are dominantly massive sulphides (3-15% Ni) in irregular bodies located at or near the base of high MgO ultramafics. Disseminated sulphides, (1-3%Ni) up to 30 metres thick commonly overlie the massive ore. At Cosmic Boy, disseminated sulphides form the major mineralisation style. In some cases, a broad halo of disseminated cloud sulphides grading 0.4-1.0%Ni envelopes the deposit (eg Digger Rocks). As noted in the Kambalda-St Ives area minor concentrations of massive, disseminated and cloud nickel sulphide mineralisation also occurs in stratigraphic hangingwall positions, above the main basal sulphide accumulation.

column6: Good access is obtained to the entire tenement via shire roads, and the lack of remnant vegetation ensures that almost every corner of the tenement can be seen from these roads. From drilling activities in WA Kaolins nearby tenements, it is known that economic occurrences of kaolin clay only occur in relatively high topographic areas. As a result, areas of low ground were discarded as being un-prospective. Of the remaining topographic high areas, field examination found that granite outcrops were common. This indicates that the depth of weathering in this area is insufficient to host economic volumes of high brightness kaolin resources.

column6: Combined reporting has been granted for the project-C 88/2005 The Springvale tenements covers parts of the target mafic-ultramafic intrusives including the prospective peripheral zones of the large Springvale intrusion and parts of the potential feeder dyke Corridor Gabbro. In the past, reasonably intensive exploration, mainly focussed on the traditional Bushveld layered mineralization model, has resulted in identification of 17 mineral occurrences in the immediate area. Of particular significance and prospectivity are a series of shear-zone hosted sulphide gossans along the southern edge of the intrusion which may be derived from larger sulphide segregation deposits at depth. Assessment of their possible relationship to hydrothermal mineralization is also considered prospective. The Corridor Gabbro on the eastern side of the Springvale intrusion includes the discrete Emu Bore intrusion.

column6: Exploration during the nickel boom of the late 60s was constrained by the lack of airborne geophysical data at resolutions that could be used for exploration purposes. The under explored nature of the terrain is a positive feature of the region, as, although the number of discovered mineral deposits is small, there are some significant examples and it is likely that more will be discovered with persistence. The best example is the Boddington Gold Deposit which was discovered in 1980. E70/2790 has had no previous exploration of any kind carried out and is only now prospective because of interpreted aeromagnetic structures under sand plain cover which are considered worthy of geochemical and drilling follow-up. column6: Localised tight to open folding about sub-horizontal axial planes. There is a very strong structural control to the Archaean lode gold deposits of the Pilbara Craton, with most being related to regional fault systems. The gold mineralisation usually occurs at the contact between quartz vein stockworks and brittle fractured wall-rocks. Most of the ore in these deposits is finely disseminated, with gold generally being invisible to the naked eye. Much of the gold mineralization across the Pilbara Craton appears to have been syntectonic rather than post-tectonic, with late-stage high-level gold mineralization events associated with shear zones and normal faults.

column6: As deformation progressed, the strain was readily more accommodated by the imposition of major brittle-ductile structures comprising the thrust duplex. These vein stages have been numbered sequentially from Stage 1 through to Stage 4 from oldest to youngest:- 1 Stage 1 veins are uncommon, display pronounced boudinage, and are folded around early fold hinges 2 Stage 2 comprises quartz+Fe-carbonate chlorite veins which are evident in the Twilight mineralisation 3 Stage 3 quartz+carbonate veins represent volumetrically the greatest suite and are associated with mineralisation. Pyrite associated gold mineralisation occurs mostly within the silica altered vein selvedge in proximity to the quartz veins, though minor amounts of mineralisation occur within the quartz. Stage 3 veins were emplaced during progressive thrusting and veins show development of a down dip stretching lineation on their margins.

column6: Numerous minor intrusions are found within the Fortescue and Hamersley Groups, mainly mafic sills and 2 Annual Report for E47/1262 for the Period Ending 5 January 2008 dykes. column6: Low-order anomalies have been identified on the contact zone and within the granite body; these range from vacuum auger samples recovered from transported clays, to near end-ofhole RAB samples in the northern contact zone and internal to the monzogranite with values up to 200ppb Au (Figure 6). Five areas worthy of further testing have been identified. These are: Low-order gold anomalies in the northern western contact zone; Low-order anomalies internal to the granite in the northern area; The western contact zone in general where drill coverage is insufficient to test for the expected style of mineralisation; An isolated intersection in granite bedrock in the central tenement area (MUR_1, two metres at 0.52 grams per tonne Au) that has not been tested; Low-level anomalies identified by vacuum auger drilling in the central eastern area of the tenement. Palaeo-drainage from the deposits in the Yundamindera camp may partly explain this distribution; however auger anomalies are also developed over the MUR_1 intersection and possibly reflect a primary source. At present the auger sampling and drilling is too widely spaced to adequately define the extent of the anomalies.

column6: ROCK NAME : Weakly weathered, medium- to high-intensity albite-chlorite-sericite-pyrite altered diorite This sample crystallised to form the medium-grained massive dioritic igneous assemblage of plagioclase + ferromagnesians (?hornblende, biotite) + minor quartz + trace apatite + zircon. A metaluminous, possibly reduced, calc-alkaline magmatic association is inferred from the mineralogy. Subsequent invasion by a moderate volume of hydrothermal fluid caused moderately strong selective pervasive replacement by the alteration assemblage of albite + chlorite + sericite + minor quartz + ?pyrite + leucoxene. In more detail, plagioclase was completely replaced by albite + sericite, ?hornblende was replaced by chlorite + quartz, biotite was replaced by chlorite + minor leucoxene, and primary ?ilmenite also was replaced by leucoxene.

column6: Scout aircore drilling program (126 holes for 1898 metres) Previous exploration at Lake Mason has focused on the defined radiometric anomalies within the eastern extremity and northern shore of the main Lake Mason channel within E57/591, where pre-JORC target mineralisation of approximately 1M tonnes at an average grade of 170 ppm uranium for 200,430 kg U3O8 (440,936 lbs) has been defined by aircore drilling at Bolitho Bore. A tractor mounted air-core drilling rig and geologist were contracted for the duration of the program.

column6: An EM conductor located in the Yindabiddy Pool area, with a strike length of 10km, was attributed to black carbonaceous slate. The slate is pyritic in places and was correlated with the Ashburton Formation. 5) Plutonic Operations (1991): Consultant Geologist, J A Climie undertook an evaluation of the Noranda Prospect for Plutonic in 1991 to determine if the mineralisation could reflect distal or perched mineralisation related to an unconformity-type deposit at depth. column6: Bogada Bore Annual Report for 2007 Page: 9 However, none of the 2007 intersections were sufficiently high-grade to warrant immediate follow-up. The bulk of the gold at Bogada Bore is contained within the Zones 2 and 4. The Zone 4 mineralisation is largely contained within a series of west-dipping and sub-vertical strike parallel shear zones occurring close to the contact between high-Mg basalt, sediment and dolerite (Figure 10), whereas the Zone 2 mineralisation appears localised at or close to the contact between dolerite and tholeiitic basalt. The mineralisation occurs within silicified shears in association with arsenopyrite, pyrite, carbonate and quartz. The random orientation of much of the arsenopyrite indicates that the mineralisation occurred late in the history of the shear zones.

column6: Correlation between counts per second (cps) and uranium abundance depends on the age of the mineralisation and radiometric equilibrium. Uranium carried in solution and precipitated in recent surface deposits is normally classed as young and is not likely to be in radiogenic equilibrium with its daughter products that produce the measured radiometric signature. This means that the cps rate measured from a young uranium deposit might be significantly lower than expected and not reflect the true abundance of uranium at the site being measured. Holes were drilled using a reverse circulation air-core system and were logged using a down hole spectrometer. Water samples were collected.

column6: As and Sb show continuously anomalous trends along the major faults. Both As and Sb are soluble in oxidised fluids, but precipitate as the fluids become more reduced. In contrast to the linear As, Sb anomalies, Mo and W form discrete anomalous zones that are proximal to fertile intrusive complexes. The Sickle footprint is well defined by the pathfinder zonation of As and Sb in the hangingwall to the deposit, with Mo and W as proximal indicatiors, potentially related to the unusual intrusive granitoid and porphyry suites (and by inference gold mineralisation) identified in drilling and in the open pit mapping. The hyperspectral sampling supports this zonation, however is complicated by the extremely acid compositions related to the alteration adjacent to the massive sulphide lenses and pyrite stockwork systems

column6: Location: The Kennedy Range project comprises Exploration License 09/1340. The tenement is located approximately 200km north-east of Carnarvon, in the Gascoyne region of Western Australia. Geology: The exploration licence lies within the Gascoyne Complex which is a deformed and high-grade metamorphic core zone of the early Proterozoic Capricorn Orogen that lies between the Archaean Pilbara and Yilgam Blocks. At the regional scale, the tenement lies largely within a complex zone of migmatites and schists surrounded by granitoids (Figure 2 adapted from Williams et al., 1983). Work done: Exploration work during the reporting period comprised data compilation & evaluation, field assessment, rock-chip sampling and a two ground radiometric surveys over the Red Hill Well and Munaballya Well South areas.

column6: The High Grade blocks were classified as Measured due to the large number of composites, which produced a high quality estimate and a low coefficient of variance. After classifying according to these criteria, isolated groups of Measured were downgraded to Indicated after the block model was visually inspected. The central area of the deposit has been drilled to a 75m by 75m spacing, and blocks in this area were estimated to a sufficient confidence level for optimisation, detailed mine planning and scheduling but not selective mining at elevated cutoffs. These blocks were classified as Measured and Indicated Resources. Inferred blocks are limited in number and form on the edge of the resource.

column6: The area was previously explored by BHP in the late 80s as part of a large regional greenfields exploration program of widely spaced BLEG stream sediment sampling with followup detailed grid soil sampling in a search for shear hosted gold mineralisation within higher grade metamorphic rocks. The exploration was successful with the discovery, in 1987, of the Gault Deposit (230 000ozs) at Tampia Hill some 20km to the south of E70/2806. The discovery of the Gault deposit and some other anomalous gold prospects close at hand, focused BHPs attention into a very small area around the deposit resulting in 2 little attention being paid to the wider region. BHP withdrew from the area as a result of problems gaining access to the properties containing the resource. The northern part of the tenement was explored briefly by CRA in 1989-1991 but difficulties with access to freehold land hastened their departure without a serious exploration effort made.

column6: Nor is there any mention of what type of sample was used in the metallurgical testwork, so the accuracy of the data can not be verified. There was an arsenic assaying campaign undertaken on exploration drilling completed by Delta, this was confined to 15 RC holes. From the results of the drilling program, a correlation between gold grade and arsenic grade was made, and formula worked out for assignation of arsenic values across the entire deposit, based on a line of best fit scatter plot of the arsenic and gold grades. There is a fundamental problem with this statistical analysis in that it did not document if the 15 RC holes were drilled at regular intervals over the strike length of the Mayday mineralisation which gives rise to the question as to whether the RC holes were representative of the deposit. The conclusions from the statistical analysis were that the Mayday North deposit is of high arsenic content and generally unsuitable for treatment at Kanowna Belle Processing Plant.

column6: Ecotec (WA) Pty Ltd (Ecotec) was engaged by Barminco to conduct a threatened fauna assessment of the project area and determine the potential for impact on any threatened fauna that may be present. Temporary water bodies in the region provide food and breeding sites for a range of water birds at various times of the year. Four species of migratory waders, specially protected under agreements with China and Japan, may visit these lakes following significant rainfall events. These birds are the Wood Sandpiper (Tringa glareola), the Common Sandpiper (Tringa nebularia), the Sharp-tailed Sandpiper (Calidris acuminata) and the Red-necked Stint (Calidris ruficollis), all of which travel between Australia and Asia annually. The Bush Stone-curlew (Burhinus grallarius), although not recorded in the DEC database, is a likely inhabitant of the area.

column6: Elsewhere within the Project area gold is associated with weak quartz stockworks within coarser sediments, sandstone, arkoses and quartz-rich grits which are also aligned along south-westerly trends and in massive quartz veins. column6: 4.0 REGIONAL GEOLOGY AND MINERALISATION There is no exposed geology in the Top Well project area but the regional setting consists of Archaean granite domes containing remnant greenstone xenoliths and roof pendants, representing attenuating remnants of a northern extension of the east limb of the Mt Ida greenstone belt. Dead Camel Hill to the south of the project area is one such remnant which was explored by CRA Exploration in 1995, who reported narrow komatiitic units within the belt. At present encouraging nickel and copper intersections are being reported by Western Areas NL at their Mt Alexander Joint Venture area situated some 25 km to the southwest. E29/547 Top Well Page 3 Annual Report - 1 June 2007 to 31 May 2008 5.0 EXPLORATION HISTORY E29/547 Top Well was acquired to enclose a cluster of aeromagnetic highs in the northern part of the tenement which suggested the possibility of concealed fragmentary greenstone sequences north of the Dead Camel Hill greenstone belt previously explored by CRAE. Exploration during 2006-2007 consequently focussed on the northern part of E29/547.

column6: ii) Lesser thin argillaceous layers were deposited as fine detrital clay, accompanied by minor chemical sedimentary carbonate and minor clastic quartz grains. The sediments most likely were deposited under low-energy conditions in a marine environment. In response to low-grade regional metamorphism in the greenschist facies, the sediments recrystallised to form new assemblages of carbonate (dolomite), sericite, leucoxene and opaques (?pyrite). The carbonate sedimentary layers generated fine-grained microgranular mosaics of carbonate (dolomite) + minor sericite + trace leucoxene + opaques (?pyrite), and the argillite layers recrystallised to form a foliated mat of sericite + minor carbonate (dolomite). Note that the foliation in the meta-argillite layers is oriented at an angle to sedimentary layering: if the foliation lies in the axial plane of a regional fold (a reasonable assumption), then this sample is located toward the fold hinge.

The tenement package covers a total of 275 blocks and is prospective for iron ore, base metals (-gold, silver), nickel copper (-PGE) sulphides and tantalum - tin (-emerald). The companys exploration focus will be on iron ore with a view to locating and developing deposits that can contribute to meeting the unprecedented demand for iron ore in recent years. Some tenements are prospective for base metals (nickel, copper, zinc, lead) and Baracus Pty Ltd will also assess the potential for these metals as part of their exploration program.

column6: A general characteristic of these structures is that the margins of granitoid complexes commonly have steeply dipping foliations that are parallel to, and pass across, contacts with greenstones. These greenstones have also undergone strong metamorphism. At places a thick sequence of volcanic and sedimentary rocks of the 2775- 2630Ma Fortescue Group, the oldest group of the Hamersley Basin, unconformably overlies the older dome and keel pattern of the East Pilbara The East Pilbara is host to a variety of mineralisation styles formed in a range of different tectonic environments including sediment-hosted massive sulphides, volcanic-hosted massive sulphides, vein and hydrothermal base metal and shear zone-hosted gold and other precious metals mineralisation. Local Geology The geology of the project area comprises a typical East Pilbara greenstonegranite terrane. The tenement lies within the Marble Bar Greenstone Belt which is wrapped around several granitoid complexes.

column6: South from 45,500mN composites included significant intervals in the 0.5 - 0.8% HM range, particularly in the upper zone, while further north intervals below 0.8% HM were obviously much less common. We also compared average block model grades for 500m N-S strips (using a nominal cutoff grade of 0.5% HM to extract mineralised blocks) with 3rd order polynomial trend lines fitted to the composite grades (Figure 4.23). This showed that north from 45,500mN, average composite grades rose substantially in relation to resource grade trends in the model. These comparisons indicated that there was a significant selection bias between the 2003-2004 assemblage results and the 2008 results. This means that relative to the rest of the model, the portion north of 45,500mN, and particularly north of about 47,000mN, will have: Elevated assemblage values for zircon due to higher composite grades.

column6: The Kurnalpi Terrane includes c. 2.72 2.70 Ga mafic volcanic rocks, calc-alkaline complexes, feldspathic sedimentary rocks, and mafic intrusive rocks, and c. 2.69 2.68 Ga bimodal rhyolitebasalt and felsic calc-alkaline complexes that extend along a linear belt at the western edge of the terrane. The tenement mostly comprises post-regional folding biotite-bearing monzogranite and minor greenstones of the Jubilee Domain (Cassidy et al, 2006), which is interpreted, on the basis of geochemistry, as representing an extensional arc basin with an assemblage of tholeiitekomatiite felsic volcanic rocks. Work done: Image Resources undertook a first-pass, broad-spaced soil sampling program over a number of targets across the tenement generated from examination of detailed aeromagnetic data. In the surrendered part of the tenement 206 (-2 mm-mesh) soil samples were taken at 200 m intervals along lines 500 m and 1000 m apart and analysed for Au, As, Cu, Cr, Co, Mn, Ni, Pb, Pt and Zn. Results: In the surrendered part of the tenement, soil sampling over the magnetic target in the extreme southeastern corner produced scattered assays of between 1.2 and 3.8 ppb Au, and a few assays of 5.6 and 8.9 ppb Au, against background values of 4-6 ppb Au.

column6: Conclusions: Drilling completed at the Minnie Springs prospect has successfully confirmed the grade and thickness of Mo Cu W mineralisation as intersected within prior RC drilling plus increasing the continuity of mineralisation over a 700m strike length with widths and depths respectively of up to 100m and 150m. Mineralisation is dominantly vein related and interpreted as having formed during late stage magmatic hydrothermal activity associated with syntectonic emplacement of a multi-phased intrusive. Regional exploration completed outside of the Minnie Springs prospect area has successfully delineated new areas of elevated Mo W Sn and W respectively at the Hidden Valley and Nina prospects. Newly identified areas provide testament that regional parts of the project contain considerable potential for additional granite hosted discoveries such as that identified at the Minnie Springs deposit to be uncovered. Additionally, newly re-viewed/acquired radiometric data has demonstrated that new style of mineralisation, such as primary and/or secondary style uranium may also be present throughout the project area.

column6: Air core and rotary air blast drilling of 171 holes, and assay of drilling data. Results: Resource modelling shows that there are a total of 78,000 ounces of Au in the inferred category in the Palomino area, geophysical interpretation generated structural targets in unexplored areas sitting under regolith cover. Most of the targets areas were drill tested and a few low grade zones of gold anomalism were identified. Known gold anomalous areas of interest were retained and the less prospective areas were dropped as part of the 50% compulsory reduction at the third year since the tenement was granted prior to 10 February 2006. Conclusions: Areas identified with weak gold anomalies and other untested structural targets require infill and reconnaissance drilling.

column6: The Lode is a brittle fault breccia on the footwall contact of the chert. Seven RC holes have tested this fault to a vertical depth of about 50 metres returning best intersections of 3 metres at 4.35 g/t gold and 2 metres at 2.96 - 29 - g/t gold. There is insufficient drilling to determine the plunge of any ore shoots and the auriferous system can be considered open at depth and along strike to the north and south. At Denise-Mary, shallow pits and bulldozer scrapes have exposed a felsic porphyry intrusion hosting quartz-limonite veins. Relatively poor exposure in the Denise-Mary area allows for a bigger auriferous system than presently recognised.

column6: The gold mineralisation is associated several ENE trending quartz veined zones with an overall strike length of approximately five kilometres. The host structures are steeply south dipping (80 o ) or sub vertical and are brittle in nature. They are sub-parallel to the stratigraphy and most mineralisation occurs in doleritic host rocks. Magnetic differentiated dolerites are a common host rock for gold mineralisation as is common in much of the Eastern Goldfields. Furthermore there is some association between higher grades and better vein development within the more magnetic parts of the dolerites, as well as the development of veins and associated magnetite destruction.

column6: The broad spaced drilling that has been completed in the project area was successful in identifying anomalous gold associated with granite under cover. Geophysics, combined with broad spaced drill testing, would also assist in defining any potential palaeo drainage channels in the project area.

column6: This hole was planned to intersect the mineralised quartz vein in order to further characterise mineralisation and to gain some geotechnical knowledge of the ore zone. The geology in the drill hole was dominated by a mafic rock that varied in grain size from fine to coarse (basalt to gabbro). There was an interpreted mineralised zone from 46.8m ? 53.25m that showed brecciation of the host rock, epidote and potassic rich (pink) feldspar alteration and quartz veining that ranged in scale from mm to cm wide. There was up to 2% sulphides present in the host pyrite and chalcopyrite.

column6: Aircore drilling tested structural corridors, stress anomalies and magnetic targets and it successfully outlined a new supergene zone of gold anomalism at Bobs Bore South. column6: It is recommended by the author that no further drilling be resumed at the Finch Prospect, as no mineralisation was found in the 2 diamond holes drilled this year. The Assay results received for the diamond holes 08FCHDD001 and 08FCHDD002 showed negligible CU/Pb/Zn, which indicates that there is no potential mineralisation in the zone drilled. The negligible results could also indicate that only the upper part of the Upper Shale and Upper Hanging Wall were drilled of the Nifty Stratigraphic column, and these units have never supported any mineralisation, and had been classified as barren units. To obtain a bigger picture of the underground geology, and if indeed the geology is part of the Nifty Syncline, more stratigraphic units of the Nifty Stratigraphic column need to be intersected, especially the upper, middle and lower carbonate units, as it is these units which host the sulphide mineralisation found in the Nifty deposit. The author sees the Finch Prospect as low priority for drilling, but if any drilling was to be undertaken at Finch, possibly one deep (600-800m) diamond hole, situated within the outlined, strata bound Cu zone of >500ppm and another deep diamond hole situated north of the projected Nifty Syncline axis, adjacent to the interpreted WMC Fault and at an Easting of 361500E and Northing between 7590500N and 7591000N.

column6: The grid straddles a portion of the eastern margin of the sediment and tuff filled Yindarlgooda Rift where it is in contact with a suite of carbonated mafic and ultramafic volcanic rocks referred to by CRAE as the Jubilee Mafic-Ultramafic Complex, a zone considered prospective for base and precious metal mineralization. CRAE noted the presence of weak Au, Cu and Zn anomalism along the margin of the rift (within E28/1134) and recommended follow-up RAB drilling although this did not take place. CRAE did not comment on the nickel values, perhaps because their principal focus was on Au and Cu-Zn mineralization. Anomalous Ni-Cr-Co values reflecting underlying ultramafic lithologies were in fact identified in five consecutive lines representing a strike length of approximately 1,600m (peak value 0.34% Ni). In each case the anomalous values lie at the north eastern limit of the lines, indicating that the ultramafic hosts continue to the east and outside of the gridded area.

column6: The scarp is deeply dissected by numerous spectacular gorges. To the north the Fortescue River Valley is bordered by low-lying gently rounded hills forming the Chichester Range. These hills are mantled by thick colluvial deposits with minor outcropping bedrock which rises to a maximum height of 30 to 40 metres. The Chichester Range forms a low ridgeline where erosion has cut through the basal Marra Mamba Iron Formation to the underlying shales of the Roy Hill Shale Member. Beyond these lateral valleys the land continues to rise gently over outcrops of mafic igneous and sedimentary rocks of the Fortescue Group.

column6: In general, the areas (mesas) of Robe Pisolite were found to be surrounded by outcrops of Proterozoic basement (basalt and sometimes sediment) implying the pisolite outcrops were simply weathered remnants of channel iron accumulations that had probably been eroded and washed further down the drainage. In both the Panhandle and Airport prospects assays from the pisolites that were sampled reported Fe assays in excess of 50% but with relatively high silica (4 to 10%) and Al2O3 (4 to 8%) reflecting the weathered nature of the samples. At the Panhandle prospect, coarse grain sizes and wood fragments in excess of 1 cm in size were common, suggesting proximity to the basal section of the channel. This could also be inferred from the outcrop mapping which found significant amounts of basaltic outcrop nearby negating the possibility of a large channel being present. At the Airport prospect, the pisolite outcrops were found along the margins of Bellary Creek which is thought to have eroded away the channel iron mineralization leaving only remnants as evidence of prior channel iron accumulations.

column6: The tenements are 100% owned and cover much of the SW margin of the Earaheedy Basin (Figure 1), including most of the known zones of carbonate-hosted Zinc-Lead (Zn-Pb) mineralisation. A broadly spaced drilling programme was conducted that defined several prospects containing oxidised and primary Zn-Pb (Zn dominant) mineralisation. These prospects are mostly stratabound and primarily confined to the Sweetwaters Well Member (also known as the Navajoh Dolomite sub-unit) of the Yelma Formation. This member forms a single laterally continuous dolomite horizon over 30 km strike. In some drillhole intersections, the entire width of the sub-unit (up to 100 m) is mineralised (cited from Companys website).

column6: Uranium mineralisation is found as secondary mineralisation in the form of oxidised minerals like carnotite. This mineralisation is mostly developed in areas of granite/greenstone bedrock. Mineralisation is exclusively comprised of the soluble hydrated potassium-uranium vanadate mineral carnotite, K2(UO2)2(VO4)2.3H2O. The carnotite post-dates the calcrete, commonly occurring as void linings in porcellanous varieties, as seams and disseminations in earthy varieties, as fracture paint on slip planes around the margin of mounds, and as grain coatings within the clay-sand host beneath the calcrete. There are major three types of calcrete related uranium deposits: a) Trunk Valley Calcretes: Mineralisation occurs in channels, platforms and chemical deltas and is usually concentrated near the water table.

The Kimberley Basin forms the platform cover to the craton and consists of a succession of sedimentary and volcanics rocks of Proterozoic age. The terrain formed by the Kimberley Basin is rugged and is essentially a broad plateau dissected by strong jointing that has resulted in a well developed drainage system. The oldest unit that crops out within the licence is the Warton Sandstone which is a white quartz sandstone heavily dissected by jointing. The Carson Volcanics conformably underly the Warton Sandstone and may be exposed within the licence.

column6: Hunter (1993) correlated a number of the Coolgardie units with volcano-stratigraphy at Ora Banda, Kalgoorlie and Kambalda. Standing (2001) makes the case that much of the volcano-stratigraphy in the Kalgoorlie Terrane and particularly in the Coolgardie area, although well mapped, has been supported by only very limited petrography, whole-rock and trace element geochemical data and even less rare earth element data. Therefore, Standing (2001) questions many of the traditional correlations that have been made for the different regions but in particular for the Coolgardie area. Standing (2001) suggests that the stratigraphy at Coolgardie is unique relative to that in the centre of the Kalgoorlie Terrane or at Ora Banda, and as such he recommends the use of a local stratigraphic nomenclature (Figure 4). Figure 4 Stratigraphic column of the Coolgardie District Greenstone Belt Standing (2001), on the basis of pointed petrographic and geochemical work in conjunction with remapping, suggests that a new nomenclature, based in part upon the unit names proposed by Coolgardie Gold N.L.

column6: The forward modelling technique used assumes the perceived geological source, calculates the theoretical magnetic field surrounding this source and compares it with the observed magnetic field. The shape, location and properties of the modelled source can then be adjusted to improve the fit between the theoretical and observed fields. Potential field modelling of this sort does not generate a unique solution. Parameters such as susceptibility, depth to top and thickness can be combined in many ways (within certain ranges) to produce very similar theoretical responses. The Glen Ayle Project areas are located within the Capricorn Orogenic Zone which lies between the Pilbara and Yilgarn Cratons.

column6: Some 86 reverse circulation (RC) drillholes have been completed by FerrAus intersecting the targeted Marra Mamba Iron Formation. Further RC drilling and DD drilling is planned to establish and refine mineralisation extents, further understand metallurgical characteristics and obtain insitu bulk density data. A nominal 55% iron (Fe) lower cutoff was broadly used in conjunction with geological features (stratigraphy and structure) to outline the extent of iron mineralisation including in the hardcap horizon. Statistical analyses on samples and 2m composites were completed. Variography and search neighbourhood analysis were also conducted as input into grade estimation.

column6: Weak anomalism in soils and its orientation suggest that this may be the case. In addition Cu, Au, Pb, Zn mineralisation is present and is most well developed in quartz veins and shears trending approximately 120. In the Glenburgh area in general the presence of anomalous gold mineralisation Glenburgh area was indicated by the detection of gold (up to 15 parts per billion over a regional background of <0.5ppb) using bulk leach extractable gold (BLEG) analytical techniques on stream sediment samples. The anomalism is associated with east-north-easterly trending late to syntectonic shearing of the Archaean metamorphic rocks. The known primary Au mineralisation at Victoria Bore is hosted within Archaean rocks and is characterised by chlorite, sulphide alteration overprinting biotite, garnet and silica flooding and quartz feldspar veins within a package dominated by mafic to felsic gneiss and migmatite.

column6: Regional tectonism and granite emplacement has resulted in strong tilting of the greenstonemetasediment sequence, typically dipping 60-80 to the north with subsequent thrust faulting, and possible sequence repetition locally. Outcrop exposure is generally very good with the exception of heavy, tallus scree slopes on some of the prominent chert ridges and the 8-Mile Creek drainage system that run through the project area. Regional metamorphism in the project area is generally low grade, except adjacent to granitiod complexes, where it has reached lower amphibolite facies. The Muccan Granitiod Complex (MGC) is situated to the immediate north of the project area and is expressed as a flat expanse of well-drained spinifex plain. The southern contact of this complex is intrusive into a greenstone and meta-sediment sequence of rocks and appears knife-like.

column6: This included non-ground disturbance work such as desktop research, reconnaissance mapping and Aboriginal Heritage surveys. To the anniversary date of this report, work has focussed on exploration and resource drilling (RC predominantly) of the discovered iron mineralisation that is present within these tenements. Drilling results to date have been encouraging, with the publically released Solomon Resource Upgrade reported during this reporting period (JORC compliant, 8 November 2008). column6: Overlying the Antrim Plateau Volcanics is the Goose Hole Group, consisting successively of the massive micritic Headleys Limestone with minor stromatolitic units, particularly near the base, the Nelson Shale which consists of carbonatic siltstones and mudstones and thin gypsum beds at numerous intervals, the richly fossiliferous Linnekar Limestone and the Panton Formation, consisting of siltstone and lesser arkosic sandstones and mudstones and minor limestones. These units form the Negri Subgroup of the Goose Hole Group and are overlain by the Elder Subgroup that consists of the Eaglehawk Sandstone, a marginal marine to fluvial fine feldspathic sandstone and minor siltstone, overlain by the Overland Sandstone, a clayey lithic arkose unit. Michigan Copper Belt USA-The Model The Michigan Copper belt on the Keweenaw Peninsula, Michigan USA has produced approximately 7 million tonnes of copper and significant silver. Copper mineralization consists of structurally controlled native copper dominated mineralization in fragmented and amygdaloidal basaltic rocks and interbedded coarse grained sediments of the Portage Lake Volcanics and stratabound mineralization in the overlying Nonesuch Shale. Mineralisation is a basin wide phenomenon, with the major deposits of native copper hosted by the Portage Lake Volcanics in the Calumet area (over 5 million tonnes Cu metal) separated by about 100 km from the lesser native copper deposits and the sulphidic White Pine deposit (approx 1.9 million tonnes Cu metal) in the Nonesuch Shale at White Pine.

column6: Finegrained alteration biotite (dark brown) forms small flakes and aggregates in the altered groundmass. x20, Image P5183150) This view illustrates the partly preserved primary holocrystalline igneous, rather than fragmental, texture of groundmass in the andesite porphyry. Small oriented lath shapes of primary groundmass plagioclase (oriented NE-SW) are distinguishable, despite moderately strong replacement by albite (white to grey) and biotite (reddish brown), sericite (small bright pale yellow flakes), and opaques (right, magnetite). x20, Image P5183149) This view captures a relict primary apatite microphenocryst (grey, centre) which has suffered sculpting of crystal margins where small alteration biotite flakes (reddish brown) have formed. The presence of apatite microphenocrysts in the andesite porphyry suggests that the andesitic magma was geochemically evolved (ie elevated abundances of large-ion lithophile elements including K, P, and probably Ce).

column6: A review of the Melville Deposit was completed by Orelogy, Perth in April-May 2008 to ascertain the current value of the resource. Pit Optimisation utilising Whittle 4D and a Sensitivity Analysis utilising current mining and process costs, recoveries and various gold prices were completed. A number of optimisation runs were examined with the base case results showing that even though the gold price has increased from US$500/oz to US$650/oz (since the last optimisation in 2005), the mining and processing costs impact significantly on the value of the project. Including inferred ore had a minimal effect on the size and value of the optimal pit. Sensitivity analysis was undertaken by increasing process and mining costs, reducing process recovery by 10%, increasing gold price, reducing overall slopes and including inferred ore.

column6: Summary and Recommendations The Tardie area, near Yalgoo, is considered to have excellent potential for economic uranium mineralisation. Past exploration reports of work completed within the region should be reviewed and data compiled in the context of aerial photography and satellite imagery to determine the next step. The immediate target is for uraniferous calcretes within ELA 590/1211, but a strategy should also be developed for the acquisition of additional tenements for similar styles of mineralization as well as for hard rock sources of the above secondary mineralisation. IBML is not aware of any uranium mineralisation within Skytones Gifford Creek or Yinnietharra tenements. Furthermore, the field visit did not identify any significant potential host sequences.

column6: Workings and prospecting pits are scarce to non-existent in outcropping areas throughout the district, suggesting either that the sequences are not well mineralized or that historical activity was limited by the remoteness and lack of surface water supplies. A major mineralized shear zone, the Aldiss Fault, is situated to the northwest of the project area, some 5km east of the inferred Terrane boundary interpreted to coincide with the Roe Hills Fault. The Aldiss Fault is not particularly conspicuous as an aeromagnetic 8 C21/2007 Woodline Project Annual Report for the period 1 Jan to 31 Dec 2008 CR34109 Newmont Exploration Pty Ltd feature, but it is the controlling structure for the significant Karonie-French Kiss line of prospects, which are currently under advanced exploration by Integra Mining Ltd. It is not clear where (or if) the Aldiss and Roe Hills Faults continue to the south beyond a zone of disruption along the Binneringie Dyke and the main depositional centre of the Proterozoic Woodline Formation. Although the Project area is on the margins of the Yilgarn Craton and in some cases close to major granite intrusive bodies, metamorphic grade in the greenstone belts is markedly low to the north and west of the Cundeelee Fault, being predominantly lower greenschist facies.

column6: The tenements are accessible via tracks running north from the Trans Access road. The tenement consists of low to weakly undulating plains with low laterite capped rises frequently representing inverted paleochannels running in an east?west orientation in the southeastern portion of the tenement (Plan 2). The vegetation is predominantly salt bush flats with native willow following drainage lines. Black heart sheoaks and minor sandalwood and dogwood are present on the lateritic rises.

column6: Overall, most geochronological data point to an age of circa 1800 Ma for late (D5) gold in the Tanami region. The age of the apparently earlier gold event (D1 or D3 at The Granites) is not constrained (Huston et al., in prep). Bagas and Huston (2005) suggest that gold mineralisation at the Kookaburra and Sandpiper deposits in the Bald Hill area occurred during c.1790Ma during the Tanami Orogeny and broadly coeval with the emplacement of granites. They suggest that the gold-bearing quartz veins were emplaced throughout the northeast-southwest compressional DB2 folding and faulting episode as saddle reefs and along bedding contacts, on the subvertical fold axes, and as cross-cutting subhorizontal sheets. It has been suggested that gold mineralisation at Coyote occurred during a DB3 east-west compression, when DB2 faults and folds were opened up to allow fluid ponding and mineralisation (L. Bagas, WAGS, Pers.

column6: Two orthocumulate cooling units were intersected on the section; in hole 1010 the upper unit was intersected from 125m to 183m and the lower unit from 493m to 507m. column6: This district lies directly to the north of the Robinson Ranges. With exploration and subsequent mining, the Peak Hill district Page 10 of 30 March 2009 became the second most profitable Proterozoic region (behind the Telfer Dome) for gold production in Western Australia. Mines such as Peak Hill, Horseshoe Lights, Fortnum and Plutonic were all discovered during the early 1980s early 1990s. Much of the tenure in the area was very tightly held during this period by precious metals and base metal exploration and mining companies. This situation continues today, although most gold mines (beside Plutonic) have been exhausted and current tenement holders are largely new floats (with large Exploration Lease holdings) with interests in the remnant gold and base metal resources in the region.

column6: A summary of exploration is presented on Figure 2. Gold mineralisation within the Davyhurst area is associated with two spatially separate and geologically distinct zones, designated by Hellsten et al (1990) as the Western and Eastern Sequences. Mineralisation within the Eastern Sequence is typically marked by sulphide mineralisation associated with thin (<30 metre thick), broadly folded biotite- actinolite-carbonate schist hosted within massive amphibolite. Deposits of this nature include Great Ophir, Lights of Israel and Golden Eagle (Norum, 2007a). Mineralisation within the Western Sequence is hosted by highly strained units of foliated to banded dolerite and chlorite-tremolite schists within competent blocks of basalt.

column6: Interpretation : This sample formed as framework-supported arenaceous sediment composed of crystal particles (quartz = plagioclase > zircon) and minor fine argillaceous matrix. Partial recrystallisation in response to a regional metamorphic event in the middle greenschist facies generated the new foliated assemblage of quartz + plagioclase + biotite + minor muscovite + zoisite. Small zircon crystals are of clastic origin, and therefore may have been derived from diverse sources of possibly different ages. This is supported by the different forms of the two zircons observed. They appear to be of suitable size for SHRIMP U-Pb dating.

column6: Mineralisation ranges from shallow to deep, mainly located in the Newman Member of the Marra Mamba Iron Formation, over a strike length of 7 km. Lesser amounts of bedded mineralisation occur in the Macleod Member and the West Angela Member of the Wittenoom Formation. Deposits of secondary surficial canga, pisolite and limonite occur overlying, and adjacent to the bedded mineralisation. Significant detrital deposits of limonite, red ochre detritals and mature detritals occur in close proximity to the bedded deposits. column6: Mapping by company geologists in 2005 show that the mafic-ultramafic rocks in most cases appear to be juxtaposed against sedimentary rock units by faults. It is proposed here that there may be only one sedimentary formation within the Mosquito Creek Belt, and that the thin units of mafic-ultramafic rocks may represent fault-imbricated slices of a volcanic basin floor upon which the sedimentary rock were deposited (probably as a prograding submarine fan system). This mapping also supports an interpretation that the Mosquito Creek Formation can be subdivided into two parts; the upper part characterised by interlayered shale, siltstone and thinly bedded, fine to mediumgrained sandstone, and the lower part containing a greater abundance of 1 to 10 mthick coarse-grained sandstone and conglomerate beds (interlayered with shale, siltstone and fine to medium-grained sandstone).

column6: It appears that Colreavy East may have anomalous nickel coincident with the copper, but unfortunately the most relevant nickel data is not in the digital database. There is a puzzling weak linear nickel anomaly running eastwards for two kilometres from Colreavy. The western half of this runs perpendicular to topographic contours, and could be downhill dispersion, but the eastern half is parallel to the contours. This feature is largely coincident with the east-west copper anomaly described above, and thus weakens my argument that the copper pattern is a dispersion trail. An east-west dyke is another possible source for this feature (but the aeromags show no obvious dyke-like feature, and only a weak east-west linear discontinuity).

column6: However, further bulk sample testwork of alluvial material is required to verify this result to support a mining proposal. Past workers have also identified the potential for fault hosted copper-gold mineralisation around Mt Elephant in the southern part of the Project area. Best results from orientation geochemical surveys include assays of up to 10.24% Cu and 2.17 g/t Au at the Elephant North prospect. Three holes drilled into the Mt Elephant prospect yielded a best intersection of 5m @ 1.3% Cu within a gossan also containing trace amounts of gold, silver and cobalt. Gossans similar to Mt Elephant would also have the potential to host a small resource of DSO hematite ore. Further exploration for channel iron deposits and DSO hematite within the minor Ashburton Formation BIFs is considered warranted, along with further review of the copper-gold potential of the Project area.

column6: The Brockman Iron Formation consists of BIF, shale and chert and is divided into the Dales Gorge, Mt Whaleback, Joffre, and Yandicoogina Shale Members. The Dales Gorge Member is host to the majority of iron ore mineralisation, with Tom Price, Paraburdoo, Whaleback, and Rhodes Ridge being typical examples. During the Tertiary a series of erosion-deposition-hardpanisation (ferricrete) cycles resulted in the three regionally extensive Hamersley surfaces which can contain economic Detrital Iron Mineralisation. These surfaces have subsequently been eroded by the existing drainage system, often preserving remnants of the Hamersley surfaces in mesas. 3.2 Structure The Hamersley Province has undergone a complex deformation history, with at least five deformation events (D1-D5) recognised, as follows: D1 is indicated by layer-parallel isoclinal folds and boudinage of chert and BIF horizons.

column6: Gold mineralisation at Pilgangoora has been reported associated with quartz veins and blows as well as altered talc-carbonate-chlorite ultramafics along shear contacts. Gold has also been found associated with banded iron formation as evidenced at Mt York. Within the Pilgangoora Greenstone Belt gold mineralisation is largely restricted to fault and shear zones in Warrawoona Group rocks. The exploration lease at Pilgangoora covers a sequence of altered maficultramafic volcanics from the Warrawoona Group with several major shears present in the area. Members of this group exposed along the eastern margin of the tenement represent the best targets for continued exploration at Pilgangoora.

column6: The leaseholder spent half a day compiling the map as described which includes the time spent having the photos processed and printed at a Photo Lab. 2008/2009 ANNUAL REPORT FOR P/L 77/3643 Off-Field Work Data Compilation (Drill Hole Cross-Sections) The leaseholder spent seven days compiling a total of 36 new drill hole cross-sectional views of 36 old RAB holes which have been drilled on this ground since 1990. To create all these new A4 size cross-sections, each page was first overprinted with some basic data including a 'Legend' to provide essential information relating to the tenement including the tenement number, the name of the prospect, the date it was drawn and the adopted scale. column6: Mylonitic fabrics in pegmatite dykes that surround the 2838 6 Ma Bonney Downs Granite (which in part abuts the southern margin of the Mosquito Creek Belt), suggests that regional shearing continued in this part of the Pilbara Craton until at least ca 2840 Ma. Mapping by company geologists in 2005 show that the mafic-ultramafic rocks in most cases appear to be juxtaposed against sedimentary rock units by faults. It is proposed here that there may be only one sedimentary formation within the Mosquito Creek Belt, and that the thin units of mafic-ultramafic rocks may represent fault-imbricated slices of a volcanic basin floor upon which the sedimentary rock were deposited (probably as a prograding submarine fan system). This mapping also supports an interpretation that the Mosquito Creek Formation can be subdivided into two parts; the upper part characterised by interlayered shale, siltstone and thinly bedded, fine to mediumgrained sandstone, and the lower part containing a greater abundance of 1 to 10 mthick coarse-grained sandstone and conglomerate beds (interlayered with shale, siltstone and fine to medium-grained sandstone). Gold mineralisation in the Mosquito Creek Belt exhibits strong structural and lithological controls, from the regional scale through to the outcrop scale.

column6: PNC located 3 deposits within Eocene sediments where the uranium mineralization occurs immediately below the redox boundary at the base of weathering. Mineralisation in the deposits at Ambassador, Shogun and Emperor is tabular and flat lying and occurs between 20 and 50m below surface. They suggest that uranium of hexavalent form is adsorbed into the organic matter presumably in the reducing environment. The deposit was reported to contain 10.8Mt at an average grade of 0.12% U at a cut off grade of 300ppm U for a uranium content of 13,000 tonnes.

column6: Both peloids and ooliths range in size from 1 to 2 mm, and are enclosed in a matrix of chert. The textures indicate a shallow, probably turbulent, marine environment. Banded iron-formation (PEf(i) is not common, but is significant as an indicator of an increase in water depth. It occurs intermittently near the top of the formation, notably west of Mount Royal and on the south side of the Lee Steere Range. Alternate iron-rich and cherty mesobands range in thickness from 10 to 100 m. The chert mesobands are white, iron-free and internally massive.

column6: 1239m of shallow (maximum depth 93m) slimline RC drilling (in 16 angle holes) was completed in the Halleys area. All drill samples were bagged and 259 5m composite samples were collected for assay. Significant intervals were split sampled through a riffle splitter, totalling 314 samples were sent for assay. All samples were sent to Genalysis and analysed for Au, Ag, As, Co, Cr, Cu, Fe, Mn, Ni, P, Pb, Pt, Pd, S, Ti, V, Zn, using a combination of 4 acid digest ICP_OES for the multi-elements and 25g/t fire-assay MS for precious metals. QA/QC was completed at the rate of 1 standard per hundred samples and 4 replicate samples per 100; Therefore 5% of the samples were QA/QC.

column6: Major folding can be found in the extreme eastern portion of the project area and is dominated by a fold hinge made up of basalt and ultramafics hosting chemical sediments ranging from BIF to sulphidic chert. These chemical sediments are the same units that host the gold occurrences of Dolly Pot, Dugite and Python to the east of E77/1427. Minor gold is also associated with the BIF and sulphidic chert units within E77/1427, either within the major eastern fold hinge or where units are truncated by local faults and shears. The licence lies along strike from the Marda gold trend. This trend has been partially tested by RAB drilling on the eastern and western sides of E77/1427 however 3km of the trend remains undrilled due to low soil sample results (Plan 1, Appendix 1).

column6: The visit was made in conjunction with visits to adjacent project areas. The tenement E45/2779 overlies Native Claims of the Njamal and Warran Claimant Groups. Atlas Iron Pty Ltd had talks and negotiations with the Claimant Group represented by the Yamatji Aboriginal Corporation to reach an agreement enabling future exploration and mining over the tenement. Tenement E45/2779 is located in the East Pilbara Granite-Greenstone Terrane which comprises the eastern portion of the Archaean Pilbara Craton. The East Pilbara GraniteGreenstone Terrane comprises groups volcanic and sedimentary rocks (greenstones) deposited between c. 3515 and 3240 Ma, in addition to younger, dominantly sedimentary, greenstone successions, and numerous suites of granitoid rocks varying in composition from trondhjemite through to monzogranite that were emplaced between c. 3576 and 2850 Ma.

column6: An additional deposit at King Brown was also discovered during this period. In the north Sons of Gwalia carried out laterite and BLEG sampling on a broad scale grid with soil sampling, shallow RAB and RC follow-up within the Johnston Range Sheet (1987-1989). Lateritic gold resources were defined at four separate locations (Zone B, C, F & G) and an oxide resource was delineated at the saprolitic Johnston Range deposit (renamed the Gwendolyn Mine). On the Johnston Range Sheet between 1988-1990 Samantha Gold NL, later Broken Hill Metals NL, conducted regional soil sampling at 80m intervals along 800 and 400m spaced lines. A large number of anomalous gold areas were delineated but few were followed-up by infill soil sampling and RAB drilling, the company eventually withdrew from the region.

column6: At Marda Central the cross cutting faults associated with the gold mineralization brecciate and deform the BIF/Chert horizons. Mineralisation trends WNW and is generally confined to boudinaged segments of the upper & lower sub units of the Marda BIF. Gold mineralisation has a tendency to be small tonnage, low to medium grade with anomalous gold restricted to the BIF horizon within the immediate area surrounding the intersection of the associated fault. Quartz veining and/or schistose Evanston Project-Annual Technical Report-P77/3413-2009 ultramafics with high gold values often defined the fault planes. At Golden Orb, in poorly exposed cherts and to a lesser extent BIF, a supergene enriched zone enhanced by a narrow SE plunging ore shoot contains both stratabound and structurally controlled gold mineralisation.

column6: The entire Balagundi project area has undergone thorough assessment and follow-up of targets by previous explorers, which dominantly included CRAE, Geopeko, Acacia Resources Ltd and Lachlan Resources NL. Arsenicantimony and base metal anomalies were identified in surface and auger soil sampling, but drilling of these anomalies, IP anomalies and interpreted EM conductors failed to return any significant geochemical assay results. Lachlan Resources NL tested the interpreted extension of the rhyolite and syn-volcanic fault hosts to the Nimbus mineralization (Gilmore 1999) through the means of EM surveys and drilling. Geochemical assay results indicated weak base metal anomalism associated with the partly oxidised transition zone. No further targets could be identified.

column6: A gold in mag lag anomaly (Bibra Prospect) on E52/1711, approx 4 km north of the Frankopan Prospect, was generated and identified and subsequently aircore drill tested. Gold mineralisation was confirmed in bedrock at Bibra that extends over 3.5 km in length and up to 1 km wide as defined by a 200 ppb max Au down-hole contour. There is a strong correlation between gold, tungsten and tellurium. Conclusions: The gold mineralisation remains open in all directions at Bibra and follow-up drilling is warranted to further define and extend the mineralisation along strike and define the down dip orientation and extent. RC and/or diamond drilling may be warranted to test the best of the aircore drilling, in conjunction with an aeromagnetic interpretation.

column6: Those sites that were identified as having inhibiting botanical or environmental factors were: Mt Ida 01. Although not likely to be impacted, with reasonable care, the DEC permanent plot for the Yilgarn Ranges Survey site Mt Ida 04 was located close to the collar location. column6: The greenstone succession comprises tholeitic volcanic rocks, fine grained clastic sediments, felsic volcanics and mafic intrusions lying between Big Bell, Tuckanarra and Meekatharra. The principal structural unit is the NE trending Abernethy Shear Zone that occurs immediately west of the licence area. At the Hope River Prospect gold mineralization has been defined by drilling. The mineralization occurs along the N-S trending Hope River Shear Zone which splays off the regional Abernethy Shear Zone. Gold mineralization is associated with quartz dolerite intrusions and requires further follow up.

column6: Since the release of the report and recommendations of the EPA as per Bulletin 1291, on the 30th June 2008, the DEWHA indicated that they had reservations about the conclusions reached by the EPA regarding the level of predicted impact on the Western Ringtail Possum, Baudin's Black- Cockatoo and Carnaby's Black-Cockatoo. Following an exchange of information, DEWHA provided a letter to Grange indicating that the only outstanding issue was the potential impacts that the Southdown project could have on the Carnaby s Black Cockatoo. DEWHA s threshold of significant impact for these species has noticeably decreased hence increasing the requirements for mitigation, including offsets. This was demonstrated by the substantial offsets required of the Fiona Stanley Hospital Project (FSHP) for the impact to 25ha of Carnaby s Black Cockatoo foraging habitat in the southern metropolitan region as per the EPBC Act approval in July 2008 (EPBC 2008/3970). The Southdown Joint Venture engaged Strategen Environmental Consultants Pty Ltd (Straegen) to undertake an evaluation of the relative extent and significance of impacts to Carnaby s Black Cockatoo as a result of the proposed Southdown Project.

column6: There are two important structural trends in the Sorby area; a major set of northeast to north-northeast faults and an antithetic set of northwest-trending faults. Smaller deposit scale faults follow the NW trends and are interpreted to control mineralisation within several pods, but are not well mapped within the deposits. The relationship of stratigraphy and structure to mineralisation is described further in section 1.9. The Sorby Hills mineralisation is typically silver and lead-rich with moderate to high pyrite (FeS2) content and generally low amounts of sphalerite (ZnS). Galena (PbS) occurs as massive to semi massive crystalline lenses often found in the more argillaceous units, and as coarse to fine disseminations or as open-space fill in fractures, breccias and vugs.

column6: Soil structure can be influenced by the particle size distribution, chemical composition and organic matter content of a soil, and is often affected by root growth, vehicle compaction, and with respect to reconstructed soil profiles, the methods of soil handling and deposition. When a soil material is disturbed, the breakdown of aggregates into primary particles can lead to structural decline (Needham et al., 1998). This can result in hard-setting and crusting at the soil surface and a massive soil structure at depth, potentially reducing the ability of seeds to germinate, roots to penetrate the soil matrix and water to infiltrate to the root zone. Observations and assessment of soil structure were made at all surface soil survey sites within the three Project areas. Soil structure in profiles at Mertondale and Raeside was similar, with well structured, friable topsoil of moderate to strong aggregates in the upper surface horizons, occasionally increasing in consistence with depth above the hardpan.

column6: An idealised komatiite sheet flow stratigraphic succession in descending order is: gabbro (non cumulate) pyroxenite pyroxene cumulates (including harrisite) OOC olivine orthocumulate, thin heterogeneous units oMC olivine mesocumulate, upper oAC olivine adcumulate, thick uniform sheet flow sequence oMC basal olivine mesocumulate oOC basal thin unit olivine orthocumulate Textural interpretations are an important exploration guide, and are a prime basis for drillhole siting. Strong drilling results can be rapidly encountered through effective field interpretation of komatiite facies based on textural observations. Some sulphide mineralisation has been noted in the fresh ultramafics, but there does not appear to be any correlation between the sulphides and elevated nickel mineralisation within the ultramafics at depth. Drill log data indicates that the ultramafics consist of orthocumulate serpentinites and olivinites, while the granites contain lenses of felsic porphyry, and fine-grained diorites and rhyolites. The mafics consist of gabbro, dolerite and basalt.

column6: The mapping defines a series of fine to coarse grained mafics on the western flank, which underlie the first major breakaway clearly visible to the left upon driving around the western side of Redcliffe. Mapping includes the breakaway structures and has shown significant parallel swarms of weakly sulphidic vertical quartz veining within weathered indurated well-sheared mafics. This mafic series continues across approximately to the 330 trending midline of the Redcliffe pit where it is agreed that mineralisation propagates partly within sulphidic quartz veins and partly within strongly sheared sericitised mafic-felsic contact schist and mylonite. Surface geology in outcrop reveals that the same mafic lithologies may appear as fresh to partly weathered in some locations and also moderately to strongly weathered in the greater of proportions as purple-brown-tan-crme patchings, such that comparison for detail and similarity is difficult to impossible. Another observation is that a 060-240 degree trend band of thicker and more clustered quartz veins occurs, the veins are still parallel and sub parallel to geology and striking at ~330-150, but have perhaps been injected as a distinct band across the geology during expansion and extension.

column6: Central Workings: Au is carried predominantly within the pegmatitic units that run sub vertical through the sediment stack. The sediments have been tilted more steeply in this region due to the pressure caused by late forming granite to the west and south of the mineralization. As the mineralization is related to the pegmatites, the area of potential is limited as these geological units are discontinuous and small in this region, with the current resource within a 50m strike length. Southern Workings: The Au occurrence runs within 100m of the late forming south west granitic pluton that has distorted and silicified the adjacent sedimentary pile. Au mineralization is located within the sedimentary structure as well as quartz replacement veins and on occasions pegmatitic type units.

Highly weathered ferruginous bedrock containing carbonate nodules or mottled weathered granites are present.

column6: Away from Magnum, nine RC holes were completed over 8 BHP EM targets. Best result was 5m @ 5,300ppm Pb from GAN5, located 7km southeast of Magnum but this anomaly was not repeatable. Initial diamond drilling failed to intersect any significant mineralisation but downhole EM identified three major north south trending conductive zones to provide specific drill targets. Follow-up drilling intersected significant gold mineralisation up to 15m @ 14.07g/t Au from 464m. The results from the drilling were interpreted as two subparallel mineralised zones hosted by a northeast dipping gabbroic sill, intruded into the Coolbro Sandstone package.

column6: The initial program consisted of an orientation survey of 150 samples to test the suitability of MMI soil sampling for the regolith and rock types encountered in the project area. The survey was carried out over areas of known and unknown nickel mineralisation. The initial orientation survey successfully identified nickel anomalism with up to 26 time background nickel over the White Cliff Gossan area. The second soil sampling program consisted of 1350 samples collected over an area of 250 square kilometres. The program tested 22 magnetic and structural targets and successfully identified nickel anomalism up to 12 time background over aero magnetic lineaments in the central western (Westside anomaly) section of the lease and again further south (South Western anomaly) (Figure 5).

column6: High-grade tantalum mineralisation (>420g/t) is generally confined to the Albite zone within the deposit. The Spodumene and K-Feldspar Zones generally have poor tantalum-tin grades usually below open-cut cutoff grades. A key to the accurate definition of high grade and low grade lithium ores in the pit is a highly credible calculation of the BAD Factor. The antipathetic relationship between lithium and soda in high grade ore types has long been recognized in the mill and the pit. As the most influential component of the BAD Factor calculation is the Na2O content, improving the relationship in the resource model between the lithium and soda estimations will improve the quality of the BAD calculation.

column6: In addition, nickel-copper, platinum group element (PGE) and vanadium-titanium mineralisation is present in several mafic-ultramafic intrusions. Epigenetic gold (with or without copper) is almost invariable associated with shearing and faulting in a variety of geological settings. Favourable settings including sheared units associated with the Regal Thrust (including Weerianna), splay faulting associated with the Sholl Shear Zone and around the edges of several mafic/ultramafic intrusions. At the Weerianna Mining Centre gold mineralisation is associated with quartz veining within chlorite-serpentine schists which have undergone variable degrees of silicification and carbonate alteration. Sulphides including pyrite, arsenopyrite and chalcopyrite are sometimes present in substantial amounts.

column6: Archaean-aged granitoids either occupy or underlie much of the area. Within the project area, especially at Unaly Hill, major quartz bodies are intrusive along the Youanmi Shear. column6: Visual checks of the flight paths were conducted in Mapinfo. Each RepTEM Survey Profile and Conductivity line flown was then overlayed on top of the flight path, (Figure 1). Using both the graphic data produced for each line it was possible to work out where there were areas of low conductivity and areas of high conductivity, which would in turn indicate where there are areas of basement highs and basement lows, or channel-hosted saline aquifers. 12 Where there are Basement highs are generally associated with relatively low conductivity, while basement lows (channels) are usually associated with relatively high levels of conductivity. We used a progressive approach to divide the information up; these were basement, channel and a transition layer from channel to basement, (Figure 3).

column6: A zone of stringer mineralisation comprising disseminations, bands or veins occurs parallel to cleavage and envelopes the main sulphide zone. The alteration at the Horseshoe Lights deposit consists of chloritisation, C124_2009_2010A.docx 4 silicification and seritisation. The main ore zone has a broad zone of quartz kaolinite alteration which is interpreted to be due to argillic hydrothermal alteration, weathering or a combination of both. Earlier work on the origin of the Horseshoe Lights deposit proposed a VHMS origin for the orebody but destruction of primary textures by hydrothermal alteration and structural deformation make this interpretation difficult to confirm. 4.0 PREVIOUS EXPLORATION The Horseshoe Lights deposit was discovered in 1946 and mined by a prospector who worked the area for two years producing 27.82 kg of gold from shafts sunk over the iron rich discovery gossan.

column6: By definition the stringer zone has less than 20% total sulphides, and this boundary can be rather subjective. However based on sulphur assays, there is a clear cut-off at 25 to 30% S with the massive sulphides. In practice this zone begins where the decrease in sulphide mineralisation allows host volcanic lithologies to be recognised. The lower contact is arbitrary, to some degree pyrite +/- chalcopyrite +/- sphalerite mineralisation is present throughout the volcanic sequence but demarcation of the stringer zone is dependent on the loggers perception of economic mineralisation. The very low strain and metamorphic grade has resulted in excellent preservation of the sulphide textures from which textural zonation has been recognized (Vearncombe, 1995).

column6: The rock contains numerous pseudomorphs of leucoxene and red oxide that appear to have represented mafic and/or titaniferous lithic and mineral fragments. Lithic fragments are commonly randomly orientated, but a significant number show a parallelism with strands of leucoxene and red oxide. The lithic fragments are probably devitrified volcanic glass and this rock is interpreted to be a volcaniclastic, possibly tuffaceous, sediment. 12 Geological mapping 2009 R.Jeffery 8.0 GEOCHRONOLOGY and GEOLOGICAL HISTORY The use of sensitive high-resolution ion microprobe (SHRIMP) U-Pb zircon geochronology by the GSWA has constrained the timing of magmatism and sedimentary deposition, and has been instrumental in stratigraphic correlations in the Pilbara Archaean rocks. The West Pilbara is composed largely of Archaean crust that is 250 million years younger than the oldest crust exposed in the East Pilbara.

column6: North Pool Project - E53/977 Relinquishment Report Emergent Resources Limited Period 3 March 2009 to 2 March 2010 7 5.0 LOCAL GEOLOGY The local regolith, geology and structure is detailed in the previous annual report (period ending 2nd March 2008), and is summarised here (Figure 3). Generally outcrop is sparse in the Project area. The main prospect area is represented by low rubbly outcrop comprising ferruginous/gossanous argillite, in a topographic low between. Local silicification of the acid volcanics is considered to be a weathering product, rather than alteration resulting from mineralising fluid however this has yet to be confirmed. The localised ferruginisation of the argillite and development of jaspery outcrops can be associated with anomalous Zn values, and appear to be structurally rather than stratigraphically controlled.

column6: The Yerrida Group was divided into 2 units, the lowermost Juderina Formation made up of the Finlayson Member sandstone, siltstone and dolomite and the unconformably overlying Maraloou Formation comprising carbonaceous shale. Overlying the Yerrida Group were sandstone and carbonate of the Yelma Formation (formerly Yandil Formation) which was considered to represent outliers of the Earaheedy Group. Exploration completed in the period 1996 to 2001 included geological reconnaissance and RAB drilling to test for lead mineralisation along the extension of Magellan Hill, adjacent to the Cortez prospect and to previous RAB anomalies and in areas of cover. The best result recorded was 4 m of 4209 ppm Pb from 20 m in a sandstone immediately above the Maraloou Formation. None of the results were considered significant and portions of the tenement surrendered.

column6: The host geology is a quartz veined shear zone in greywacke, related to the Ruby Queen mineralisation, and has returned values of up to 33.5 g/t over 1.5 m. The majority of the old workings lie within mining leases M80/291 and M80/309. Other areas within E80/4103 recommended for follow-up by PMA (1996) included the St Lawrence drag fold where Dominion recorded rock chip samples of up to 4.6 ppm Au and ultrabasic unit reported by Porter (1990), immediately west of the West and Left workings. PMA also suggested a re-evaluation of the Ruby Queen uranium anomaly discovered by Mobil (MEMA) in 1980 for gold potential (Binns et al 1980 and OShea 1981). MEMA drilled a number of percussion and two diamond drill holes into the prospect and concluded that the uranium anomaly was a result of surface concentration in a high uranium background lithology. No gold assays were undertaken.

column6: INTRODUCTION This report outlines the mineral exploration activities carried out over the tenement group C73/2008, which comprised tenements E70/2801 and E70/3000, between 12 March 2009 and 11 March 2010 for the Rocky Gully Project. The primary target in the area was nickelcopper sulphide mineralisation. Herons work indicated that the geology and mineralisation of the project area share similarities with those of the NeboBabel (Musgrave region), Voiseys Bay (Canada), Thunder Bay North (Canada), Talnakh (Norilsk, Siberia) and Santa Rita (Brazil) massive sulphide nickel deposits. Such chonolithconduit mineralisation models have not yet been tested within the AlbanyFraser Orogen. Much of the project area is freehold land.

column6: The project area is located near the north-eastern shores of Lake Barlee, approximately 137 km west of the town of Leonora in the Murchison region of Western Australia. The tenement encompasses a total area of 21,010 hectares. As part of the initial planning stages of the proposed exploration program, Jupiter Mines commissioned Outback Ecology Services (Outback Ecology) to undertake a terrestrial fauna, desktop study in conjunction with vegetation and flora desktop study of the Mt Alfred project area. No site inspection was undertaken and results presented are conclusions based on a desktop study only. A general assessment was made as to the likelihood of particular species of conservation significance occurring within the project area, given the broad habitat types likely to occur.
