column6: Ecological features: Ecological role: A major breeding area for Banded Stilt Cladorhynchus leucocephalus. Plant structural formations: No vegetation occurs on the lake bed; islands and lake margins support low shrubland. Surrounding areas support open scrub. Significance: A good example of an intermittent saline lake of the bioregion. Identified as meeting one Ramsar Criterion for listing as a Wetland of International Importance (Jaensch and Watkins 1999).

column6: The main types of sandstone deposits include roll front deposits - arcuate bodies of mineralisation that crosscut sandstone bedding; tabular deposits - irregular, elongate lenticular bodies parallel to the depositional trend, deposits commonly occur in palaeochannels incised 5 into underlying basement rocks; and tectonic/lithologic deposits - occur in sandstones adjacent to a permeable fault zone. Sandstone deposits constitute about 18% of world uranium resources. Ore bodies of this type are commonly low to medium grade (0.05 - 0.4% U3O8) and individual ore bodies are small to medium in size (ranging up to a maximum of 50 000 t U3O8). The main primary uranium minerals are uraninite and coffinite. Conventional mining/milling operations of sandstone deposits have been progressively undercut by cheaper in situ leach mining methods.

column6: 6 The Mt Dove Prospect Area contains one main BIF horizon that exhibits significant iron enrichment. The mineralisation comprises a mixture of banded hematite, goethite, and shaly limonite iron ore. The enriched horizon at Mt Dove is divided into two lenses by an iron poor chert that occupies a saddle like feature of the topography. The hill itself is roughly sigmoid in shape with the western part representing the larger portion of mineralisation. The eastern hill appears to thin out to a regular magnetite-chert banded iron formation.

column6: The project area covers the southern portion of the Woodie Woodie Manganese Corridor (WWMC); a north-south elongate domain of Archaean-Proterozoic sediments and mafic intrusions hosting numerous structurally and stratigraphically controlled Manganese deposits. The WWMC is on the eastern margin of the Hamersley Basin where the Archaean-Proterozoic Mt Bruce Supergroup is devoid of the Marra Mamba and Brockman Iron Formations which host numerous, large, high grade Iron Ore deposits to the south and west. The WWMC is bounded to the east by the Paterson Province a Proterozoic Mobile Belt hosting numerous structurally-controlled Au-Cu (Telfer), Cu (Nifty), U, PGE (Kintyre) deposits. Primary, epithermal mineralisation at Woodie Woodie is believed to have been Archaean in age, whereas secondary, supergene mineralisation is a much later Oligocene event.

column6: A block size of 20x20x2 metres was utilised for all resources. The mineral resource calculated for the Siberia North prospect is tabled below (Table 7). WORK COMPLETED 2009/10 A Pre-feasibility Study of the KNP was completed by VIALP in January 2009, focusing on the Highway, Goongarrie Hill, Goongarrie South and Siberia North prospects. column6: A serpentinised peridotite forms a semi-continuous member along the eastern edge of the dolerite. The Iron Stirrup ultramafic is the main host rock for gold mineralisation at the Old Faithful, Iron Stirrup and Darius prospects which are found in the adjacent tenements directly south. The unit is dominantly talc-carbonate schist with some talc-carbonate-chlorite and talc-chlorite assemblages and extends in to the tenement EL45/2375.The suite is highly deformed and is thought to have volcanic and komatiitic affinity, possibly in association with Archaean sea-floor spreading or rifting. A suite of black to glassy cherts interbedded with silicic volcanics and/or tuffs lie to the east of the Iron Stirrup ultramafic. This sequence can be traced as a continuous unit through the Project area adjacent to the Iron Stirrup ultramafic.

column6: Coal exploration began in earnest in the Fitzroy Trough in 1965 and continued into the early 1980s. Companies such as Thiess Brothers, Premier Mining and Australian Inland Exploration were prominent amongst those that explored large areas of the Fitzroy Trough but failed to delineate potential mining resources. Drilling carried out by Blackfin PL in 2005 on an area centred on the Petaluma #1 petroleum well on the Deep Well Anticline, 40 kilometres northeast of E04/1520, confirmed the presence of a thick coal seam (approximately 14 metres) at depths below 200 metres. 4 Figure 3: Tenement Geology Interpretation 5 In 2009, a JORC-compliant resource of 511 million tonnes of thermal coal was announced for the Paradise and Duchess Coal Deposits, 70 kilometres northeast of E04/1520. This report provides a summary of all work completed within the surrendered portions of the Nerrima-Moffats Project tenement E04/1520 during the period 20 April 2006 to 19 April 2010.

column6: The region falls within the Edjudina Terrane (Swager et al., 1990) of the Eastern Goldfields Province and is bound by the Claypan fault to the west and the Pinjin fault to the east. This region differs from the domains to the west with minor volumes of metabasalt and metakomatiite and more prolific calc-alkaline andesitic complexes with associated clastic rocks as well as BIF, chert and metasedimentary sequences intruded by metadolerite (Swager,1995a,1997). The region has undergone greenschist metamorphism although high grades upto amphibolite can occur close to granite margins. Locally the geology consists of intermediate schists and sediments with BIF forming prominent north west trending ridges. The basaltic schists tend to form more flat to gently undulating landforms and shallow surficial sediments cover most of the region and outcrop is limited.

column6: Regional Geology The northern margin of the project is flanked by the east-northeast trending weld range BIFs and dolerites, which are part of the Windanning Formation of the Luke Creek Group. Mapping and interpretation by Dr John Martyn of John Martyn and associates suggests the sequence north and south of the range is in part east west trending and thus discordant to the north northeast trending Weld Range banded iron formations and dolerites. To the south of the range the Mindoona Basalt north of Mt Mulcahy and westwards to the old Ryansville gold mine the sequence is west trending and discordant to the trend of the Weld Range. Watkins and Hickman (1990) show a major fault along the southern margin of the southern BIF of the Weld Range. Martyn has mapped an unconformity of basalt or dolerite overlain by chert pebble quartzite followed by south facing wackes.

column6: The high K content of the Loadstone Monzogranite may indicate development by convective fractionation with the development of lighter derivative liquids that may crystallise as high level leucocratic stocks and plutons and may explain the presence of the various felsic intrusives on the granite margins (Wyborne, circa 1990). These granites are usually volatile rich and can be associated with Au/Cu and possibly U mineralisation. The Loadstone Monzogranite is also associated with an anomalous regional aeromagnetic aureole. Members of the Koongie Park Formation occurring within the tenement include hornfelsed (volcanogenic) metasediments, south of the Loadstone Monzogranite, flanked to the east by felsic volcanic and volcaniclastic units (AGSO/GSWA mapping). The area underlain by the Koongie Park Formation in southern portion of the EL is largely obscured by colluvial soils and lateritic duricrust.

column6: Target A conductor is a high priority target. It appears to be in a favourable position on the contact of a magnetic unit interpreted to be an ultra mafic. Nearby historical drilling and geochemistry suggests either nickel or gold could be contained within such a target. The modeling of the data suggested the top of the body began at a depth of approximately 60 metres (base of oxidation? ), has a strike length of 60 metres, has a depth extension exceeding 200 metres, dips to the east-north-east at 65 to 70 degrees and is highly conductive with a conductivity of over 7000S, indicative of massive sulphide.

column6: A set of antithetic NW-trending structures has also been defined, including a linear believed to control the northern edge of the Pincombe Inlier. The Pincombe Inlier continues NE below surface of this linear and is termed the Pincombe axis (Figure 2). Lee and Gunn (1988) have proposed a tectono-stratigraphic model for the evolution of the basin. Initial downwarping of the craton in the late Proterozoic initiated development of the Bonaparte, Ord, Officer and Canning basins, which probably remained interconnected until the Middle Ordovician. A period of non deposition in the Silurian was followed by development of an extensional depocentre in the Bonaparte Basin in the Middle Devonian.

column6: The search was accelerated in the 1970s when the energy crisis of that time caused an increase in demand for thermal coal. The recording of coal occurrences in ditch samples collected when drilling petroleum wells had been noted, which added to the interest in the area. The results did not encourage further work in the areas examined and, with a worldwide downturn in demand for coal in the 1980s, there was a falling away of interest. More recently there has been an upsurge in activity with Rey Resources taking up some 8,000 sq km of tenements, principally following up on the coal discoveries recorded by Premier Mining and Australian Inland Exploration. Reys announcements have generated further interest in the area and other companies (including Cullen) have come in and taken up ground holdings.

column6: The objective of the mineral mapping and alteration study (HyMap data) was to highlight redox (reduction/oxidation) conditions within mineralising fluid migration pathways, which when draped over the established lithostructural framework (the structures which promote and/or arrest fluid migration) combine to provide exploration targets. The compiled public- domain data, part of which will be merged with the surface MMI (Mobile Metal Ion) sampling completed by Emergent, is used to validate and prioritise targets. The evaluation of the different datasets was completed by different companies: Resource Potentials managed the compilation and interpretation of all magnetic imagery; the CSIROs Mineral and Environmental Sensing Group evaluated the companys HyMap hyperspectral imagery (Appendix 1); whereas the other datasets were managed internally by the company. Emergent staff, after discussions with their collaborators, prioritised targets for future work programs. All MMI geochemistry datasets require evaluation within a controlled regolith-landform framework before the commencement of field activities.

column6: Exploration has been recorded in the area since the early 1970s. This is partly as a consequence of explorers extending their efforts from the Archaean Yilgarn greenstone based work and partly as a consequence of exploration companies seeking new deposits in the Proterozoic terrain north of the Yilgarn. Previous work has revealed mineralisation at Mt Bartle, North Pool and Diamond Well with peak values of 1.06% Pb, 1.03% Zn and 19g/t Ag from surface rock chip sampling of the Diamond Well fault gossan. Copper deposits in the region include the old Lee (Ricci), North Prospect, Rooneys, Green Dragon and Thaduna mines. The Thaduna Mines produced 2,823 tonnes of copper metal and remaining historically reported inferred resources average 3.4% Cu and contain 17,000 tonnes of copper metal.

column6: The Yerrida Group was divided into 2 units, the lowermost Juderina Formation made up of the Finlayson Member sandstone, siltstone and dolomite and the unconformably overlying Maraloou Formation comprising carbonaceous shale. Overlying the Yerrida Group were sandstone and carbonate of the Yelma Formation (formerly Yandil Formation) which was considered to represent outliers of the Earaheedy Group. Exploration completed in the period 1996 to 2001 included geological reconnaissance and RAB drilling to test for lead mineralisation along the extension of Magellan Hill, adjacent to the Cortez prospect and to previous RAB anomalies and in areas of cover. The best result recorded was 4 m of DIAMOND WELL PROJECT (E51/1206) Annual Exploration and Report Period 2 July 2009 to 1 July 2010 Data CD 4209 ppm Pb from 20 m in a sandstone immediately above the Maraloou Formation. None of the results were considered significant and portions of the tenement surrendered.

column6: Assays showed low-order gold trends of several ppb with a horizontal configuration within the transported profile (Fig. The first 15 holes LWRB-1 to 15 comprised vertical RAB drilling. Holes LWRB-1 to 9 and 11 tested two targets to the west, all encountering granite at shallow depths ranging from 2 to 11 m. There were no anomalous Au results. Holes LWRB-10 and 12 to 14 situated 3 km to the northeast all encountered transported overburden more than 50 m thick consisting of wet puggy clays. The wet conditions proved beyond the capacity of the RAB rig to deliver samples to surface, and the holes were terminated without reaching identifiable bedrock.

column6: The elevated gold values define a large +10 ppb gold anomaly in the north-east of the project area, with 36% of the samples having gold results of +10 ppb. There is a coincident gold-arsenic anomaly which delineates a prospective trend over a 3km strike and 250m width. Samples collected over sediments contained anomalous zinc values, while samples collected over mafic lithologies had elevated barium. A total of 70 rock chips were collected in the Grants Creek tenements during the 2004-2005 reporting period. All samples were collected from or near quartz outcrops or vein occurrences.

column6: This licence formed part of a much larger group of tenement which was explored from 1976 onwards by the Ashton Exploration JV which led to the discovery of several kimberlite dykes along the western edge of the Halls Creek Mobile Belt including the Argyle Pipe. This work initially comprised a regional drainage sampling followed up later by additional sampling and aeromagnetic surveys. Two magnetic anomalies (DUN07 and DUN08) within E80/2294 were identified as having the potential to be caused by diamondiferous diatremes. Follow-up gravity surveys did not reveal a characteristic low typical of a concealed kimberlite pipe. However, loam samples collected at both anomalies tested positive for kimberlitic indicator minerals and the chemistry of the chromite grains from DUN08 was typical of a kimberlitic/lamproitic source.

column6: To the west of the extents of the magnetic high that defines the komatiite sequence the area was covered with a sandy loam with quartz and nodular ironstone lag. Sporadic small sub-crops of pegmatite and coarse granitoid were encountered and with minor occurrences of chert/shale and heavily weathered sediment. Surface expressions ranged from areas less than 1m to bodies several metres wide that could be followed for 10s of metres. The pegmatite contained coarse feldspar and quartz with minor muscovite. No lithium bearing minerals were obvious.

CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS 9.1 Conclusions The Project is a highly prospective conceptual iron-ore exploration opportunity that has the potential to contain significant amounts of Detrital and or Robe Pisolite deposits. Note that it is likely that the average P content of Pilbara ores will increase with time, potentially making the above materials increasingly attractive for blending purposes. The current depletion in the Pilbara Iron resource base at Paraburdoo coupled with the possible supply of a significant amount of lump material from the Ashburton Project, should lead to an increase in interest by Pilbara Iron. The relative close proximity to the FMG rail at Christmas Creek may also attract interest from FMG, who are keen to demonstrate to the market place that they have the potential resource base to both maintain there current proposed rate of production their proposed capacity expansions.

column6: Gravity Separation (HLS) Testwork Preliminary gravity separation testwork was conducted using heavy liquid separation (HLS) on ore crushed to -2mm and then deslimed at 45m. o Three (3) of the four (4) high grade composites achieved the required grades with 62- 63% CaFe and good SiO2:Al2O3 ratios, although the Fe recovery was slightly low at 73%. Upgrading of the products where necessary, and improvement of the iron recovery, may be achieved by optimising the process parameters and/or by using secondary processing. Magnetic Separation (Davis Tube) Testwork Preliminary magnetic separation testwork was conducted using Davis tube separation on ore crushed to -2mm and then pulverised. The results are encouraging in terms of the grades achieved, ranging from 61 to 65% CaFe and most tests achieving good SiO2:Al2O3 ratios.

column6: 3.0 INTRODUCTION 3.1 Preamble Fimiston Mining discovered Apollo Hill in December 1986, during a drill program aimed at finding the source of abundant alluvial gold at the base of a prominent hill in the area. Active drilling since then has outlined extensive gold mineralization and alteration over a 1km strike length, which is up to 250m wide and dips 45-60 to the east. Multiple gold mineralization events have occurred at Apollo Hill during a complex deformational history. Gold mineralization is accompanied by quartz veins and carbonate-pyrite alteration associated with a mafic-felsic contact. This prospective mafic-felsic contact zone can be traced throughout the tenements over a strike length of 24km.

column6: From mid-1961 to the end of 1962 there was intensive exploration for iron ore throughout the area of the Hamersley Basin in which two main types of ore were targeted: pisolitic channel iron deposits that formed in palaeo-channels of major drainage systems, and hematite and hematitegoethite supergene-enriched banded iron formation. In the West Pilbara the iron ore target was palaeo-channel pisolitic ore (Robe Pisolite). In 1977 Australian Hanna was the first company to commence exploration for low-grade, magnetite quartz, unenriched banded iron-formation iron deposits on their BalmoralBilanoo project area. Banded iron formation occurs worldwide in Archaean cratons from about 3.5 Ga until 2.5 Ga, with their overall volume reaching a maximum in the Hamersley Basin of Western Australia at about 2.5 Ga. Most Archaean iron formations display fine laminations and micro-banding.

column6: Later stage north east and north west striking fault systems (developed in response to east-west compression during D3/D4 deformation) are considered to have been important structures controlling mineralisation around the Mt Magnet gold camp (including at the Hill 50 mine). The lithologies have a near vertical dip and a variable strike. Transported overburden thickness in the region ranges from extensive (several tens of metres) to virtually nil. Locally, soil cover and hardpan obscure a large part of the geology and the only outcrops are typically those of BIFs and cherty units and occasional mafics/dolerites. 4.2 Local Geology The geology within the tenement consists of four main lithologies; 1. a thick, north-westerly trending banded iron formation (BIF) unit which forms a prominent ridge in the west 2. mafic to ultramafic differentiated intrusive sills with minor, thin banded iron units and chert layers 3. felsic volcanics and 4. granitoid plutons either side of the greenstone belt (see Figure 2 below).

column6: RC drilling at Terminator indicated that mineralisation is more structurally complex than first thought, and requires further drilling to adequately understand the orientation of the different mineralised zones. Anomalous drill intercepts from aircore holes east and north of the Terminator Prospect also require follow up with aircore drilling as they may represent parallel zones of mineralisation. Due to aircore being unable to penetrate chert horizons at Thomsons Bore, a program of RC drilling is proposed, which will also aid in interpretation of the numerous mineralised zones. Independence Group NL is planning to commence a scoping study incorporating both C2 and Rosie, as well as planning a resource drillout of these deposits over the next reporting year. REFERENCES Farrell, T.R.

column6: The population at Weld Range is considered significant as it lies at the northern extreme of the species range and appears to be isolated restricted to the slopes and valleys associated with the Weld Range. During correspondence with Atlas, the Department of Environment and Conservation (DEC) has requested: the proponent undertake a habitat risk assessment and targeted surveys for SRE [Short Range Endemic] fauna, particularly Idiosoma nigrum to verify the presence of significant species in proximity to (within 200m of) proposed drilling or other disturbances. Significant fauna species include species that are listed under legislation or as Priority by the Department of Environment and Conservation (DEC), but also includes species that are known or suspected of having a restricted distribution; referred to as Short Range Endemic (SRE). Areas such as the Weld Range are conducive to the evolution of SRE species, as the range provides relictual habitat in which such species can develop in isolation. SREs are common among invertebrate groups such as millipedes, land snails, pseudoscorpions, isopods (slaters) and scorpions.

column6: The Bresnahan Group post dates the Capricorn Orogeny, but the age of deposition is poorly constrained with no isotopic age dating. The Bresnahan Group is unconformably overlain to the south by the Bangemall Group, which forms a large basin. Williams, (1990) proposes a two-fold subdivision of the Bangemall Group into an older 1.6-1.2 Ga sequence (Edmund Subgroup) and a younger 1.2-1.0 Ga sequence (Collier, Manganese and Kahrban Subgroups). By contrast Tyler et al (1991) quote the age of the Bangemall Group as 1.5-1.1 Ga, and they infer an age of c.1.6 Ga for the Bresnahan Group. The Hamersley and Ashburton Basin sequences have undergone very low-grade metamorphism (mostly lower greenschist facies), whereas the Bresnahan and Bangemall Groups are unmetamorphosed.

column6: Work done: Exploration activities on the surrendered portion of E77/987 consisted of review of WAMEX open file data and public domain data, prospectivity review and field reconnaissance. column6: Small erosional windows show mainly granitic subcrop. In the northern part of the Agnew-Lawlers greenstone sequence, west of the mafic- ultramafic units, clastic sediments, referred to locally as the Scotty Creek Formation (conglomerate), host the Waroonga-Genesis gold deposits. The extent of the Scotty Creek Formation to the south, and within E36/656, is inferred only but may present target areas for bedrock-hosted Au mineralization within the tenement area. The tenement area is dominated by gently southeast dipping sheetwash plains that reach down from the White Cloud Cliffs to the west of E63/656 with drainage joining the ephemeral Scotty creek that flows through the easternmost part of the tenement. The creek originates near strongly gold-mineralized parts of the Agnew-Lawlers greenstone belt.

column6: One possible explanation for this involves the infiltration of an Fe-rich melt into the main cumulus crystal pile and its cooling as an intercumulus melt in the crystal pile. This leads to a major shift in Fo in these olivines to lower Fo values (a process very well documented in cumulate assemblages from numerous layered intrusions; Irvine 1980; Naslund 1984) with little or no change in their Ni content, because of the far higher olivine-Ni KD (partition coefficient) with decreasing temperature (KD = 7-8 at 1250C and increases to ~20 at 1100C: Li and Ripley, 2010). If the residual melt achieved sulphide saturation, then the sulphides that crystallized would be significantly more Ni-poor and Cu-rich than magmatic sulphides formed from parental basaltic magmas. This is in keeping with the observation that the dominant sulphide at the Navigator Prospect, albeit in very small amounts, is chalcopyrite. In this model, the Fe-rich residual melts percolating down may become relatively more Ni-rich by dissolving any interstitial sulphides encountered as they do so, as S capacity at sulphide saturation increases significantly as melt Fe contents increase.

column6: Results: Previous exploration campaigns within the Canning Basin have defined the Lightjack Formation as being the key coal target for thermal coal in the region. The Formation hosts regionally extensive coal measures varying in thickness from sub-metre to tens of metres. Folding of the Lightjack Formation has resulted in extensive outcrop/subcrop zones with a combined strike length of ~335 kilometres in ground held by Rey Resources Ltd (including E04/1769), providing numerous, shallow thermal coal drill targets. Conclusions: A drilling programme has been proposed to test the coal measures within tenement E04/1769, commencing 2011 (subject to heritage clearance). iii TABLE OF CONTENTS ABSTRACT ii SUMMARY iv

column6: Whilst the drill rig was operating at the roadside, various traffic management signs and witches hats were placed for at least 100m either side of the drill rig and the local Shire Works Manager was regularly consulted about the suitability of the precautions taken. The green plastic bags and 1m re-split bags were collected every few days and stored on a salt affected piece of land close to the Great Eastern Highway with the owner?s permission. Deviation From Estimated Drilling Costs The program initially proposed comprised 100 Air-Core drill holes, followed by a second phase of up to 100 Deep RC drill holes in areas of encouraging results. RC drilling was adopted for the initial tests however, as this gave greater confidence of penetrating ferruginous duricrust and achieving an adequate test. The program was suspended after 21 drill holes as it was evident by then that the highly folded magnetic unit accessible along the roadsides, contained low levels of vanadiferous titano-magnetite of insufficient grade or extent to be potentially economic.

column6: The main reef worked on this line was the Bosuns, where a quartz-hematite-goethite breccia extends for some 900 metres. Gray and Ebsworth (2010) consider the gold mineralisation to be controlled by a complex interaction between anticlinal folding of a shale/slate unit and faulting of the fold hinge. The Bosuns prospect occurs in the Eastern line, and displays both quartz vein-hosted and sandstonehosted gold mineralisation. All the old mine workings have been focussed on the quartz vein-hosted style which is associated with tight folding of the bedrock. Following a drilling program at the Bosuns prospect by Highlake Resources, the quartz veins were subdivided by Fothergill (2000) in the following types: Quartz veins parallel to bedding and cleavage, with larger veins present in slate hosts than in sandstone host; Shearhosted quartz veins, variably brecciated and enclosed by stockwork veins; probably the most strongly mineralised.

column6: The Emull base metal occurrence within the E80/2612 tenement area is hosted by altered and contact metamorphosed calc-silicate rocks, which have been partially assimilated by the Emull gabbro. The deposit was recognised as a series of copper stained, siliceous gossans located adjacent to the contact between the Emull gabbro and felsic volcanic rocks of the Koongie Park Formation. Thin semi-massive and disseminated mineralisation is confined to 4 discontinuous but apparently stratabound lenses, dominated by sphalerite, with subordinate chalcopyrite and galena. The largest lens has a strike length of 500m and a maximum width of 50m. The genesis of mineralisation at Emull is not certain, although models based on an origin as a volcanic hosted massive sulphide (VHMS) deposit partially assimilated during intrusion of gabbro, or as a skarn developed during intrusion of gabbro into carbonate units within the Koongie Park Formation, have been proposed.

column6: Mt McRae Shale (AHr) The Mt. McRae Shale is a 50 to 60m thick shale sequence comprising two main strands the lower shale rich zone (pyritic shale when fresh), and the upper Colonial Chert Member (locally referred to as the Footwall Zone or FWZ). Mineralisation usually extends down into the FWZ where the overlying Dales Gorge Member is enriched. Brockman Iron Formation (PHb) The Brockman Iron Formation forms the northern, south dipping strike ridge in the Project Area. This formation, comprising the Dales Gorge Member, Whaleback Shale Member, Joffre Member and Yandicoogina Shale Member, is host to the larger high grade iron ore deposits in the Pilbara.

column6: Historic gold workings such as the Pride of Leonora occur just to the east outside the project area and produced 1217 ounces of gold from 1899 to 1905 at an average grade of 24.6g/t Au. Other nearby workings indicates that the majority of gold mineralisation is associated with sulphide bearing ferruginous quartz veins and stockworks emplaced along zones of shearing between tuffaceous horizons and metasediments. In most cases, these mineralised shears trend in a north north-westerly direction but auriferous shears also follow a west north-westerly direction. Another gold association is the contact zone between small granitoid plutons and the greenstone associated with west north-westerly trending faults. 3 Previous Exploration During the late 1970s, the area attracted base metal exploration for volcanogenic massive sulphide mineralisation following the discovery of the Teutonic Bore zinc-copper-silver deposit situated 55 kilometres northwest of Leonora.

column6: Regional controls on the mineralisation appear to be stratigraphic with lithological and structural control becoming important at the mine scale. In the west of the Peak Hill district the Horseshoe Fortnum group of deposits, the western and southern Peak Hill deposits, Harmony, Wembley, Heine?s Find, Mikhaburra, Cashman and Ruby Well are all hosted in cherty or quartz rich units at or close to the top of the Narracoota Volcanic rocks of the Glengarry Group. The faulted contact between the basalts of the Narracoota Volcanics and the overlying Thaduna Greywacke is considered highly prospective throughout the Nabberu Basin. Gold occurs in quartz veins locally but mineralisation is thought to be volcanic exhalative. Thickening of gold mineralisation may be associated with regional northwest trending crosscutting faults and mineralisation along the Narracoota Volcanics contact is associated with structural dislocations.

column6: A significant number of Proterozoic dykes of varying composition (doleritic, dioritic and dacitic) and orientation are seen throughout the area. The youngest interpreted rocks in the area comprise sizable (up to 20m wide) quartz/sericite/epidote veins that cut all other rock types, including the Proterozoic dykes. Seventy-one RAB drillholes (CFR001-071) were completed on the Centre Forrest prospect on 80m spaced lines over 720m of strike for a total of 2058m and 552 samples. It was possible to drill RAB holes to blade refusal at the western end which lies over granite-gneiss, but this was not consistently possible over the mafic package to the east. Particularly on the southern lines, it was commonly only feasible to drill to 25 or 30 m before puggy clay blocked the hole, or the sample was unacceptably wet.

column6: This resource estimation has been carried out to professional industry and best practice standards and is compiled by a Qualified and Competent Person, as required in the rules of the ASX and the JORC code, December 2004.  Current JORC Indicated+Inferred Resource 452,694 tonnes @ 2.78g/t Au Oxide gold recoveries excellent, resource 193,411 tonnes @ 2.65 g/t Au to 30 metres depth. Felsic schist hosted, with Cu,Pb,Zn,Ag in primary zone The A-Zone Prospect (or Carlinga Well A-Zone) contains a shallow gold resource (previous non-JORC estimate 461,188 tonnes @ 3.11 g/t Au) defined by Roebuck Resources/ Polaris Pacific NL Joint Venture in the late 1980's. Quartz-veined pyritic quartz-sericite schists with strongly elevated copper lead zinc silver grades host this mineralisation, which is cut by a number of late stage dolerite dykes which have exerted some influence on supergene copper mineralisation. column6: The model used by Octagonal for the Matrix Reef involves hydrothermal gold-bearing fluids moving along either extensional (quartz vein-filled) fractures, or along shear type (indicator) fractures. The relative changes in pressure (access to extensional openings), or in composition of host rocks (carbonaceous material), cause the fluids to become unstable causing gold precipitation. The high grade of 148 g/t Au reported for the Matrix Reef is an indication of the very coarse nature of the gold mineralisation. The McIntyre Goldfield is characterised by coarse gold nuggets, which appear to be derived from both primary (hydrothermal) and secondary (regolith) fluids. column6: Carbonaceous Sandstone (Yr): This unit is conformable with the sandstone unit and is interpreted as an erosional contact between the Yelma Formation and Maraloou Formation; Maraloou Formation (MIs): The unit often contains finely crystalline pyrite and carbonate veining. The unit has been intersected to depths over 300 metres during diamond drilling beneath the Magellan deposit and minor base metal sulphides were recorded. At Cano mineralisation occurs from the surface (eg MMRC163-164, 211-213) 4 in the southern and western parts of the deposit and although relatively flat lying, becomes deeper to the north and east due to an increase in surface relief. The near-surface mineralisation is often thicker than the deeper mineralisation which is probably a supergene effect. The deposit covers an area of approximately 900 metres by 500 metres, orientated northwest by northeast.

column6: Based on the tenements position within the same north-northeast zone of subparallel dolerite dykes as the diamondiferous kimberlites in the North Kimberley field, there is a moderate to high potential for the discovery of diamondiferous kimberlites / lamprophyres within the Bauxite Resources tenements. The presence of major fault intersections proximal to the tenement areas within the same northeast trending corridor as diamond-bearing kimberlites in the North Kimberley field supports the requirement to complete further geophysical surveys, interpretation, and ground follow-up work over these areas in order to identify potential diamondiferous kimberlite pipes within the Kimberley Group. Extensive residual and supergene bauxite mineralisation within the regolith over the Carson Volcanics in the North Kimberley Basin reflects a known mineral field. The potential to discover phosphate nodules within marine sediments or phosphatised zones of altered limestone and dolomite within the Kimberley Group is moderate. Prospective horizons for phosphate within the tenement areas include the King Leopold Sandstone (basal conglomerate), Carson Volcanics (minor limestone), and the Hart Dolerite (potential for carbonates altered to dolomite).

column6: 3.2 Prospect Geology The tenement overlies part of a north-northwest trending stratigraphy comprising mafic and felsic volcanics and metasediments, cut by strike parallel faults, and intruded and truncated by granitic bodies. A detailed analysis of any geological mapping in the area has been undertaken.

column6: Regionally the granite and gneiss domes display a weak northeasterly trending metamorphic foliation. Page | 4 The granitoids which post-date the gneiss also transect the early foliation of the greenstone belts, and bear no protoclastic fabric. It is possible that these granitoids were generated during the doming of the gneiss, and subsequently intruded the greenstone belts and gneiss. The dome structure has been greatly modified by intense deformation which produced north-north-westerly trending belts of strongly granulated and mylonitized rock. Second generation formation is considered to be synchronous with the formation of these zones, and resulting in folding and crenulation of the earlier metamorphic fabric.

column6: Internal granitoids and porphyries are also common and metamorphic grade is typically greenschist to amphibolite facies, with metamorphic grade increasing towards the east. Locally the geology comprises a moderately to steeply east dipping sequence of dominantly mafic and felsic volcanic rocks with dolerites and ultramafic rocks common. A package of talc chlorite schists and other variably sheared ultramafic units dominate the central area of the project and host the gold mineralization at Kirgellas Gift and further north at Anglo Saxon. The southern area is dominated by granitic intrusives covered by a veneer of greenstone lithologies. Late east-west oriented Proterozoic dolerite dykes cut all stratigraphy through the centre of the tenement.

column6: Gold deposits within the area are a mixture of low tonnage high grade underground ore and moderate grade, moderate tonnage open pit developments. Recent successes in exploration in the area have defined broad low grade gold resources within sheared granite and also within andesitic volcanics associated with intrusive granite bodies. Gold mineralisation occurs in a variety of host rocks and structural settings with the Savannah project lying along strike from the Edjudina line of workings which extends over 15 kilometres between the Glengarry Mine and Clymies Well. Gold production from this area is recorded as approximately 1363 kg from 43,043 tonnes at an average grade of 31.67g/t Au. The gold is associated with boudinaged quartz veins with anastomosing shear zones hosted within pyritic sericite chlorite schists with felspar porphyry dykes occurring within the shear zones.

column6: Exploration for pegmatites enriched in Tin/Tantalum/REE Exploration of Pegmatites within the batholith is traditionally carried using a radiometric survey to target fractionated radiometric material but can also be undertaken using an additional tool; the detection of Kaolinite-rich regolith from landsat imagery can help focus exploration on K-feldspar enriched pegmatites that may exist under shallow regolith cover (See Appendix I and II). In applying this method of remote sensing targeting, the southern part of the Shaw River Batholith shows less obvious radiometric anomalies and kaolinite associated alteration than the northern part of the area which has historically been prospective for Tin and Tantalum. 9 Stream Sediment Sampling and Rock chips sampling The work plan for targeting Tin, Tantalum, Gold and Base Metals includes stream sediment sampling. A good stream sediment campaign should provide around 4 to 5 samples per square kilometre, equating to ~ 2585 samples according to the local drainage pattern (see Appendix III).

column6: Considering data available, the tenement has immediate potential for two types of mineral prospectivity; uranium in calcrete / vein style and rare earth elements (REEs) in eluvial style deposits that have been weathered out of pegmatite dykes. Uranium is a major mineral of interest in the area and much exploration occurred in the 1970s for calcrete style deposits. It is now believed that vein style mineralisation associated with the numerous pegmatites in the area could provide the most potential. The uranium source is likely from the regional basement augen gneiss which has above average background radiation levels. This gniess has been metamorphosed into the Morrissey suite migmatite and has two pegmatite belts to the north and south.

column6: Comprehensive reviews of historical data highlighted a zone of anomalous nickel and copper in the Christchurch Dam area (located at the centre of the northern portion of E28/1383), which was confirmed by Heron using a Niton XRF survey. Herons field mapping of the Christchurch Dam area revealed targets that were drilled with three angled diamond holes were drilled for a total of 419.5 m. EM surveys were conducted to pick up sulphide stringers. Diamond hole ADDD0002 intercepted massive sulphide stringers between 60 and 65 m depth with a maximum assay result of 0.12 m @ 0.97% Ni, 0.23% Cu and 1,207 ppb Pt+Pd from 62.49 to 62.61 m. Trace disseminated sulphides were encountered in ADDD0001 and ADDD0003 but did not return significant results. A representative cross-section for the Christchurch Dam prospect is provided in Figure 9. Petrographical analysis of diamond core samples showed that the majority of the sulphides were remobilised except in minor basaltic dykes which contain possible former primary magmatic Fe NiCu sulphides.

column6: Most currently active have grades in the range of 49 g/t, although this may reduce in areas of strongly weathered regolith. Lode-gold deposits may form in any lithology (Figure 6) within a greenstone belt, however spatial analysis suggests preferences (Groves 1990). Rheological factors are important, as a brittle material is more likely to localise fluid flow and thus allow mineralization. Chemical composition also plays a role, with Fe or Fe-+Mg rich rocks capable of destabilizing gold complexes precipitating Fe sulphides and gold. This is the situation in the Kalgoorlie and Kambalda districts where major gold-lode deposits are hosted within mafic rocks.

column6: The terrain is degraded agricultural, with frequent salt scalds and erosion gullies created by contour channels formed to keep salt from rising into salt-free soils which are presently under cultivation. Regional geology and magnetics Most of the tenement is covered by sand plain deposits overlying poorly outcropping, interpreted moderately to strongly deformed granite and granodiorite of the South West Terrane of the Archean Yilgarn Craton (Fig. The tenement encloses a broad swath of the interpreted Jimperding Gneiss Complex which is a remnant greenstone belt that is locally defined by occasional small outcrops of granulite-facies quartzites, gneisses and mafic granulites, enclosed and intruded by granites of the Western Gneiss Terrain. The belt is very poorly exposed but has been traced by high-resolution aeromagnetic surveys which define broad sub-parallel NNWSSE trending linear structures, in places forming fold closures (Fig. The regional landform consists of low rolling hill topography interspersed with broad drainage valleys which as a result of land clearing have degraded to salt marshes and claypans with variable degrees of salt encrustation.

column6: The author of this report considers the ID2 estimate to significantly understate the grade of the resource because it is an unconstrained model with relatively large blocks. As such, the blocks are too tall to properly represent some of the lodes, resulting in significant dilution. The search envelope is isotropic, whereas geological and geochemical interpretation indicates strong anisotropy within the lodes. There are no manual geological or geochemical constraints applied to the search envelope.

column6: As a result of the historic coal exploration review a helicopter reconnaissance survey was conducted over the Lightjack Hill Project. The survey confirmed excellent access within the project area via fence lines and station tracks to numerous wells. With the exception of isolated buttes and mesa style ranges most of the terrain is subdued with much of the prospective geology outcropping as discrete areas of subcrop and rubble (Figure 1 and 2). The Canning Basin started to form in the Ordovician, when a marine incursion transgressed eastwards over the Precambrian basement. Sedimentation probably proceeded slowly in the basin from the Ordovician to the Middle Devonian, and was interrupted by periods of tectonism and erosion.

column6: Low to moderate grade manganese enrichment was intercepted at the Blue Cliffs Prospect in drill holes EARC0022 EARC0026 and EARC0028 EARC0034, and in the Blue Nugget Prospect in drill holes EARC0037 EARC0040 (Table 4 Table 6). Manganese enrichment is from surface or near surface, flat-lying, comparable laterally across the Blue Cliffs Prospect, and discontinuous at the Blue Nugget Prospect. column6: An extensive palaeodrainage network, which developed during the Late Cretaceous, is preserved throughout the area. The valleys are broad and flat, are infilled by alluvium and lake deposits, and contain braided and meandering stream channels. Extensive salt lakes, such as the Lake Grace System and Dumbleyung Lake, result from the poinding of internal drainage and surface discharge of groundwater behind topographical and structural restrictions. The licence covers a portion of the Western Gneiss Terrane of the Yilgarn Craton. There is minimal outcrop in the licence area and no know mineral occurrences.

column6: Once the recent auger sampling is completed at Skeleton Rocks the data should be processed and interpreted by Nigel Brand. Any significant nickel anomalies should be followed up with surface EM surveys. There appears to be no real exploration potential within the southern part of the Lucy Rocks area, these areas should be considered for relinquishment. The Skeleton Rocks West Project regionally is located at the southern extension of the Westonia Greenstone Belt, a discontinuous, NW-trending greenstone belt that stretches approximately 100km from Dicks Reward in the northwest towards Edwards Find in the southeast, where the belt almost joins with the Southern Cross Greenstone Belt (Gee, 1982) (Figure 2). The Westonia greenstone belt generally comprises a mix of amphibolite, felsic metasediments, felsic and mafic gneiss, ultramafics, and localised iron formations.

column6: The purpose of the drilling was to confirm the location of the palaeochannel as indicated by the gravity survey and then determine the stratigraphy and oxidation state of the sediments contained within it to provide a vector to those regions that contain sediments suitable to host uranium mineralisation. All holes were shallow, with depths ranging from 14- 24m, and the sediments intersected consisted of units of sand and sand clays with lesser amounts of gravel with the fill overlying a granite basement. The sediments were all oxidized with the extent of oxidation ranging from very weakly to strong, which is favourable for the uranium to remain dissolved in the ground water rather than for it to precipitate to form mineral deposits. Downhole gamma surveying was conducted on 2 aircore holes. The holes were cased with 50mm PVC casing as deep as possible before the hole became blocked and then the survey conducted to the depth of casing.

column6: In a CAMIRO study using Pb isotopes the mobile metal ions were proved to have been transported from deeply-buried ore bodies to the surface. The theory behind MMI is that a buried ore body through physical (e.g. capillary rise) and electrochemical processes frees mobile metal ions, which are migrating to the 8 surface where they are weakly attached to soil particles. These mobile metal ions are sampled by the MMI technique. Their mobility is subsequently restricted by different processes resulting in them being permanently bound to the soil particles.

column6: Complications of Anomaly Interpretation In the grading process, small, discrete conductors were given a better grade than larger bodies, which were assumed to be lithological. Lithological conductors are generally formational (i.e. composed of a particular stratigraphic unit), with extended strike lengths, broader anomalies, and moderate to large electromagnetic responses. Often their conductivity is due to graphitic content rather than economic mineralisation. However the conclusion should not be drawn that larger conductors are definitely not mineralised.

column6: It was considered that although the tenement was host to coal measures within the northern portion of the tenement these coal-bearing sediments were at depths greater than 350m from surface. column6: The Project area overlies the contact of the Carnarvon basin and the Pilbara Craton (Figure 3), where early Proterozoic granitoids which have been intruded by Proterozoic dolerite dykes and sills make up the basal unit throughout the Jailor Bore project area. These granites are presumed to be the source of the uranium within the area and some of the gneisses and granites are also reported to be radioactively anomalous. This project is considered prospective for calcrete type chemical trap deposits in the Gneudna Formation limestones in E09/1194 and E09/1298, for roll front type redox boundary deposits in the porous sandstones and conglomerates in E09/1298, E09/1434 and, and for unconformity deposits similar to those in the Alligator River (N.T.) and Athabascan basins (Canada) along the major structures that underlie the basin in E09/1434 and E09/1575. The reporting year concentrated on the aerial photography interpretation of the Jailor Bore Area, a planned site visit and native title negotiations.

Samples RG058-67 consisted of unmineralised to strongly mineralised host sandstone, from the main outcrop area.

column6: 9 A total of 116 soil samples passing 2 mm mesh, 30 rock chip samples and 4 drillhole samples were assayed for Au, As, Bi, Co, Cr, Cu, Fe, Mn, Mo, Ni, Pb, Pt, Sb, and Zn by ICP-MS and ICP-OES following aqua regia digest at Ultratrace Laboratories in Perth. Sample sites are shown on Figures 8 and gold results on Figure 9. Results of the soil and rock chip sampling were generally disappointing as they did not back up the aeromagnetic target or help delineate a new target area. Gold values in soils on the tracks were generally low with a background reading of 05 ppm. Little correlation can be drawn between areas identified as being anomalous from regional aeromagnetics and the assayed soil samples.

column6: The detailed interpretation of the low level aeromagnetic survey suggests several conceptual structural targets exist, which warrant further investigation. Initially the sampling program was carried out on a 50 x 200m grid using a tractor mounted auger supplied by Roy S. Miles, a Dumbleyung based fencing contractor and later it was completed using a hand auger. 1520 samples were collected to an average depth of 500mm.

column6: Gold production from this area is recorded as approximately 1363 kg from 43,043 tonnes at an average grade of 31.67g/t Au. The gold is associated with boudinaged quartz veins with anastomosing shear zones hosted within pyritic sericite chlorite schists with felspar porphyry dykes occurring within the shear zones. The Yarri mining centre includes several mineralised structures and quartz reefs in east dipping shear structures within the Yarri Monzogranodiorite and along the basalt/monzonite contact. Historic production in the region includes 695kg of gold from 45,559 tonnes at a grade of 15.3g/t Au whilst in more recent times mining in the 1940s and late 1980s at the Porphyry and Million dollar pits totalled 4446 kg of gold from 1.3 million tonnes at a grade of 3.42 g/t Au. Historic gold production at the Edjudina Mining Centre, 6 km SE of the tenement, of 33,215 oz @ 46.9 g/t of gold was recorded, sourced from contiguous underground mines developed on series of sub-parallel quartz lodes over a strike length of 1.4 kilometres between 1898 and 1939.

For soil samples the Fe ranges from 5.7% to 9.3% Cu ranges from 37ppm to 128ppm Ag ranges from 0.01ppm to 0.16ppm The surface rock chip sample had anomalous values of Fe: 53.06% Cu: 48 ppm Ag: 0.03ppm Assay data analysis has shown an anomalous Fe rock chip value of 53.06% in the north central portion of the sampling zone. Soil sampling results show anomalous Ag value of 0.16ppm in the centre of the sampling zone and anomalous Cu value of 128ppm in the southwest. Based on this soil sampling data, the next phase of exploration work will include refining the drilling targets and a RAB drilling programme.

column6: A total of 31 lines were sampled. The results of the sampling programme (Tables 3 & 4 and Figures 6 to 10) revealed broad coincident copper (>100ppm Cu; maximum value of 259ppm Cu) and nickel (>60ppm Ni; maximum value of 456ppm Ni) anomalism, in the north east of the sampling area. These results could reflect one or more of the following: the underlying high magnesium basalt or the presence of concealed ultramafic lithology, or Potentially be due to mineralisation of the lithology, common in the Yilgarn Craton and often associated with gold mineralisation. There is an interesting coincident arsenic (>50ppm As; maximum value of 178ppm As) and gold (>5ppb; maximum 87ppb Au) anomaly in the north of the sampled area, a good target for potential gold mineralisation. It is worth noting however that the anomalous areas are mapped as generally sub cropping basement, whereas the areas between the anomalism are generally mapped as transported colluvium or alluvium, and therefore the anomalism may potentially extend below this transported cover.

column6: Locally the geology is dominated by significant Cenozoic ferruginous clay, colluvium and silts. Highly weathered ferruginous bedrock containing carbonate nodules or mottled weathered granites are present. Clay saprolites and alluvium, consisting of channel & overbank deposits, calcareous loams and fine sands are associated with several significant drainage systems in the licence. Within the tenement area BIF units are observed in the slivers of tenement to the SW, while in the main block of the tenement weathered felsic volcanic and a weathered mafic intrusive of doleritic affinity was identified passing quickly to the north into residual sandy soil. EXPLORATION Exploration carried out during 2010/11 was carried out in conjunction with adjoining tenements held by Hawthorn Resources E31/782 and E31/760 (through Ridgeback Holdings E31/888 Newland Dam 2011-2012 Annual Report -3 - title transfer pending) and also with extensive exploration activities carried out in the Trouser Legs JV area (Hawthorn 70% , Gel Resources 30%) on adjacent tenements M31/78, 79, 88, 113, and 284. .

column6: Massive sulphide bodies are usually fairly narrow and of short strike length, and they are often highly conductive. If sufficient pyrrhotite or magnetite is present, a magnetic anomaly may be associated with the EM anomaly. Stratiform deposits, however, commonly contain disseminated sulphide mineralisation, and electromagnetic responses over such bodies may be diffuse to almost non-existent. Strike length can be considerable in the case of stratiform deposits, and magnetic signatures, if any, tend to parallel the trend of the regional geology. SPECTREM EM anomalies are graded A, B, C or D, with grade A anomalies being the most favorable.

column6: The Siliciclastic Sequences are the youngest Archaean rocks and are predominantly turbidites but include carbonaceous shale, sandstone, conglomerate, chert and magnetic shale (BIF). A regional, four-stage, contractional deformation history has been constructed for the Eastern Goldfields (Morey, 2007): D1 - the earliest shortening event is characterised by a roughly NS directed thrusting and recumbent folding that resulted in large scale repetition of the greenstone sequences. D2 - a major stage of ENE-WSW shortening which gave rise to NNW trending, regional, upright folds and major reverse faulting/thrusting. This deformation episode was associated with multiple shortening episodes and intervening extensional stages. D3 - further ENE-WSW shortening reactivated NNW-trending D2 structures to produce dominantly sinistral strikeslip ductile faults.

column6: Uplift accompanied by extensive erosion and weathering took place from Late Cretaceous through the Tertiary in the Perth Basin. Numerous marine incursions occurred during the Late Tertiary to Pleistocene period that eroded a marine platform extending inland for a distance of around 30km to the Darling and Whicher Scarps. Unconformably overlying the Cretaceous Leederville Formation in the Southern Perth Basin is a paralic sequence of marine-estuarine, beach and dune deposits, locally enriched in heavy mineral sands and known as the Yoganup Formation. This is variably overlain to the west by the Guilford Formation and by later alluvial fan deposits and thin aeolian quartz and calcarenite dunes of the Bassendean, Spearwood and Quindalup dune systems. There have been numerous phases of HM accumulation, ascribed broadly to the Capel (0-10m RL) and the Yoganup (20-80m RL) palaeo-shorelines.

column6: The western margin of the tenement is dominated by metasedimentary gneiss and felsic granulite as major phases and minor basic granulite. This unit is bounded to the east by a basic granulite containing felsic and granitic intrusives predating the post tectonic metamorphism. This unit is host to gold mineralisation at both the Duggan and Griffins Find prospects. Intruding this unit in the northeast of the tenement is a younger porphyritic granite containing rafts of the basic granulite. A major shear striking to the NNW runs through the central area of the tenement.

column6: Mapping by GSWA has led to definition of the Glengarry Basin (Gee, 1979 & 1987, and Gee & Grey, 1993) which has more recently been subdivided into the Yerrida, Bryah and Padbury Basins (Pirajno et al., 1998 & 2000). Due to the complex structural framework, combined with cover obscuring many areas, it is considered that further revision of the stratigraphy of the area will take place as more information becomes available. The region has a history of copper production at Thaduna from epigenetic, fault-related mineralisation, and gold production further to the west at the Peak Hill mining centre where epigenetic gold in quartz reefs were exploited. The Horseshoe Lights copper-gold mine, located in the north-western part of the Bryah Basin has produced some 300,000 oz gold and 50,000t copper. The mineralisation is hosted within felsic schist of the Narracoota Volcanics and comprises massive, disseminated and stringer sulphides with a Cu-Au-Ag-Pb-Zn association, with GSWA interpreting the deposit as volcanogenic massive sulphide (VMS) style.

column6: Conclusions The work completed within the first year of E52/2539 provides a promising target for future exploration activities. The multi-element MMI geochemical association suite of the primary target suggests that the geochemistry maybe associated with hydrothermal alteration derived from an intermediate granitiod. An outcropping altered diorite was mapped immediately north of the geochemical anomaly and several rocks found within the area of geochemical anomalism show pervasive silica sericite alteration and maybe directly associated with the mineralisation. Follow up surface geochemistry will be required to infill sampling to a sufficient density to allow for drill targeting. column6: The Mundine Well Dolerite Suite has been dated at 755 3 Ma. E09/649 was first granted to Sovereign Resources NL in 1994. Equatorial described the geology of E09/649 as consisting of two distinct types of granite: (1) early stage, gneissic biotite-muscovite adamellite granitoid to the north and (2) late stage, fine to coarse grained and foliated granodiorite and adamellite (similar to the Minnie Springs Prospect host). column6: A large number of gold, platinum group metal (PGM) and nickel copper sulphide targets have been outlined, identifying the Lamboo Intrusion as a fertile magmatic body. column6: This fault is a major structure, estimated to extend in a northerly direction for some 150 km. The Inglewood, Tarnagulla, Eganstown and Ballarat goldfields are situated from 3 5 km west of the Campbelltown fault. Gold mineralisation in the Campbelltown Goldfield is associated with the faulting of tightly folded north trending anticlines and synclines. Old mine workings extend over a distance of 5 km, and occur in two lines (~ reef systems), about 500 metres apart. The apparent en echelon disposition of the reefs along the two reef lines implies the presence of a shear zone, informally termed here as the Campbelltown Shear Zone.

column6: While further exploration for nickel has been conducted since the early 1970s and a best result of 3m @ 3.05% Ni was intersected in a 1998 Bundarra Holdings Pty Ltd RC hole, an economic nickel accumulation is yet to be discovered. The nearest economic nickel deposit is located approximately 24km to the northeast of the Spargos prospect at the Nepean nickel mine, which is at the southern end of the Coolgardie greenstone belt and was discovered by Metals Exploration NL in 1968. Twelve RC holes for a total of 2,933 metres were completed at the Benari Prospect on E15/913 (Figure 7). The drilling intersected the defined MLTEM conductors but most were found to be sulphidic sediments, however, ultramafic lithologies were confirmed in some holes.

column6: The results follow the similar trend discovered by Kurnalpi Golds RAB program although it does not seem to be continuous along strike as little mineralisation was intersected at the north of Zandor and between the central trend and the southern workings. Of particular interest is KURB164, where a high grade but narrow quartz vein, hosted in massive basalt was intersected at 63m. To the south of Zandor, very little anomalous gold was intersected and although the historic workings were not targeted directly, the results were disappointing. column6: The preservation of chert mesolayers within zones of hematite alteration suggests that these jaspilite occurrences essentially represent domains that were exposed to the same, second-stage hypogene fluid that precipitated hematite in the orebodies at Windarling. However, in contrast, these more peripheral hematitic alteration domains lacked the earlier hypogene dolomite alteration and were therefore not subject to the same level of iron-oxide concentration that accompanied the leaching of dolomite. The other line of field evidence that points to the formation of jaspilite during the second-stage hypogene hydrothermal event (that formed iron-ore mineralisation) is the presence of massive to irregular bodies of red and translucent chalcedony within some jaspilite units. These jasperoid bodies display transitional or diffuse boundaries with the host jaspilite units, and may be up to 50 m long and extend across strike for up to 20 m. Chalcedony takes the form of diffuse replacement zones and more distinct dilational veins. The veins appear to have formed during a progressive hydrothermal event, during which early hematitic chalcedonic replacement zones or veins are cross-cut or replaced by later barren white chalcedony.

column6: Mylonitic rocks are comparatively abundant in a deformation zone up to 10km wide, with north-northeast and northnorthwest trending structures apparently having been rotated into the Darling trend. This shear zone was referred to as the proto-Darling Fault and Donnybrook-Nannup Shear zone. b. ALTERATION The Donnybrook project is interpreted to host epithermal style mineralisation. Epithermal deposits are distinguished from Achaean metamorphic quartz vein-lode deposits by gangue mineral types and textures, alteration styles and metallic assemblages. Distinctive criteria which distinguish the epithermal deposits in the Donnybrook region are: Platy textures with silica replacing original carbonate and/or sulphate minerals Breccias, re-cemented by silica, especially quartz and chalcedony-jasper-chert (locally laminated) Multiple fine quartz veining/stockworking Grey pyritic silica and pyritic chert breccias Wall rock alteration is best illustrated from the diamond core from holes within the Donnybrook Project.

column6: EIS Final Report Ashburton Monster Project Avocet Resources 13 EIS Final Report Ashburton Monster Project Avocet Resources 14 Interpretation The results of the RC drilling show that the iron-rich and banded cherts observed and mapped at surface are primarily a weathering effect and do not appear to extend to depth. This makes the model of a Homestake-style deposit less likely, although there are still a number of iron-rich surface outcrops that remain untested. The intersections of significant thicknesses of graphitic shale in a number of drill holes, especially MORC001 and MORC005, provide an explanation for the Airborne EM anomaly. The Au/Ag prospectivity along the strike length of the Monster vein structure is limited to the far western end of the drilled area and the highest gold grades were associated with a mapped cross cutting fault structure with a deep weathering profile. Slightly lower but still anomalous Ag and Au in the west are also associated with pyrite-rich quartz veining in the main target quartz vein (Figure 13).

column6: (Seymour, D.B et al, 1988; Powell, C. & Horwitz, R.C 1994) Powell and Horwitz (1994) proposes the subdivision of the Wyloo Group into upper and lower sub-groups based on the presence of a distinct unconformable geological boundary separating the two groups resulting from tectonic activity in the formation of the Ashburton Trough (i.e. Mount McGrath Formation unconformable overlies the Duck Creek Dolomite.) This hypothesis is supported by the locality of deposition of the sediments that comprise both the lower and upper Wyloo Groups. Sediments belonging to both the lower and upper Wyloo Groups are present only within the Mount McGrath and Ashburton Trough respectively. This geological unconformity that separates the Wyloo Group into separate upper and lower subgroups was created during the down faulting and subsidence at the latter parts of the lower Wyloo Group sedimentation in the Mount McGrath Trough, resulting from lateral tectonic extensions and the formation of the Ashburton trough.

column6: A similarly oriented shear (Eastern shear zone) was interpreted by RGC 10km to the east. Between these the stratigraphy is disrupted by a series of northwest trending faults. Exploration was primarily focused on gold mineralisation.

column6: Page 9 of 24 In the Boorara domain, more complex lithostratigraphic successions are recorded because early felsic volcanism in distinct centres developed at the same time as the regional extensive komatiite volcanic flows. These units generally trend north-east, and prominent structural lineations in the form of shear zones trend northwesterly. The main structural element of the Boorara domain is the south plunging Scotia Kanowna Anticline, which contains the prospective Highway Ultramafic overlying tholeiitic basalts. This structure is sometimes referred to as the Scotia- Kanowna Dome. The Gordons tenements lie on the eastern limb of the Scotia Kanowna Dome.

column6: The Tertiary palaeochannels of the Lake Raeside project areas may have the potential to host roll-front uranium deposits such as those in the Gawler Craton of South Australia. The presence of organic matter or pyrite in and adjacent to the palaeochannels can present an ideal redox trap for the precipitation of uranium. The combination of uraniferous source rocks and potential trap sites could make the Lake Raeside palaeochannels prospective exploration targets for roll-front uranium. Carbonate is often formed when organic matter is oxidised and any uranium associated with it can be deposited as calcrete. Radiometric anomalies along sections of the Lake Raeside drainage system offer excellent readily testable drill targets for future uranium exploration.

column6: Structural data from Landsat, Air Photo and Air Magnetic images were collated and transferred to a scale useful for understanding the tenement in detail. The tenements are situated over Proterozoic sedimentary formations with a dominant SW-NE strike orientation that have been folded around the flanks of the Goodin Dome. The Doolgunna Formation rocks have potential gold exploration targets related to the fault structures radial to the Goodin dome and also chert horizons associated with the intruded mafics. It is possible that planar faults, bedding plane faults, major rock contacts and areas where multiple fracture planes are coincident will be sites of hydrothermal alteration and potential gold targets. Base metal mineralization is normally likely to occur in relation to specific lithologies and stratigraphic units associated with sulphides within sedimentary, mafic and volcanic rock units common to the Doolgunna and Maraloou Formations.

column6: The oldest unit recorded from E04/2151 is the Late Devonian (Famennian), Windjana Limestone which, along with the overlying Nullara Limestone, forms the major cliffs of the Oscar Range. The Devonian reef complex within the Oscar Range area has been extensively studied and is described in Playford and Lowry (1966). Extensive outcrops of the Early Carboniferous, Gumhole Formation and Fairfield Formation are mapped to the north of the limestone cliffs. Within the tenement, limestones, dolomites and a variety of clastic sedimentary lithologies have been encountered in shallow drilling and pitting. Brown to black carbonaceous siltstone and brown to white, fine to medium grained sandstones dominate the clastic sedimentary sequence.

column6: It lies at the convergence of Australias main Proterozoic structural trends that reflect the amalgamation of the North, West, and South Australian Cratons (Smithies, 2013). Within the West Musgrave province the nature and age of the basement is poorly constrained with intrusive components as old as c.1600 Ma and banded gneiss dominated by material derived from volcanic, volcanoclastics and sedimentary protoliths (Smithies, 2008). The 1335-1295 Ma Mount West Orogeny and 1220-1155 Ma Musgravian Orogeny are major crustal events that involved intrusion of early I-type Warakurna Supersuite and later A-type Pitjantjara Supersuite granites, high-grade crustal reworking, intensive deformation, and widespread ultra-high temperature metamorphism (Smithies, 2008). The Ngaanyatjarra Rift is the main structural expression of the Mesoproterozoic Giles Event which saw the earlier Mesoproterozoic rocks of the Musgrave Province extensively intruded and covered by bimodal magmatic rocks of the Warakurna Supersuite. Volcanic rocks of the Warakurna Supersuite (Bentley Supergroup) are the dominant component of the Bentley Basin the fill of the Ngaanyatjarra Rift.

column6: Detailed historical gravity modelling of the northern part of the Dandaragan Trough indicates that the Urella Fault is listric with an average dip of approximately 55o west, and a very large down throw directly from the Mullingara Inlier to the deepest part of the trough. Hence in-filling of the trough was likely very swift and the opportunity for substantial uranium leaching to occur was much diminished. Page 12 of 21 The potential palaeochannels in the basement are far too deep (up to 12,000m) to represent a target. The only possible targets would be palaeochannels developed in the near-surface sediments such as the Parmelia Formation. column6: Exploration for uranium in the granite sequence has been minimal, and there has been only cursory investigation of other channels within the valley. In 1970, regional radiometric surveys defined a large and intense anomaly in the Yeelirrie Valley drainage system. Shallow auger drilling by Western Mining Corporation in 1971 showed a large body of carnotite mineralisation hosted by calcrete. Over the subsequent 12 years, over 6,000 drill holes comprising reverse circulation (RC) and diamond drilling defined a sizeable resource of 35 Mt of 0.15% U3O8, for 52,500 t of U3O8. Permission to mine was refused under the three mines policy which limited uranium exports during the 1980s.

column6: On 21 November 2013 IGO withdrew from the agreement. 4.0 GEOLOGY AND MINERALISATION 4.1 Regional Geology The Eastern Goldfield Province occupies the eastern third of the Yilgarn Craton. It is a typical Archaean granite-greenstone terrain characterised by large areas of granitoid and broad to narrow, linear and arcuate belts of greenstone. The greenstones are deformed and metamorphosed to greenschist facies or higher and comprise thick mafic to ultramafic volcanic sequences and intrusives, felsic and intermediate volcanic sequences pelitic and psammitic sedimentary sequences and inter-bedded chert, banded iron formation and shale. Granitoid intrusions and regional deformation involving multiple episodes of folding and strike faulting have disrupted the greenstone sequences.

column6: The drill contractor Yearlong Contracting Pty Ltd utilised a tractor-mounted vacuum drilling mechanism to drill 48 mm diameter holes. Holes were drilled on an initial 160 metre by 160 metre spacing. Where drilling intersected significant thicknesses of laterite drilling was infilled to 80 metre spacing. Samples were collected at 0.5 metre intervals in the vacuum flask and the entire sample was submitted to Nagrom in Kelmscott, WA for analysis. Samples are initially assayed using Fourier Transform InfraRed Spectroscopy (FTIR) and those samples showing inferred Available Al2O3 (Av.Al2O3) greater than 25% are further assayed using BOM digest to test for Av.Al2O3 and Reactive SiO2 (Re.SiO2).

column6: At 152 m depth high grade nickel copper sulphide veins were intersected within the basal contact zone of the Mulga Tank dunite, the veins dip steeply to the south and are sub- parallel to the drill-hole, which was not orientated optimally to intersect them. A 50 m thick zone of widespread and locally abundant late fractures and veinlets of chalcopyrite, pyrite and lesser sphalerite has been intersected from about 165 m (Photos 5a and 5b). The top 20 m of this copper-zinc zone comprises a 20 metre wide zone of extensive pyrrhotite that occurs in narrow veins and breccia zones and also as disseminations throughout the sedimentary rocks and basalt (Photo 5c). This is the source of the Upper target at Conductor 2. The zone of copper veining extends for a further 30 m down hole and at 180 m depth is coincident with a second 10 m thick zone of disseminated pyrrhotite within a unit of black shale, which is probably the source of the lower conductor at Conductor 2.

column6: The greenstone belt corresponds to the western most subdivision of the extensive north-northwest trending Norseman-Wiluna Greenstone Belt and covers a total strike extent of approximately 150km. The Ularring Greenstone Belt occupies an extensive sequence of mafic and ultramafic rocks with interbedded volcanogenic sediments and felsic to intermediate volcanics. The geology is structurally complex, consisting of cross cutting and regional shear zones, a regional antiformsynform-antiform sequence (in the southern hinge region at Mt Ida), reverse faulting, extensive deformation, intrusive porphyries and basal ultramafic contacts (see figure 2). The Ida structural corridor, incorporating the Ida Shear Zone, represents an extensive regional lineament that has been recognised over a distance of 500km. The regional structural feature juxtaposes the Kalgoorlie Terrane from the Southern Cross Terrane and incorporates the Ularring Greenstone Belt (figure 3.1.1 1).

column6: Some of the larger D2 folds are thought to have been re-orientated during D3, from an original N-S trend, into trends more closely aligned with the D3 shear zones (e.g. Bungalbin synform and Broadbents antiform; Fig. Metamorphic grade in the supracrustal rocks of the central Southern Cross Domain ranges from very low to low grade in the interior of the larger greenstone belts, through to medium to high grade along the margins of the larger belts, and across the full width of some of the narrower greenstone belts 4 (Ahmat 1986; Chen and Wyche 2001). column6: 5(a) coincides with a magnetic low and is shown on the Winning Pool sheet as a small pluton of porphyritic biotite granodiorite, adamellite and granite. The extensive areas underlain by Mesoproterozoic Bangemall Basin sediments shown in Fig. 7 are almost all composed of monotonous, well-exposed, light-toned, variably bedded dolostone, siltstone, sandstone and conglomerate of the Irregully Fm (map unit Pbw), which is folded into open NNW-SSE and NNE-SSW structures and intruded by extensive dolerite dykes along the same directions. In the north of the study area, a local dark siltstone marker (map unit Pbwd) has been differentiated within the monotonous dolomites. Locally a basal, well-bedded clastic unit (Yilgetharra Fm, map unit Pby) is present, which is composed of sandstone, siltstone, conglomerate, and forms prominent hogbacks and scarps.

column6: The mapping and sampling followed a Heritage Clearance Survey carried out between the 6th and 9th of August on the Tjurabalan Determination Area organised by the Kimberly Land Council. The work consisted of making geological observations amd measurements, taking rock samples for geological study, measuring gamma radiation intensity and estimating Potassium, Uranium and Thorium content using a gamma spectrometer (Exploranium GR 130). Targeted samples were mainly sandstones in order to assess potential fluid circulation, hydrothermal alteration or Uranium anomalies. Within E80/3530 investigations centred on the vicinity of the Buffalo Creek Fault, from the Northern Territory border to the Diva uranium prospect. Samples all come from the Gardiner Sandstone Formation and were taken from three transverse profiles crossing the fault; (1) samples GT0087 to GT0091, (2) GT0092 to GT0095 and (3) samples GT0096 to GT0098.

column6: The objectives of the desktop study were to identify records or potential occurrence of conservation significant flora including: Declared Rare flora (DRF) and Priority flora (PF) species; and Threatened Ecological Communities (TECs) or Priority Ecological Communities (PEC) in the Project area. Results of these searches produced one DRF, seven PF (all of which were perennial shrubs) and one PEC; Banded Ironstone Hills with Dryandra arborea (currently known as Banksia arborea). The targeted flora survey was carried out from 10 to 11 January 2012, following substantial springtime rains. Eighteen proposed drill pad sites were surveyed and marked out. The objectives of the targeted flora survey were to: identify conservation significant flora in the vicinity of proposed drill sites to enable mitigation of impacts by exploration; provide population estimates of conservation significant flora; and map the distribution of conservation significant flora in the Project area.

column6: 5 PREVIOUS COMPETITOR WORK Previous work in the general Fraser Range area and within E63/1281 is summarised in Waterfield (2011) and Ryan (2012). Exploration in the Fraser Range commenced in the late 1960s to early 1970's when Newmont and partners targeted Ni-Cu mineralisation based on similarities to the Thompson Nickel Belt of Manitoba, Canada. Sub-economic disseminated Ni-Cu mineralisation was drilled at several prospects to the west of Plato in ultramafic and noritic intrusives, with best results of 0.81% Ni and 0.31% Cu over a 0.2m interval. Values up to 1.2% Ni were returned from the base of a laterite profile underlain by weakly sulphidic amphibolite. During the 1980's Growth Resources and subsequently in the 1990s Oroya Mining held tenements over the Plato prospect area, but no exploration was undertaken.
