column6: Regionally, the geological sequence on the Kingfisher Islands is part of the Yampi Formation. Location 1 was a site from the 2013 exploration programme that was revisited (Figure 4). The sandstones here appear darker than the rest of the island, and have extensive vitreous goethite infill along joint planes (<5cm thick) and minor alteration of the wall-rock. The host rocks are hard, mediumgrained, porous arkose-feldspathic sandstones that have been partially recrystallised. column6: These jasperoid bodies display transitional or diffuse boundaries with the host jaspilite units, and may be up to 50 m long and extend across strike for up to 20 m. Chalcedony takes the form of diffuse replacement zones and more distinct dilational veins. The veins appear to have formed during a progressive hydrothermal event, during which early hematitic chalcedonic replacement zones or veins are cross-cut or replaced by later barren white chalcedony. In genetic terms, these jasperoid bodies may represent the product of deposition, in distal setting, of silica leached from dolomitic BIF in the core of a nearby hypogene iron-ore mineralisation system. column6: Limited outcrop and drill data suggest the hanging wall sequence of the host komatiite is similar to that of the footwall. Both the Black Swan Komatiite and footwall sequence are intruded by felsic rocks similar in composition to the footwall felsic volcanics. The Silver Swan deposit comprises a discrete, steeply plunging, high grade massive sulphide shoot composed of pyrrhotite, pentlandite, pyrite chalcopyrite, magnetite- ferro chromite mineralisation occurring on the footwall of the Black Swan Komatiite. It extends from a depth of 190 m, to past 740 m below the surface, with a 550 m down plunge extent, 20 m maximum thickness, strike length of 75 m, and dips at between 45 and 75NE. The shoot comprises upper and lower lens like bodies, laterally separated by a poddy neck zone and has sharp edges.

column6: By comparison the distribution of regional regolith geochemical anomalies within E08/1954 suggests that structures associated with the D2 event also exercised a strong control on localised small scale mineralization within E08/1954. During 2010-2011 field reconnaissance, sampling was conducted at a variety of locations with a preference to D2 orientations (including the known gold occurrence within tenement P08/616, known as Sunken Treasure). Results showed that gold mineralisation is localised in D2 structures and that gold mineralisation does not appear in all D2 structures. Mapping continued during 2011-2012, to assist with the understanding of the structural complexity within E08/1954. Awareness of the implications of scale and type of structural controls and their relationship to mineralisation at Kooline E08/1954 reached a level at which it can assist with effective exploration.

column6: Gold mineralisation is hosted by northwest, north-northwest and east-west trending shear zones and is typically associated with quartz, iron carbonate, iron chlorite and sericite alteration and variable (minor to 5%) pyrite and arsenopyrite mineralisation. The mineralised portions of shear zones tend to occur on the contact or close to a contact between two lithologies. Gold mineralisation can also be associated with quartz-sericite-pyrite-silica altered dacitic to andesitic fragmentals that are coincident with shallow north-plunging quartz boudins or chert boudins within shallow north or moderately east-dipping extensional (lag) shears. The chert boudins represent pipes of silicified pyritic dacite or andesite. 4.2 Mineralisation The dominant structural features within the Rabbit Warren South Project are a NNWtrending foliation with mineral lineations plunging at 40 to the north.

column6: 550 to 520 Am: Development of the Petermann Orogeny, which created the predominant east-west trending shear zones and thick mylonite zones. 65 Ma to present: Weathering since the end of the Mesozoic provided supergene processes favourable for near-surface metal enrichment (eg Ni laterite over Ni rich source rocks). The Musgrave Block features limited geological exposure however cover sequences are generally composed of a combination of thin layers of sand (<20m where longitudinal dunes are present), laterite and calcrete in paleo-drainages or as a broad remnant horizon. Detailed deposit data published on the Nebo and Babel Ni-Cu PGE deposits shows a thin surficial cover and saprolite developed to a depth of 50m. Similarly, historic drilling data at the Tollu Cu prospect indicated a base of oxidation weathering from surface to around 60m.

column6: Both the Prairie Downs and Deadman Hill projects have outcropping iron mineralised Brockman Iron Formation. The regional gravity and magnetic picture indicates a curving north-south to east-west trending signature, which correlates closely with known and interpreted occurrences of the Brockman Formation in the south east Pilbara. A ground gravity survey carried out by Warwick Resources in 2009 and a more detailed survey carried out by Atlas in February 2011 over an extended area confirms the presence of a significant east-west trending gravity high within tenements E52/2283 and E52/2045 in Atlas Irons Watershed project area, which is believed to be buried Brockman Formation. The drilling program was designed to test for the presence of Brockman Formation at depth and, if present, determine the economic potential of this section of the Formation. Wireline logging was completed over the entire hole by ABIM using both magnetic susceptibility and density tools.

column6: Four samples were taken by Halls Creek Minerals in 1994-95, with mineralised rock fragments returning 46.2%Cu, and three soil samples returning between 0.38% and 0.53%Cu. A two metre wildcat auger sample was also taken and assayed 0.38% over the first metre. Follow up work was planned, but the JV switched to Brown Dog NL the following year. Analysis showed most samples to be between 10ppm and 390ppm Cu, with a maximum of 0.215%Cu, and a coherent anomaly over 2km strike length and up to 500m wide was defined (>50ppm Cu). A RAB drilling programme was recommended, however no reports are available to confirm whether this occurred, and given the tenement was surrendered in October 1997 by H Schulda, it seems unlikely the work was performed.

column6: This model is similar to the proposed metamorphic-dehydration model with regards to the importance of thrust faults but invokes a different mechanism to produce an ore-fluid enriched in base-metals. Although the preferred host rock for base-metal mineralisation seems to be dolomite near the contact with the Archaean basement, elsewhere in the Mt Barren Group mineralisation occurs in the Kybulup Schist (Abeysinghe et al 2002). Areas of Kybulup Schist (phyllite in the Ravensthorpe project) overlying a thrust fault should be considered prospective. Most of E74/507 has not been traversed and past geological interpretations have been largely dependent upon the interpretation of aerial photographs. One goal of this programme of work was to verify (ground-truth) the interpreted geology.

column6: The banded iron-formation layers represent periods of diminished or no supply of clastic material into a relatively deep basin. The Mount Belches Formation is intruded by late granitoid intrusions. In the southern and southeastern parts of the Bulong Anticline, the Hickman Find and Duchess of York prospects are located at the faulted contact of the felsic volcanic sequence with the overlying, but younger mafic volcanic and intrusive rock sequence. At the Transfind mining centre the major part of the historical production is from the Transfind workings with gold mineralisation in and along quartz veins within felsic epiclastic metasediments. The Curtin prospect and older workings to the north show gold mineralization within variably porphyritic biotite monzogranite in and along north- to north-northeast-trending pyritic shear zones within quartz veins.

column6: Strong weathering within the project area has resulted in a gold enriched pisolitic surface layer, totally gold depleted saprolite and dispersed gold anomalism at the base of weathering. Initial RAB drilling of prospects in many cases appears too shallow to intersect anomalous or fresh bedrock mineralisation. Primary gold mineralisation is associated with quartz-pyritepyrrhotite stringer veins within anastomosing shears zones in pelitic sediments at Anomaly 1 and altered amphibolitic units within prospects on the Crossroads Trend. The Crossroads Trend extends for over 12 kilometres and follows a sheared granite margin also referred to as the Cockatoo Shear Zone. Along the Crossroads Trend deeper drilling intersected broad, anastomosing shear zones containing low-grade gold mineralisation associated with quartz stringers and pyrite pyrrhotite veins and disseminations.

column6: A series of gold prospects in the McPhee Formation in the Marble Bar greenstone belt includes some that are currently being exploited through alluvial mining. The Little Las Vegas to the east of the Talga River has quite low reported values of anomalous gold. The main group of six prospects, however, are located just west of the Talga River (Van Kranendonk, 2010). Disaggregated pods of massive chromite in serpentinised peridotite in the Doolena Gap greenstone belt originally formed seams and layers in the peridotite host rock. The host rocks represent either intrusive sills or the lower cumulate parts of thick volcanic flows, but the deformation state is typically too high in this region to discriminate between these two options, and mineral compositional work has not been carried out.

column6: Lake Rebecca and Lake Yindana are typical playa lakes, comprising interlayered alluvial silt/clay and evaporitic material. Gypsiferous sand dunes mark the immediate lake margins, with the wider surrounds characterised by alluvial and colluvial sand/silt punctuated by rare granitoid outcrop [Figure 6]. 4.3 Regional Mineralisation The Pinjin Mining Centre is historically the major gold producer in the immediate area, with intermittent production dating back to the early 1900s. Mineralisation is largely constrained to two major sub-parallel trends associated with the Pinjin Fault. The Rowes Find mining operation also produced 21.5kg of gold from 1963-87, with the Enterprise Uranium Ltd Ponton Project E28/2308 Partial Surrender Report 2014 Ponton_E28-2308_2014PS.doc - 7 - mineralisation hosted by a series of east-trending shear zones along the margins of metasedimentary greenstone rafts within granitoid (Smithies, 1994).

column6: The Duck magnetic anomaly was first identified in GSWA 400m line-spaced data flown in 1997. It has an unusual layered character disrupted by numerous irregular magnetically bland zones. A coincident positive gravity anomaly (also in GSWA data) suggests the presence of mafic/ultramafic components. The Burgess Find gold workings occupy a belt a few hundred metres east of the magnetic complex. The disrupted layered character of the magnetic anomaly became more evident after a detailed 50m line-spaced aeromagnetic survey was flown by Enterprise.

column6: The Red Eye project area represents an opportunity for new mineralisation models to be applied to the typically orogenic/shear zone focused exploration targeting within the Kalgoorlie Terrane. Field reconnaissance has led to the identification of USTs and miarolitic cavities at the carapace zone of the Scotia Dome (Figure 3). These are typical indicators of a magmatic-hydrothermal transitional environment which is conducive for hydrostatic failure, brecciation and associated mineralisation (Doran, 2013). A number of deposit types are characteristically hosted within these settings including Porphyry Cu-Mo-Au, Intrusion Related Gold Deposits (IRGD), Granitoid-Hosted Au and Skarn W-Mo-Au The Timbarra gold deposit in New South Wales can be used as an analogue for IRGD-type mineralisation. Timbarra is a Triassic aged, disseminated gold system containing ~400 Koz total resources within several ore bodies hosted within the carapace zone of a monzogranite (Mustard, 2001).

column6: This information will be used to develop new and augment existing conceptual models relating to the major structural controls on mineralisation. This in itself can be used to guide exploration strategies but the primary aim is to test a number of conceptual ideas and scenarios with deformation fluid flow numerical models. The overall vision is to gain a better understanding of the regional to camp-scale structural controls on mineralisation in order to direct exploration. Together these aspects of the project will be used to address Excelsiors exploration issues which are centred on prioritising the close to 90 potential exploration targets over more than 25km strike length of the BTZ. Not all of these targets can be tested and therefore it is the aim of this project to help Excelsior rank them.

The revised exploration strategy is allowing Newcrest to critically reassess regional prospectivity of the Telfer Project.

column6: The tenements were acquired primarily as high potential targets for concealed channel iron deposits (CID) as they are located upstream of the Marillana paleochannel that hosts the Yandicogina CID operations of both BHP Billiton and Rio Tinto. Secondary exploration targets were bedded iron (BID) and detrital iron (DID) deposits hosted or derived from the Brockman Iron Formation. Geological mapping at 1:25,000 scale was carried out over all of the tenements but only identified small outcrops of martite goethite mineralisation in the Joffre Member of the Brockman Iron Formation with even smaller areas of associated detrital mineralisation and canga. These outcropping areas were unable to be drill tested because of the inability to obtain approval from the Banjima traditional owners (as well as the steep terrain). column6: The Laverton Domain sequence may represent autochthonous basement to the younger rock units in the Edjudina and Linden Domains. The Duketon Domain of the Burtville Terrane includes c. 2810Ma intermediate and felsic volcanic rocks and associated maficultramafic rocks in the central and eastern parts of the Duketon Greenstone Belt as well as greenstone assemblages dominated by mafic and ultramafic volcanic and fine-grained sedimentary rocks. A modification of this tectonic subdivision was proposed by Pawley et al (2012) based on remapping, new geophysical, isotopic and geochemical data. These authors subdivided the former Burtville Terrane into the redefined older Burtville Terrane, which includes the former Duketon and Merolia domains, and the newly recognized younger Yarmana Terrane. The Hootanui Fault separates the Kurnalpi and Burtville Terranes, while the Burtville and Yarmarna Terranes are separated by the Yarmana Shear Zone.

Exploration efforts within the region have focussed almost exclusively on shallow (<20m) calcrete-hosted mineralisation. column6: All samples were sent to Genalysis in Perth for analysis. In December 2013 a HeliTEM airborne electromagmetic (AEM) survey over the Belvedere prospect identified two late-time conductors spatially coincident with the high amplitude magnetic anomalies (Figure 5 and 6). Gridded images of late-channel conductance and TMI magnetic data taken from the HeliTEM survey reveal these anomalies are not orientated in regional trend of the East Biranup Zone stratigraphy and are therefore consistent with a mafic-ultramafic intrusion with potential to host massive sulphide mineralisation. A follow-up ground electromagnetic survey was undertaken prior to drilling to better define electromagnetic parameters for optimisation of the drilling orientation. The results of this ground EM survey were lower than anticipated, with a peak result of 115 Sm.

column6: The key is to understand the possible proxies in available datasets that represent these processes. By using a systems approach the explorer is no longer dependent upon the influence of only one particular component of orebody formation, such as structure. In this study Optiro focused on the mineral system model outlined by the Predictive Mineral Discovery * Cooperative Research Centre, which seeks to answer five questions as to why an orebody is where it is. These questions relate to the geodynamics, architecture and structure, fluid reservoirs (source), the fluid flow drivers and pathways and depositional mechanisms (Figure 5.1). This method of exploration has been successfully applied in the Yilgarn and other gold orogenic belts and has led to the prediction and discovery of multiple million-ounce deposits.

column6: Warrawoona Stage (3525 3420 Ma) is the oldest event and involved the eruption of the Warrawoona Group volcanic rocks and emplacement of granitic rocks of the Callina and Tambina Supersuites. Two periods of deformation and contact-style metamorphism also occurred during this stage. The second formational event, Kelly Stage (3350 3290 Ma), involved the deposition of Kelly Group volcanic rocks, emplacement of the Emu Pool Supersuite and an interval of substantial deformation and metamorphism. The final Sulpur Springs Stage (3275 -3225 Ma) encompassed deposition of the Sulphur Springs Group, emplacement of the Cleland Supersuite and another major period of deformation and metamorphism. The GSWA interpreted bedrock geology of the project area is shown on Figure 2.

column6: The L48 anomaly is in all likelihood a surface-only uranium anomaly caused by leaching and weathering of the overlying siltstone with its slightly elevated uranium. Alternatively, the anomaly could represent the oxidised fluid pathway through a porous sandstone bed. If this were the case, and if reducing conditions exist at depth in the sandstone then potential for roll-front type mineralisation exists down dip. This magnetic anomaly is beneath an alluvial boulder field in a major drainage system. While it is possible the magnetic response was caused by the abundant dolerite boulders present, it seems more likely the anomaly has some deeper unexposed source.

column6: Historically there has been limited exploration within the Millrose Project with only minor reference to the various greenstone lithologies present within the project area. The Companys WAMEX data review reveals a number of shallow RAB and auger holes completed in the early 1990s with a peak value of 225ppb Au indicated by Placer Exploration Limited. Follow-up auger drilling by Placer on 200m x 100m spacing failed to support original findings. Work completed by Great Western Exploration from 2011 to 2013 included desktop studies, data compilation, field reconnaissance geological mapping and soil sampling at 2km spacing, and airborne magnetic and radiometric surveying at 100m line spacing. The geochemical surveying performed during 2013 focused primarily along the northern Monzonite contact zone (outlined using magnetics).

column6: The majority of these rock chips was collected around the historic workings at Maitland South and Lenanphyl. Maximum gold grades returned included the following: Lenanphyl: 2.31 g/t Au Maitland South: 2.55 g/t Au, 1 ppm Ag (average grade of 0.95 g/t Au across 9 samples taken from 160 metre strike along the shear zone) West Mt Maitland Cu Anomaly: 1.19 g/t Au, 8.82% Cu, 82 ppm Pb, 6755 ppm Zn Rock chipping continued in 2014, when 24 samples were collected over possible sources for the gold anomalism detected in infill soil sampling over Mudawerrie Well. Maximum values of 0.645 g/t Au were returned in assay results and in general gold results were disappointingly low relative to the northern half of the Muddawerrie BIF. However, it must be noted that most soil anomalies were located to the west of the main ridge and visible nuggety gold has been noted in cherts beneath shallow colluvium.

column6: A major watershed divide within the Carey Palaeovalley separates the Yeelirrie and adjacent Abercromby Lake Way drainage sub-catchments (Figure 4). A major surface water divide separates the Carey from the Raeside Palaeodrainages to the south. The Yeelirrie Palaeovalley is a broad flat basin that extends east from the major continental divide (approximately 60 kilometres west of the Yeelirrie Uranium deposit) and terminates east of Lake Miranda (see Figure 2). The total catchment area covers an area of approximately 8,500 km2, with the area of the present catchment basin upstream of the Yeelirrie uranium deposit covering approximately 3,000 km2. The valley has a south easterly orientation and a length in excess of 170 kilometres.

column6: There is a gross relationship between the location of Archaean lode-gold deposits and crustal-scale deformation zones in the Yilgarn Craton. A similar relationship has been noted in Canada (Robert 1990). Despite this large-scale relationship, gold mineralisation is rarely hosted in first-order structures, and deposits are instead hosted in second and lower order structures, which may or may not show a direct geometric relationship to the large-scale deformation zones (e.g. Eisenlohr et al. The general lack of mineralisation within the major structures suggest that, if the structures are interlinked and the major structures acted as fluid conduits, they did so at deeper crustal levels than those currently exposed in most gold deposits.

column6: The dykes range in thickness, being between 10 to 100 metres. h. FORTESCUE GROUP The weakly metamorphosed volcanic and sedimentary Neo Archean Fortescue Group is the most widespread supracrustal succession in the region. The succession is confined to the east along the western margin of the extensive northeast Pilbara Sub Basin of the Fortescue Basin. The Fortescue Group uncomformably overlies, or is faulted against, the Mount Edgar Granitic Complex, the Marble Bar, Kelly and McPhee Greenstone belts, and the Gorge Creek Group. The Black Range Dolerite Suite is considered to be part of the feeder dyke system for the Mount Roe Basalt.

column6: The review included an audit of the historic data to determine if all previous work has been incorporated into the current data set. This work is ongoing at the time of reporting. Gold was discovered in Coolgardie by Bayley and Ford in 1892 at what was to become the Bayleys Reward deposit on Fly Flat. This sparked a massive gold rush to the area with the town growing rapidly to accommodate a population of 15,000 people. Much of the early gold was alluvial but the incoming prospectors peppered the area with shafts and shallow workings, and although the vast majority of these came to nothing, a number of primary deposits were discovered and several companies were floated to exploit these.

column6: Dyke margins and D2 shears acted as pre-existing weaknesses, with those of a northeast or northwest trend being preferentially re-activated as either dextral or sinistral shears, respectively, as a result of increasing fluid pressure in a strike-slip regime thus producing shear vein lodes. North-northwest to north trending, steep-dipping diorite dykes and D2 faults formed extension vein lodes as a result of increasing fluid pressure and north/northwest-south/southeast extension, resulting in vertical release of fluids and pressure in the process. Current Exploration Summary Page 33 of 39 Printed: 1/2/2016 Drilling at Malaga consisted of 67 slimline RC holes (3,433m) testing a potentially mineralised NW-SE trending mineralised corridor. Previous work in this area has returned isolated high-grade assay results, although these appear to have been poorly followed up on. Furthermore, all of the drilling intersected ultramafic schists in areas previously interpreted to be underlain by basalt, which may increase the prospectivity of this area.

column6: Lithologies are predominantly metamorphosed to amphibolite facies; however there are remnants of unaltered basalts and sediments in the more central portions of the belt. The mafic volcanics are thought to belong to the Warrawoona Group; the clastic sediments are tentatively assigned to the Corboy Formation and the BIFs and cherts to the Cleaverville Formation. The prospective Cleaverville Formation usually occurs near the centre, sitting on older Warrawoona Group volcano-sediments, which occupy the flanks near the granites. Cleaverville Formation sediments occupy a complex central position between the outer amphibolites and the three inner bodies of maficultramafics and sit unconformably on the Warrawoona Group over most of the area, but are interpreted to overlie Corboy Formation sediments in the south. They are dominated by fine-grained sediments, which include siltstones, interbedded siltstones and cherts, BIFs and bedded cherts.

column6: To the south of the Sholl Shear Zone, gold deposits are confined to fault and shear zones within the Whundo Group. Most of these faults and shears appear to be related to the Sholl Shear. column6: 2.0 INTRODUCTION E80/3938 forms part of the Halls Creek Joint Venture which is located within the East Kimberley region, approximately 365km south west of Kununurra. The project hosts the Mount Angelo North Cu-Zn-Ag volcanogenic massive sulphide deposit and a large low grade copper deposit associated with a high level felsic intrusive (a granophyric microgranite) at the Mount Angelo Porphyry prospect. The Joint Venture has access to a large tenement package which is particularly prospective for the discovery of further similar copper and copper-zinc mineralisation. Access to the project area is via the Great Northern Highway and station tracks. 3.0 TENURE The Halls Creek Joint Venture is comprised of five granted exploration licenses, and one mining lease.

column6: Outcrop, although limited, within the area mapped is dominated by mafic (basalt and dolerite) and ultramafic sequences with intercalated sediments. A series of regional compilation and assessment of previous exploration including drilling, soil sampling, and geochemical data was undertaken during the reporting period to identify anomalous zones that could be targeted. Targeting criteria was applied across all tenements and included the following aspects: large and secondary structures major NW structures providing fluid access, and minor NE structures constraining mineralisation, both associated with Au and Cu anomalism redox boundary observable from ME/ASD data lithology identification (via ME analysis) geophysical features alteration assemblages observed from ASD data magnetic highs and lows associated with Au anomalism/alteration Au anomalism This resulted in identification of 18 potential targets across the region which were subsequently ranked, with prioritized targets assigned a possible model. Field trips were conducted on each target area to check access, historical drilling, and any interesting geological features observable. During 2008, Jigsaw Geoscience was commissioned by Integra Mining to undertake a regional bedrock geological interpretation (Figure 7).

column6: The distribution of the mineralisation at Dawson Hinkler and the identification of separate mineralised pods suggest that the presence of subsurface barriers that restrict ground water flow play a major role in the uranium distribution in the calcrete. Subtle linear trends in both airborne radiometric and magnetic data coinciding with rapid changes in the depth of the recent alluvium/colluvium cover which hosts the calcrete and the thickness of the latter support a partial structural control of the mineralised pods. The Lake Way uranium deposit is confined to a broad palaeo-channel delta where Uramurdah Creek empties into the northern shoreline of the Lake Way hyper-saline playa lake. Uranium mineralisation is located in surficial deposits comprising calcrete, dolomite, sand, silt and clays which overlie the basement geology to a depth of up to 40m. The uranium mineralisation is developed as a series of amorphous and discontinuous lobes.

column6: Gold mineralisation occurs in quartz filled shears and fractures at the historic gold prospects Chapmans Reward (Jutson Rocks), Langs Find and Rutters Soak. The only recorded production is 26.65 ounces from 15 tonnes at Chapmans Reward in 1925. 4.0 PREVIOUS EXPLORATION In 1923 a State Prospecting Party discovered visible gold in prospecting pits at Chapmans Reward with selected sampling from pit walls and dump material assaying up to 201 g/t. column6: We are confident the region will yield further discoveries, enabling us to build on our existing high grade Eneabba Resource base of 4.5Mt of contained valuable heavy mineral. The current high grade resource at Sheffields Eneabba Project comprises 172Mt at 3.0% HM (Table 1 and Appendix 1) in three dunal deposits (Yandanooka, Durack and Drummond Crossing), one strandline deposit (West Mine North) and one combined dunal and strandline deposit (Ellengail). Of these, the Drummond Crossing resource, with its combined zircon and rutile assemblage of 24%, is most similar in setting and style to the dunal prospects outlined by recent drilling. The four recent discoveries have combined zircon and rutile assemblages of between 23% and 36%. The dunal deposits of the Eneabba region are typically rich in zircon and rutile and the ilmenite is generally high grade (>60% TiO2) and suitable as feedstock for the chloride pigment process or as synthetic rutile feedstock.

column6: Quartz within these shears occurs as veins, veinlets or boudins. Numerous pits and Bibliographic Data Sheet Page 3 of 15 Printed: 23/8/2016 shafts occur within the tenement group. Most prospects in the Malcolm project area appear to have exploited high grade (>20g/t gold) portions of quartz veins and did not pursue other styles of gold mineralisation. Gold mineralisation is hosted by northwest, north-northwest and east-west trending shear zones and is typically associated with quartz, iron carbonate, iron chlorite and sericite alteration and variable (minor to 5%) pyrite and arsenopyrite mineralisation. The mineralised portions of shear zones tend to occur on the contact or close to a contact between two lithologies.

column6: As a result of this work, several drilling programs were designed in the Greater Gwalia area - primarily to test for extensions to existing mineralisation and/or conceptual targets as indicated by zones of disruption and structural complexity in gravity and magnetic data, as well as to provide additional factual geological information to enhance the predictability of the 3D geological model. Following this work, St Barbara Limited produced a refined working structural model for the Greater Gwalia area based on structural data from drill core and field observations. This study determined that gold mineralisation in the Greater Gwalia area is hosted by early E-W oriented extensional structures which have been deformed, and the gold remobilised, during later compression events. Several drill holes were originally planned for tenement P37/7116, however, these were not drilled due to their proximity to the Goldfields Highway and sensitive heritage sites. Targets were drilled from adjacent tenements instead.

column6: It will be described in some detail below because of the obvious implications for exploration in the district. Abra has been intersected by exploration drilling between 250 and 800 metres depth. The mineralisation is broadly separated into two separate zones, the lead dominated zone underlain by the copper gold domain. The lead domain contains an inferred resource of 50 Mt at 4.0% Pb, 0.2% Zn, and 10 g/t Ag and the inferred resource of the copper gold domain consists of 10Mt at 0.6% Cu, 0.5g/t Au, 0.2 % Pb and 2g/t Ag (Abra ASX release 2006). Abra is characterised by a well-defined zonation as follows: Stratabound hemaetite-barite-jaspilite at the top (50m)-red zone followed by Stratabound magnetite- barite- galena- dolomite/siderite (50m)- black zone, underlain by Stringer copper sulphides and quartz magnetite-barite vein breccia (300m) The stratabound mineralisation is hosted in the upper part of the Gap Well Siltstones, locally characterised by evaporitic pseudomorhps, bio-stromal dolomite, microbial mats and syndiagenetic iron sulphides.

column6: Early stage resource estimates based on wide spaced drilling can be expected to underestimate grade as has been the case for the Bulchina, Lord Henry and Lord Nelson deposits mined by Troy. In Snowdens experience, it is not cost effective at the resource definition stage to drill at a sufficiently close spacing to model the full complexity of vein hosted mineralisation. It is recommended, instead, that a change of support method and/or conditional simulation is used to develop recoverable resource models (less tonnes at higher grade than the bulk block model approach) for future resource estimates, reducing the possibility of overlooking potentially economic resources. column6: The fine-grained sandstone units may display softsediment deformation structures. The coarser upper units feature up to 60 metres of stacked, upward fining cycles. Important diagnostics are considered to be firstly, the predominance of sandstone and the absence of coal seams of significant thickness and areal extent and secondly, a carbonaceous content in the subordinate dark-grey to black siltstone and mudstone units. The basal contact of the cycle may be erosional and associated with intraformational conglomerate characteristics by rip-up clasts of siltstone and infrequent macerated carbonaceous detritus. column6: The Forrestania greenstone belt has undergone several periods of regional exploration for nickel sulphides commencing in the nickel boom of the late 1960s. The most notable periods of activity were undertaken by AMAX between 1969 and 1981 followed by Outokumpu from 1990 to 2000. Exploration discovered five significant Mineral Resources and numerous smaller occurrences of nickel sulphides. To date three of the larger Mineral Resources: Digger Rocks, Cosmic Boy and Flying Fox, have been mined. Nickel exploration in the Forrestania region followed the discovery of a gossanous, ex-nickel sulphide outcrop at the New Morning prospect in 1969 (1.75% nickel and 2500ppm copper; 1.5% nickel and 1500 ppm Cu in follow up RAB).

column6: Primary Cu-Au mineralisation takes the form of chalcopyrite and pyrite in veins. Mineralised veins are concentrated in a 5 to 30 metre wide zone in the hanging wall of the contact between the low- strain, central calc-alkaline unit with strong ferruginous alteration and intermediate schist with moderate ferruginous alteration. Low grade copper mineralisation generally forms a narrower zone or zones within the broader interval of low-grade gold mineralisation. Copper occurs exclusively as chalcopyrite, commonly associated with pyrite and magnetite, in the primary zone. The oxide gold zone is the up-dip continuation of the primary gold zone.

column6: This elongated lense shaped belt is bounded by major north-northwest trending fault/shear zones. The Archaean sequence has been intensely folded. At least five possibly sinistral (anti-clockwise) fault zones of similar but slightly more northwesterly trend are interpreted within the widest part of the belt. These are believed to successively repeat the layered succession. Also two northerly trending sinistral faults obliquely crosscut the belt in this area.

column6: Cainozoic deposits occupy approximately 80% of the area covered by ROE and 100% of the Rowes Find area. Precambrian rocks outcrop over the remaining area, with minor occurrences of Proterozoic age (less than 1%). Archaean rocks of the Rowes Find area can be subdivided into two broad subdivisions: granitoids, and metamorphosed volcano-sedimentary sequences. Four major compressional episodes interspersed with extension have been recognised. D1 thrust stacking followed by intense upright D2 folding, marks the two major folding events 9 E28/1482 Partial Surrender Report (2675-2657 Ma).

column6: GSWA mapped banded iron formations that occur adjacent to the ultramafic units in the northern part of the project. They are associated with a discontinuous high magnetic intensity zone over approximately 10km. The topography and regolith of the project comprises a southern area of shallow alluvial cover in a broad valley, a central dissected upland area of scattered outcrop with shallow soil plus laterite cover and a northern area of sand plain cover. The available regional magnetics is limited to GSWA 1500m line spacing data which only allowed for a broad outline of the main geological units and structure. Recently acquired (Dec 2005) 200m line spaced airborne magnetic data over the project area shows the GSWA mapped ultramafic rocks are much more extensive than previously thought.

column6: The Solid Geology Interpretation, presented in Figure 8, shows well developed layered magnetic units within the greenstone belts. There is insufficient exposure to allow identification of the source of individual layers, but groupings of layers showing slight differences in magnetic character have been defined and linked to the broad lithological packages appearing on the published geological maps. A more precise subdivision of the greenstone packages could be achieved by analysis at more detailed scales (eg 1:10,000) incorporating additional outcrop and drill hole data, if available. The granitoid areas have also been subdivided on the basis of magnetic intensity and texture. There is limited evidence of discrete intrusive contacts and much of the area interpreted as granitoid may represent older basement in which the greenstone sequences have evolved.

column6: The survey area is however located within two Priority 3 Ecological Communities known as Mt Holland and North Ironcap which form part of the Ironcap Hills vegetation complexes. To date none of the Ironcap Hills within the Forrestania region are within Conservation Reserves. There has been broad scale regional surveys of the Forrestania area conducted by Beard (1972) and Newbey & Hnatuick (1988) however detailed data for each Banded Ironstone Formation that forms the Ironcap Hills Vegetation Complex is limited. Beard (1972) defined the vegetation of the greenstone belt stretching from Mt Holland (SW) to Hatter Hill (NE) as the Forrestania system. This system includes granites, quartzites, and banded ironstones that formed prominent rocky ridges.

column6: Mineralisation within overlying sandstone seem to record a decline in U and HREE away from the point of fluid egress with an increase in the proportion of LREE, possibly within the mineral florencite, away from this location. column6: Geology: The tenement occurs within the East Kimberley Halls Creek Mobile Zone (Orogen), with the dominant package being the Whitewater Volcanics. Main rock types include greywacke, siltstone, rhyodacite, tuff, sandstone, siltstone, dolerite and gabbro. Work done: IKONOS and ALOS image interpretation; ASTER purchase and image interpretation; airborne magnetic-radiometric image interpretation; helicopter + 4WD supported field reconnaissance; 30 rock chips; SkyTEM survey (2) and data processing / image generation & interpretation; geological review. column6: Newcrest suggested the turbidite sediments are mostly unaltered but this is questionable given the intensity of the alteration of the neighbouring rock types. It is unclear whether these turbiditic volcaniclastic sediments are similar to the Pig Well Graben conglomerates and sandstone outcropping east of Quondong Well. Types of porphyritic granitoid intruding the Hobbes volcanic sequence include quartz monzonite, monzonite, quartz monzodiorite, rhyodacitic porphyry and highly altered (biotite-epidote-sericite) porphyritic mafic granitoids that are possibly diorites. Some are foliated with an anastomosing schistose 9 fabric defined by sericite alteration. Ferromagnesian phases in the granitoids are altered to actinolite, biotite, epidote and chlorite while feldspars have been altered to sericite and epidote.

column6: Thus a substantial amount of data entry, checking, validation etc was required. The data was entered into Micromine software and standard our validation performed. These are compared with the hard copy originals for editing and further validation. Given that this database contains about 40,500 samples this process took some time, and often highlighted errors in the original paperwork and sometimes the data entry.

column6: Based on previous explorers bedrock maps derived from a combination of geophysics and drill hole data potential gold mineralisation targets exist along the sheared margin of the granite in the eastern parts of the tenement. Targets of particular interest exist where cross cutting structures and dykes intersect this sheared margin. SMLs fieldwork consisted of two MMI soil geochemical sample programs, which succeeded in identifying areas of anomalous gold response. There is a general north-south trend to the anomalism, which may represent structures within the granitoid, that trends on to the Bannockburn Mine Lease. The likely next step in the exploration program would be targeted RC drilling of the strongest MMI gold anomalism.

column6: The distribution, composition, thickness and areal extent of these deposits are the result of interacting depositional and erosional controls related to climate, parent rocks, drainage, topography and vegetation (Hickman, Smurthwaite, Brown and Davy, 1992). 3.2 Historical Exploration The existence of bauxite in the Darling Range was established early last century but exploration by a commercial entity did not commence until the late 1950s. Significant bauxite laterite deposits were discovered in the Darkling Range by Western Mining Corporation in 1957. The deposits were deemed economically viable and WMC established a joint venture called Western Aluminium No Liability (WANL) and a special mining lease covering an area of 12,619km2 of mainly forested Crown land was granted in 1961. Scout drilling and sampling of the duricrust revealed significant deposits in the Jarrahdale-Dwellingup region to the south-east of Perth, which were later exploited after Aluminium Company of America (Alcoa) joined the WANL venture to become Alcoa World Alumina Australia in 1977.

column6: Drill hole spacing is roughly at 2-3 km and not on a grid due to the irregular nature of the salt lake shape. Drill holes spacing will be sufficient for Mineral Resource Estimation. The estimated tonnage represents the in-situ brine with no recovery factor applied. It will not be possible to extract all of the contained brine by pumping or trenching; the amount which can be extracted depends on many factors including the permeability of the sediments, the drainable porosity, and the recharge dynamics of the aquifers. column6: Structures of similar age and orientation to the Lapage Shear are recognized as having major influences during the time of mineralization elsewhere in the region (e.g., Kanowna Belle, Gordon-Sirdar and Mulgarrie). The QE1 Prospect lies with E25/326, however is not part of the Queen Lapage Project. The Rocky Dam base metal prospect lies within E25/273 just to the southwest of E25/326. The majority of the tenements in the Queen Lapage Project are covered by Lake Yindarlgooda, which consists of salt and gypsiferous lake sediments, mud flats, and Kopai sand dunes. East of the lake is dominated by sand dune cover, whereas to the west cover comprises a thin veneer sheet-wash and gravelly sediments on sub-cropping felsic saprolite.

GEOLOGY: The Jeedamya area occurs at the southern extension of the Jeedamya Felsic Volcanic Complex. In the region of the Jeedamya VMS prospect, the volcanic package constitutes a bimodal assemblage of felsic and mafic extrusive and intrusive rocks, with minor intercalated sediment, ash and tuff, which are typically metamorphosed and structurally complex. Thick ridgeforming basalt caps the metavolcanics in the Jeedamya VMS region, with the fault contact between these units being a focus for the sulphide mineralisation. column6: The Tabba Tabba Shear Zone is the major division between the East and West Pilbara craton. The Tabba Tabba Shear Zone is a granodioritic suite that forms the eastern boundary fault of the Mallina Basin. The granite - greenstone sequence is characterised by the presence of a series of large layered mafic - ultramafic intrusions. The Fortescue Group is the lowest group in the Mount Bruce Supergroup of the Precambrian Hamersley Basin and is a generally un-metamorphosed and largely undeformed sequence. No significant mineral occurrences have been recorded with the Fortescue Group rocks.
